00:04:51.440 --> 00:04:56.240
[Amit Varma]: You know, I got to sort of tell my listeners the origin story of the show, basically. And in a

00:04:56.240 --> 00:05:02.240
[Amit Varma]: sense, the origin story has everything to do with you. So a bunch of us friends were at your house

00:05:02.240 --> 00:05:07.600
[Amit Varma]: for lunch or dinner or whatever. And we were just about to go when young Deepak Gopalakrishnan,

00:05:07.600 --> 00:05:11.920
[Amit Varma]: better known as Chuck, dropped in because you and him were recording an episode of something

00:05:11.920 --> 00:05:17.440
[Amit Varma]: called Simplified. And just before you left, you had something called the Narendra Sinhoy selfie

00:05:17.440 --> 00:05:23.120
[Unknown]: stick. And we took a group selfie with that. It was around Diwali because it was a Diwali gift.

00:05:23.120 --> 00:05:28.400
[Amit Varma]: And we took a picture. And then a couple of weeks later, Chuck put up this Facebook post about,

00:05:28.400 --> 00:05:35.040
[Amit Varma]: hey, Simplified, our show is now on the IVM podcast network. And at which point I said,

00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:40.320
[Amit Varma]: hey, congratulations, I'm so happy for you. And at which point the guy who runs the IVM podcast

00:05:40.320 --> 00:05:44.560
[Amit Varma]: network, the good Amit Doshi, kind of popped in in the comments to say that, hey, you know,

00:05:44.560 --> 00:05:48.400
[Amit Varma]: speaking to me said that, you know, I'd asked you a while back if you want to do a podcast,

00:05:48.400 --> 00:05:53.600
[Amit Varma]: and you'd said, no, are you open to it now? So I said, okay, no harm eating. And we kind of met.

00:05:53.600 --> 00:05:57.920
[Amit Varma]: And then the show happened and started as something completely different evolved into this.

00:05:57.920 --> 00:06:02.160
[Amit Varma]: I parted ways with IVM after a while. So for a couple of years, the show's been completely

00:06:02.160 --> 00:06:07.920
[Amit Varma]: independent and just mine. They of course, kickstarted it. So it's interesting how

00:06:08.640 --> 00:06:14.960
[Amit Varma]: serendipitous things randomly happen. Because if we had left your home five minutes earlier,

00:06:14.960 --> 00:06:19.680
[Amit Varma]: yes, or Chuck had come 10 minutes later, the scene and the unseen may not exist.

00:06:20.480 --> 00:06:26.240
[Guest]: It's really incredible. Also, what really held everything together was the

00:06:26.240 --> 00:06:33.920
[Guest]: what you hashtagged as the Narendra Shanoy selfie stick. So I have this

00:06:34.560 --> 00:06:39.920
[Guest]: dear friend who every Diwali sends us gift hamper, which has the most random things. So

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:45.360
[Guest]: usually it has the huge, you know, it has sweets and dry fruits and things like that. And sometimes

00:06:45.360 --> 00:06:50.720
[Guest]: it'll have a couple of packets of Pringles and sometimes it'll have a photo frame, absolutely

00:06:50.720 --> 00:06:57.520
[Guest]: anything. So this time it had for completely mysterious reasons, a selfie stick. And Amit

00:06:57.520 --> 00:07:03.200
[Guest]: was the one who just took off already couldn't get over the fact that there could be a selfie

00:07:03.200 --> 00:07:13.040
[Guest]: stick rubbing shoulders with almonds and croissants and whatever. So all of you kept making fun of me.

00:07:13.040 --> 00:07:19.520
[Guest]: And basically, I think scene unseen is born from that selfie stick is what I like to think of.

00:07:19.520 --> 00:07:25.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. So, you know, I want to actually dwell on that selfie stick a bit and ask for your opinion

00:07:25.040 --> 00:07:28.880
[Amit Varma]: on something because that selfie stick was, of course, part of the origin myth.

00:07:28.880 --> 00:07:34.240
[Amit Varma]: But in a sense, metaphorically, it's a little bit more than that. Because at that point in time,

00:07:34.240 --> 00:07:39.280
[Amit Varma]: I didn't think very highly of selfie sticks, per se, or not so much selfie sticks, which are, I

00:07:39.280 --> 00:07:44.640
[Amit Varma]: mean, after all, just a device. But what people did with them, the constant focus on oneself and,

00:07:44.640 --> 00:07:51.600
[Guest]: you know, that whole Instagrammification always performance. Narcissism. Yeah, you're using all

00:07:51.600 --> 00:07:55.920
[Amit Varma]: these words, but you don't know where I'm going. But where my narrative is going is that what I

00:07:55.920 --> 00:08:01.040
[Amit Varma]: later realized while podcasting, and what I in fact, tell my podcasting students, like I

00:08:01.040 --> 00:08:06.480
[Amit Varma]: taught a course in podcasting for three cohorts. And what I sort of realized was, and the advice

00:08:06.480 --> 00:08:11.520
[Amit Varma]: I would give is if you want to set your podcast apart, it is not about the idea, it is not about

00:08:11.520 --> 00:08:16.480
[Amit Varma]: an issue, it's not about any of them. Like any niche that you think is unexplored is probably

00:08:16.480 --> 00:08:20.800
[Amit Varma]: not unexplored. There are a dozen people out there or there will be, you know, all formats

00:08:20.800 --> 00:08:24.800
[Amit Varma]: are done to that interview podcast, policy podcast, sab ho chuka hai, explainer podcast,

00:08:24.800 --> 00:08:30.720
[Amit Varma]: sab ho chuka hai. What makes a podcast unique really is, is you, is you got to be authentic

00:08:30.720 --> 00:08:35.760
[Amit Varma]: to yourself. So when I listen to interview podcast by people like Russ Roberts and Tyler

00:08:35.760 --> 00:08:39.600
[Amit Varma]: Carvin, and all that is because I'm getting them, nobody else thinks quite like them.

00:08:39.600 --> 00:08:45.280
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, that sort of became what I started aiming for. And that's when the show really found

00:08:45.280 --> 00:08:50.160
[Amit Varma]: its character, which was that I am on an intellectual journey, I'm curious about stuff,

00:08:50.160 --> 00:08:56.240
[Amit Varma]: I'm trying to find out about stuff. So that's what I want to just explore. And that's, again,

00:08:56.240 --> 00:09:00.800
[Amit Varma]: what people like about it. It's what I like about the podcast that I listen to, that is always a

00:09:00.800 --> 00:09:07.040
[Amit Varma]: person. And in a sense is that infusion of the personal into any content that makes it special,

00:09:07.040 --> 00:09:12.800
[Guest]: that makes it kind of stand out. It is impressionism versus realism, right? So

00:09:13.520 --> 00:09:18.960
[Guest]: back in the day, a good painter would be someone who could paint things as good as a photograph.

00:09:18.960 --> 00:09:25.600
[Guest]: And then when the impressionists came, impressionists started painting things in the way

00:09:25.600 --> 00:09:32.400
[Guest]: they thought, in the way it looked to them. And that was a whole different level. And then,

00:09:32.400 --> 00:09:39.200
[Guest]: you know, I believe realism is coming back into art, but impressionism is impressionism.

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:47.040
[Guest]: It's very true. So the individual is what is fascinating. Every individual is different.

00:09:47.600 --> 00:09:53.600
[Guest]: And the perspective that they bring to it is what makes anything interesting.

00:09:54.320 --> 00:09:59.440
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah. So like, I recorded an episode with a guest recently, but which will air after this

00:09:59.440 --> 00:10:02.880
[Amit Varma]: episode. So I won't even say who the guest is. And I've been telling him for a while, you should

00:10:02.880 --> 00:10:06.480
[Amit Varma]: have a podcast of your own. And he was kind of hesitant about it and said, I don't sound good.

00:10:06.480 --> 00:10:11.600
[Amit Varma]: I don't, you know, and I was like, you know, it doesn't matter. This is not radio, you don't need

00:10:11.600 --> 00:10:16.480
[Amit Varma]: to sound good. You just need to sound like yourself. It's, again, that kind of personal

00:10:16.480 --> 00:10:22.000
[Guest]: connect that sort of makes a difference. It's easier said than done. So I remember when I

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:27.680
[Guest]: started my own, you did that too. So when you start off with a medium on your own, you are

00:10:27.680 --> 00:10:34.640
[Guest]: trying to optimize for someone else, and then it never works out. And then you get your,

00:10:35.760 --> 00:10:40.720
[Guest]: you know, you get to act together. And then you realize that you have to be who you are.

00:10:40.720 --> 00:10:46.080
[Guest]: And that's the easiest way to do it. And it's also the most interesting. People listen to you

00:10:46.080 --> 00:10:52.560
[Guest]: for that reason. They want to know what you really think and not what someone else or what

00:10:52.560 --> 00:10:57.600
[Amit Varma]: you think someone else wants to know what you think. Yeah. Yeah. So, you know, I also found

00:10:57.600 --> 00:11:03.440
[Amit Varma]: during doing my podcast that just the long form nature of it kind of changed the way I was in my

00:11:03.440 --> 00:11:07.280
[Amit Varma]: everyday life as well. I've written an essay on this also for my newsletter where, you know,

00:11:07.280 --> 00:11:11.600
[Amit Varma]: if you're doing a four hour podcast, your approach to it has to be very different from if you're

00:11:11.600 --> 00:11:16.000
[Amit Varma]: doing a 20 minute podcast, you know, for a 20 minute podcast, sometimes you don't even, you

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:20.000
[Amit Varma]: know, people won't even read the book, or they'll just read that one book and nothing else by the

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:24.400
[Amit Varma]: author. And then, you know, you can ask surface questions, and you can have a standard stock of

00:11:24.400 --> 00:11:29.760
[Amit Varma]: questions and get away with it. But for a longer podcast, you really need to listen and be open to

00:11:29.760 --> 00:11:34.000
[Amit Varma]: where the other person is going and what directions are going in, never interrupt all of that.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:37.840
[Amit Varma]: And that listening is important. We don't do enough of it in the real world. And that kind

00:11:37.840 --> 00:11:43.440
[Amit Varma]: of changes you. So now my question is, since on Simplified, what you guys kind of do is you're

00:11:43.440 --> 00:11:50.160
[Amit Varma]: always explaining stuff. Has it changed the way you therefore consume content, think about things?

00:11:50.800 --> 00:11:54.480
[Amit Varma]: Like, are you a different person today than you would be when you started Simplified? Because

00:11:54.480 --> 00:12:01.280
[Amit Varma]: what you do with Simplified is you'll take things, phenomenon, events, and kind of break them down

00:12:01.280 --> 00:12:05.280
[Amit Varma]: and go deeper. So does that change the way that you approach everything in your everyday life,

00:12:05.280 --> 00:12:09.760
[Amit Varma]: where you'll suddenly see something and say, huh, this could be a subject, or, you know,

00:12:09.760 --> 00:12:14.480
[Guest]: I should look this up and research this. So that to some extent, it does, because you're

00:12:14.480 --> 00:12:20.720
[Guest]: constantly on the lookout for something to simplify. But what we've been doing, we've been

00:12:20.720 --> 00:12:26.560
[Guest]: not been doing a very intense job of actually simplifying things in the sense that when we

00:12:26.560 --> 00:12:34.560
[Guest]: explain something, it's not exhaustive. It's not insightful, not necessarily insightful. It just

00:12:34.560 --> 00:12:44.320
[Guest]: covers, it just gives people and listeners an idea of what it might be. What we do, what is unique to

00:12:44.320 --> 00:12:50.880
[Guest]: what we do is we just pepper it with our silly jokes, our observations, and the constant going

00:12:50.880 --> 00:12:57.520
[Guest]: off on tangents and recalling anecdotes and things like that, which might happen in a room full of

00:12:57.520 --> 00:13:03.440
[Guest]: friends. That was not intentional. So when we started doing Simplified, we used to research

00:13:03.440 --> 00:13:09.680
[Guest]: and script out and do everything and it ended up sounding very wooden. And we didn't like

00:13:10.240 --> 00:13:18.240
[Guest]: it very much ourselves. And so we decided to have freewheeling things. And it was very clear

00:13:18.240 --> 00:13:25.360
[Guest]: to the listener that we knew as little of it as they themselves did, which which sort of added to

00:13:25.360 --> 00:13:34.880
[Guest]: the allure. One thing that Simplified, there are two basic things that I really got out of

00:13:34.880 --> 00:13:42.800
[Guest]: podcasting. One is you tended to read more and learn more about things and because you wanted to

00:13:42.800 --> 00:13:51.120
[Guest]: explain it to someone, you'd be a little more sort of attentive. And the second is my co-host,

00:13:51.120 --> 00:13:59.840
[Guest]: now it is a Chuck and Sriketh and Tony, we would have these very nice bonding times together,

00:13:59.840 --> 00:14:07.280
[Guest]: because you'd be you know, each one riffs off in their own way. Chuck is like terrific at those

00:14:07.280 --> 00:14:14.720
[Guest]: horrible groaner puns that he comes up with and Tony is wordplay based and Sriketh has, you know,

00:14:14.720 --> 00:14:21.120
[Guest]: a wealth of anecdotes. So it is that the act of putting that podcast together, you know, it's

00:14:21.120 --> 00:14:26.960
[Guest]: really great fun. That's basically what I get out of the podcast. We don't make any money out of it.

00:14:27.520 --> 00:14:34.160
[Guest]: And so that never was the intention. But it's just fun putting it together and,

00:14:34.160 --> 00:14:37.680
[Guest]: and you know, sort of being together for at least a couple of times a month.

00:14:38.400 --> 00:14:42.320
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, a couple of things that you said kind of struck me in the sense one thing you said was

00:14:42.320 --> 00:14:47.040
[Amit Varma]: that if you read something with the intention of teaching it, of talking about it, you just read

00:14:47.040 --> 00:14:52.800
[Amit Varma]: much better, you learn much better. And I think in my episode with Krish Ashok, Ashok rather spoke

00:14:52.800 --> 00:14:58.080
[Amit Varma]: about this, as well himself, where, you know, there's a pyramid of learning and the most,

00:14:58.080 --> 00:15:02.560
[Amit Varma]: the most inefficient way of learning something is perhaps to read it. And then a slightly better way

00:15:02.560 --> 00:15:06.480
[Amit Varma]: if somebody reads it out to you or whatever, and an even better ways to write about it,

00:15:06.480 --> 00:15:12.560
[Amit Varma]: and then finally to teach it. And I just feel that that's, you know, so if you if you approach

00:15:12.560 --> 00:15:17.840
[Amit Varma]: learning about anything, with the intention or the illusion of an intention that I'm going to

00:15:17.840 --> 00:15:21.520
[Amit Varma]: teach this at some point, then you'll find yourself reading that much more carefully,

00:15:21.520 --> 00:15:25.440
[Amit Varma]: because you have to break everything down to first principles and basics or, you know,

00:15:25.440 --> 00:15:31.200
[Amit Varma]: getting meta as in fact, is the name of Chakshu, which kind of really works. The other thing that

00:15:31.200 --> 00:15:36.960
[Amit Varma]: sort of strikes me is when you said that very often we know as little as the listener does,

00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:40.320
[Amit Varma]: which is beautiful, and which is another, you know, piece of advice I'd give to creators,

00:15:40.320 --> 00:15:44.720
[Amit Varma]: not just podcasters, that one question I got while teaching the course sometimes was that,

00:15:45.680 --> 00:15:50.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, why should people listen to me? I am not an expert in anything. I am not like Ram

00:15:50.160 --> 00:15:54.080
[Amit Varma]: Guha or Arshad Bhogle or whatever, why should people listen to me? I mean, direct quotes,

00:15:54.800 --> 00:15:59.520
[Amit Varma]: people are talking about themselves, you know, and my whole point is that you don't need to be

00:15:59.520 --> 00:16:05.360
[Amit Varma]: an expert to be a compelling creator, you just need to be on a journey that many other people

00:16:05.360 --> 00:16:10.080
[Amit Varma]: are also on, you know, it could be a physical journey, it could be a journey of a certain kind

00:16:10.080 --> 00:16:16.320
[Amit Varma]: of curiosity, you could be at exactly the same intellectual or emotional state as your listeners.

00:16:16.320 --> 00:16:22.480
[Amit Varma]: And that's the charm. That's where the empathy comes in. That's where the relatableness comes in.

00:16:22.480 --> 00:16:28.400
[Amit Varma]: And after that, all you got to do is be authentic to yourself. But leaving aside these musings,

00:16:28.400 --> 00:16:32.880
[Amit Varma]: let's go back to the beginning, because you've heard my show enough to know that I want all

00:16:32.880 --> 00:16:38.080
[Amit Varma]: details from childhood. I mean, not all details, but tell me a bit about your childhood. Where

00:16:38.080 --> 00:16:44.400
[Guest]: were you born? You know, where did you grow up? I was born in Mangalore, which is where my

00:16:45.120 --> 00:16:52.320
[Guest]: mother is from. My parents are from there. And my grandparents live there. So this is a tradition.

00:16:52.320 --> 00:16:58.640
[Guest]: I was the first born. So the first born goes and, you know, is delivered in the mother's house.

00:16:59.520 --> 00:17:07.360
[Guest]: But we were back in Bombay, almost soon thereafter. And this was because my father was the

00:17:07.360 --> 00:17:13.280
[Guest]: oldest in the family. And his mother had passed away at a very young age, had just passed away.

00:17:13.280 --> 00:17:18.640
[Guest]: And they wanted, so my father had a younger brother and two, three younger sisters. And

00:17:18.640 --> 00:17:26.080
[Guest]: they wanted a woman of the house. So my father got married early. So we lived in a small house

00:17:26.080 --> 00:17:32.960
[Guest]: in Vadala. My grandfather had a restaurant. And he was an interesting guy. He had a successful

00:17:32.960 --> 00:17:38.560
[Guest]: restaurant and he made a lot of money, relatively speaking. They were poor. And then because of the

00:17:38.560 --> 00:17:44.720
[Guest]: restaurant, you know, the entire family and extended family, you know, got settled. My dad

00:17:44.720 --> 00:17:51.920
[Guest]: dad was randomly chosen to become a doctor. It is typical for that time. He was rather looking

00:17:51.920 --> 00:17:57.200
[Guest]: forward to going and sitting in the restaurant at the gala, you know, counting all the cash.

00:17:57.200 --> 00:18:05.280
[Guest]: And around this time, T.M.A. Pai was opening his Kasturba Medical College. And he was looking for

00:18:06.160 --> 00:18:11.760
[Guest]: students. So he knew my grandfather and he said, why don't you send your son? And my grandfather

00:18:11.760 --> 00:18:15.920
[Guest]: says, yeah, sounds like a good idea. And the next thing my father knows, he is studying medicine.

00:18:16.800 --> 00:18:25.280
[Guest]: And so that was how things happened. And when my dad became a doctor, he had to have a practice.

00:18:25.280 --> 00:18:35.360
[Guest]: And Vadala was too small, I mean too big and too expensive a place to start a practice. You know,

00:18:35.360 --> 00:18:41.360
[Guest]: he had to look around. So a very distant suburb at that time was Malad. So he decided to start

00:18:41.360 --> 00:18:46.960
[Guest]: this practice in Malad. And he used to live in Vadala, then practice in Malad and go back. And

00:18:46.960 --> 00:18:52.960
[Guest]: he didn't have a very good practice. And one of his friends, he became a friend because they used

00:18:52.960 --> 00:18:58.240
[Guest]: to take the same train. And there was literally like four trains a day to Malad or something like

00:18:58.240 --> 00:19:06.960
[Guest]: that. And he told him that people want doctors who can make night visits. So if you don't live here,

00:19:06.960 --> 00:19:11.600
[Guest]: you are not going to get many patients. Why don't you move here? So he decided to move.

00:19:12.400 --> 00:19:21.360
[Guest]: And when I was maybe three or four years old, we moved to Malad. And we lived in a very Marathi

00:19:22.560 --> 00:19:29.920
[Guest]: neighborhood. So I am very comfortable with speaking Marathi. Very nice people that we lived

00:19:29.920 --> 00:19:34.560
[Guest]: with. It was a different time. Everybody's doors were always open. So you could just wander in

00:19:34.560 --> 00:19:40.320
[Guest]: and out of everyone's house, that kind of thing. So growing up, I almost entirely grew up in other

00:19:40.320 --> 00:19:48.480
[Guest]: people's houses. There are a lot of really very interesting anecdotes. So the landlady of our

00:19:48.480 --> 00:19:55.920
[Guest]: house, she was PL Deshpande's sister. So they were all a very dramatic family. They were like,

00:19:55.920 --> 00:20:01.600
[Guest]: you know, every Sunday, they used to sort of, you know, harmoniums would come out, they start

00:20:01.600 --> 00:20:09.760
[Guest]: singing, somebody would act something, dance. It was a great time. And around then, so our house,

00:20:09.760 --> 00:20:16.080
[Guest]: it was very small. It was a one-bedroom Holland kitchen. And we had any given time, we had about

00:20:16.080 --> 00:20:22.480
[Guest]: 10 guests. Because anyone who was coming from Mangalore back then, I'm talking about early

00:20:22.480 --> 00:20:28.240
[Guest]: 70s, late 60s, early 70s, would just, you know, they would automatically land up and stay for

00:20:28.240 --> 00:20:35.040
[Guest]: indefinite amounts of time. So my father always wanted a bigger house. So then he, you know,

00:20:35.040 --> 00:20:44.160
[Guest]: he moved to a place which is now like mainstream Malad. But back then, it was a big mangrove swamp

00:20:44.160 --> 00:20:51.040
[Guest]: and our house is right in the middle of the swamp, but it was a big house. And from age 11 or so,

00:20:51.040 --> 00:20:57.120
[Guest]: I grew up in pretty much complete solitude. That's when I sort of acquired the reading

00:20:57.120 --> 00:21:01.520
[Guest]: habit. There was literally nothing else to do. There was no internet, no TV, nothing,

00:21:01.520 --> 00:21:06.880
[Guest]: a bunch of books. And I used to read anything. I mean, I used to read Mills and Boone, Women's,

00:21:06.880 --> 00:21:12.560
[Guest]: I was a man, magazine called Women's Era that my mother used to sell. I used to read that from

00:21:12.560 --> 00:21:19.600
[Guest]: cover to cover. Reader's Digest was one of my favorite. And I mean, it used to be a pretty nice

00:21:19.600 --> 00:21:24.720
[Guest]: little magazine, Reader's Digest, for all the contempt and scorn that it gets now.

00:21:24.720 --> 00:21:31.520
[Guest]: And then when I was maybe 12 or 13, I discovered P.G. Woodhouse. So one of my uncles is a big fan.

00:21:32.080 --> 00:21:40.960
[Guest]: So I just devoured all those books. And it was a lovely time. Yeah, growing up was mostly reading,

00:21:40.960 --> 00:21:48.000
[Guest]: reading, reading and more reading. My father was a doctor and he was a very popular local,

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:55.040
[Guest]: you know, medical practitioner. When I was very young, I remember this was when we used to live

00:21:55.040 --> 00:22:00.960
[Guest]: in that other earlier house. My father would, you know, all his collections, everything would be in

00:22:00.960 --> 00:22:10.080
[Guest]: cash. So he would go in the morning and deposit into the bank. So that one, that bank was Central

00:22:10.080 --> 00:22:16.560
[Guest]: Bank. It was just outside Malar station. And it had a very, you know, I remember the guy's face,

00:22:16.560 --> 00:22:23.600
[Guest]: a very majestic looking Parsi manager. His name was Mr. Gandevi. And I used to love him. I was

00:22:23.600 --> 00:22:29.040
[Guest]: very small. I was a few, maybe seven, eight years old. And he would always give me a, you know,

00:22:29.040 --> 00:22:34.160
[Guest]: toffee or something. And he'd keep addressing me as darling. And he would address everyone as

00:22:34.160 --> 00:22:40.240
[Guest]: darling. He would just say, nice guy. And one day when we go there, it's, my father used to go first

00:22:40.240 --> 00:22:44.480
[Guest]: thing in the morning because all his evening's collections were deposited in the bank. And then

00:22:44.480 --> 00:22:49.280
[Guest]: he would, so he had a scooter. So I would go with him and stand in front of the scooter and go.

00:22:49.280 --> 00:22:54.960
[Guest]: And we go to the branch and Mr. Gandevi is standing outside. A whole bunch of people are

00:22:54.960 --> 00:23:01.600
[Guest]: standing outside. No one's gone into the branch. That is because there is a big turd lying on the,

00:23:02.400 --> 00:23:09.360
[Guest]: on the entrance of the step to the bank. You know, someone's taken a poop. And, you know,

00:23:09.360 --> 00:23:15.200
[Guest]: everyone is very, you know, the staff and everyone, we are there and they're like, you know, let's

00:23:15.200 --> 00:23:21.920
[Guest]: call someone. Let's get out. But Mr. Gandevi has a loud voice and he's, no, he says, this is,

00:23:22.560 --> 00:23:27.600
[Guest]: we have to find out. So he went into Sherlock Holmes mode and he won't know who had done it.

00:23:28.480 --> 00:23:34.800
[Guest]: And everyone was, you know, no one really wanted to find out. Do you really want to find out?

00:23:34.800 --> 00:23:41.520
[Guest]: Do you find a turd on your, this thing? Do you want to put Mr. Gandevi at it? And I remember,

00:23:42.240 --> 00:23:48.080
[Guest]: I remember that ruckus and my father sort of laughing at it, saying that, you know, imagine,

00:23:48.080 --> 00:23:52.960
[Guest]: you find, it'll be some homeless guy or a beggar who's done it. You find him, what are you going

00:23:52.960 --> 00:24:01.200
[Guest]: to do with him? And then later in life, I realized that a lot of us, we do something very similar.

00:24:01.200 --> 00:24:08.320
[Guest]: I've done a lot of you, you end up sort of investigating things, the result of which is

00:24:08.320 --> 00:24:15.440
[Guest]: almost never useful to you at all. So, yeah, I just, for some reason, just remembered Mr. Gandevi

00:24:15.440 --> 00:24:21.840
[Guest]: and my childhood. It's a very vibrant image. But did Mr. Gandevi get to the bottom of the

00:24:21.840 --> 00:24:27.680
[Guest]: mystery turd? Yeah. So he, apparently later, so not when you were there. So my father made the

00:24:27.680 --> 00:24:31.920
[Guest]: deposit like the other gentleman. By deposit, you mean a proper cash deposit?

00:24:31.920 --> 00:24:40.800
[Guest]: A proper cash deposit. And then we learned that there was a homeless guy or some such nearby.

00:24:40.800 --> 00:24:48.160
[Guest]: And Mr. Gandevi, I did give him a year full and sent him along this way. It was, it was dramatic.

00:24:48.160 --> 00:24:52.320
[Guest]: We missed it. Yeah, we should, I would have, it would have, I would have been a different person

00:24:52.320 --> 00:24:58.720
[Guest]: if I had, you know, if I had got the benefit of that, that thing as well.

00:24:58.720 --> 00:25:03.600
[Amit Varma]: This can be such a fascinating start of a humor-cum-crime novel. It's quite lovely. And,

00:25:03.600 --> 00:25:08.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, the thing is people today don't realize how little there was to read in the sense that

00:25:08.160 --> 00:25:14.320
[Amit Varma]: it like whenever I'm with a guest of our age, so to say 60s or 70s born, you know, everything they

00:25:14.320 --> 00:25:19.520
[Amit Varma]: talk about having read is something that I also read because you didn't have that much to read.

00:25:19.520 --> 00:25:23.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. So, you know, in fact, with readers, I just, I remember then they had all these sections,

00:25:23.200 --> 00:25:27.360
[Amit Varma]: humor in uniform was one section. And they had, I think, three sections like that of different

00:25:27.360 --> 00:25:31.920
[Amit Varma]: kinds of jokes. I forget what the others were. Drama in real life was one.

00:25:31.920 --> 00:25:37.120
[Amit Varma]: Haan, there was one, there was something like that. Yeah. And today, of course, we're surrounded by

00:25:37.120 --> 00:25:44.240
[Amit Varma]: humor all over the place. And yet this one memory is somehow so incredibly vivid. Was it a big shock

00:25:44.240 --> 00:25:48.160
[Amit Varma]: to your system that, you know, in your early years, like you mentioned, you were, you know,

00:25:48.160 --> 00:25:52.800
[Amit Varma]: there were people all around you, you know, the Deshpande harmoniums, Deshpande vocals,

00:25:52.800 --> 00:25:56.720
[Amit Varma]: kids playing everywhere. But suddenly you're in the middle of a mangrove swamp and you're

00:25:56.720 --> 00:26:02.400
[Amit Varma]: reading a lot. Was that kind of a difficult adjustment at some point? Yeah. So I was,

00:26:02.960 --> 00:26:08.400
[Guest]: it must have changed me at some level. And I was always the performing kind. So when I was very

00:26:08.400 --> 00:26:16.640
[Guest]: small, thanks to, you know, my Marathi neighbors, I knew a lot of these little, you know, little

00:26:16.640 --> 00:26:22.400
[Guest]: dramatic acts or scenes from plays and I would do them. Do you remember any now? There was one

00:26:22.400 --> 00:26:30.560
[Guest]: little skit that they had, they used to make me do, which was a country bumpkin coming from

00:26:31.280 --> 00:26:37.120
[Guest]: Alibaug to Bombay. So he comes and he like, he lands up in Bombay, then he goes to,

00:26:37.760 --> 00:26:43.840
[Guest]: on a BST bus and a conductor asks him for a ticket. And this guy thinks he's talking about

00:26:43.840 --> 00:26:49.440
[Guest]: a thalipeet and he says, why would I be carrying a thalipeet? I said, not a thalipeet. Thalipeet

00:26:49.440 --> 00:26:54.960
[Guest]: is something that you eat. And ticket or something like that. I used to do that. And there was,

00:26:54.960 --> 00:27:00.240
[Guest]: you know, it was in that accent and things like that. So these people used to make all of us

00:27:00.240 --> 00:27:08.160
[Guest]: children, myself and their children as well, make, perform all these things and sing and dance. And

00:27:08.160 --> 00:27:14.160
[Guest]: when we went to our new house, there was literally no one at all. We had a few neighbors, but their

00:27:14.160 --> 00:27:18.800
[Guest]: children were either much older or much younger than me. So there was no point in sort of playing

00:27:18.800 --> 00:27:28.000
[Guest]: with them. And it must have changed me a lot. I still tend to get carried away when I'm invited to

00:27:28.720 --> 00:27:35.520
[Guest]: perform. So Sheila, my wife, finds that very amusing. So, you know, somebody gives me a little

00:27:35.520 --> 00:27:43.600
[Guest]: handle and I'm barely singing, dancing, acting or doing whatever it is. And often doing a terrible

00:27:43.600 --> 00:27:51.600
[Guest]: job at it, which is basically, I mean, as they say, when we don't dance like no one's watching.

00:27:51.600 --> 00:28:02.320
[Guest]: So I'll be, I'm a bit notorious for that in the family. But when I went to this new house,

00:28:02.320 --> 00:28:08.880
[Guest]: I became a little more introspective and I got, I got, I had a good fortune of having one uncle

00:28:09.440 --> 00:28:16.080
[Guest]: who was very well read and he had a very well stocked library and he would encourage me to read.

00:28:16.640 --> 00:28:24.400
[Guest]: So he would also read a lot of Bertrand Russell. So I liked Bertrand Russell's style of writing,

00:28:24.400 --> 00:28:33.200
[Guest]: very economical, very, you know, very sort of, you know, very to the point. He didn't waste much,

00:28:33.920 --> 00:28:42.080
[Guest]: you know, in terms of words. And a lot of what he wrote was very interesting. So one of the first

00:28:42.080 --> 00:28:48.080
[Guest]: books I read of his was a book called Why I'm Not a Christian. You know, it was sort of basically

00:28:48.080 --> 00:28:54.080
[Guest]: not Christian. It's just why we shouldn't believe in things unless we have a good reason to believe

00:28:54.080 --> 00:29:00.880
[Guest]: in them. And for me, it was, I must have been, I don't know, 12, 13 years old, but it sounded like

00:29:00.880 --> 00:29:07.680
[Guest]: eminently good sense. And then I sort of internalized it a little too strongly. And then

00:29:07.680 --> 00:29:14.800
[Guest]: I would, you know, talk precociously, you know, when elders were present, and then I would be

00:29:14.800 --> 00:29:22.720
[Guest]: rebuked for that as well. And now I see it is oftentimes in bad taste for you to just vigorously

00:29:22.720 --> 00:29:28.560
[Guest]: go at someone without knowing any background, challenging all their beliefs. But of course,

00:29:28.560 --> 00:29:35.440
[Guest]: you were right and they were wrong. But it was fun. It was, when you discover something new,

00:29:36.640 --> 00:29:44.720
[Guest]: radically new way of looking at things, you start thinking about it. And, you know, in life,

00:29:44.720 --> 00:29:51.440
[Guest]: there are not many things that make you think. It's not very often that you really think very

00:29:51.440 --> 00:29:58.080
[Guest]: hard. And when you do, it's oftentimes very rewarding. So I like that one of the times is

00:29:58.080 --> 00:30:07.040
[Guest]: when we were talking and you raised the topic of anti-natalism. So, and then I was thinking about

00:30:07.040 --> 00:30:14.640
[Guest]: that. And it made so much sense to me that I became very eloquent. And I think I've made a

00:30:14.640 --> 00:30:20.320
[Guest]: strong convert my older son, he keeps saying that he doesn't want to have children. And she's like

00:30:20.320 --> 00:30:24.160
[Guest]: completely despairing. What do you mean you're not going to have children? You can't not have

00:30:24.160 --> 00:30:27.760
[Guest]: children. What about your wife? What if she doesn't have children, so on and so forth?

00:30:28.320 --> 00:30:32.960
[Amit Varma]: Oh, my God, Sheila must be so mad at me. Oh, yeah, she's enemy number one.

00:30:34.560 --> 00:30:39.440
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, for my listeners, I once wrote a column about my atheism called a congregation

00:30:39.440 --> 00:30:44.960
[Amit Varma]: of atheists describing a dinner party, where I asked all the people at the table that, you know,

00:30:44.960 --> 00:30:49.280
[Amit Varma]: when did you realize you were an atheist? When did you realize you didn't believe in God? And

00:30:49.280 --> 00:30:53.600
[Amit Varma]: that was actually at your place. And it was one of those really outlier dinner parties in the sense

00:30:53.600 --> 00:30:58.800
[Amit Varma]: that everyone at the table was a non-believer. And I kind of wrote the column on that because,

00:30:58.800 --> 00:31:04.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, I think because there are militant atheists, people often seem to misunderstand

00:31:04.160 --> 00:31:10.960
[Amit Varma]: atheism as similar to a belief system or having an equivalence to a belief system. But as you know,

00:31:10.960 --> 00:31:16.080
[Amit Varma]: this famous letter writer to The Economist once wrote that atheism is no more a belief system

00:31:16.080 --> 00:31:20.800
[Amit Varma]: than not collecting stamps as a hobby. So you can't say my hobby is not collecting stamps. No,

00:31:20.800 --> 00:31:26.640
[Amit Varma]: it's not. So atheism is really the absence of belief rather than a belief that there is no God.

00:31:26.640 --> 00:31:30.880
[Amit Varma]: So an atheist does not believe that there is no God. Instead, an atheist simply does not believe

00:31:30.880 --> 00:31:34.880
[Amit Varma]: in God. Would if you give him the evidence, but you have to give him convincing evidence. So I

00:31:34.880 --> 00:31:39.440
[Amit Varma]: think that's where it comes down from. As for antinatalism, that became controversial because

00:31:39.440 --> 00:31:44.880
[Amit Varma]: I remember it was my conversation with you, which set me off into writing that I wrote a column

00:31:44.880 --> 00:31:49.920
[Amit Varma]: about how it's immoral to have children, which was a headline, partly tongue in cheek. But I thought

00:31:49.920 --> 00:31:56.080
[Amit Varma]: the argument I made there was fairly solid in the sense that, look, all of us know that we shouldn't

00:31:56.080 --> 00:32:01.360
[Amit Varma]: do anything without other people's consent. We shouldn't hurt other people and we shouldn't kill

00:32:01.360 --> 00:32:05.840
[Amit Varma]: other people. I think all three of these are fairly obvious. But when we choose to have children,

00:32:05.840 --> 00:32:10.560
[Amit Varma]: we are basically bringing people into this planet without their consent, which is, of course,

00:32:10.560 --> 00:32:15.600
[Amit Varma]: impossible when they're guaranteed to suffer and they're guaranteed to die. So can that possibly

00:32:15.600 --> 00:32:20.240
[Amit Varma]: be ethical? I mean, they had no choice in the matter. They were kind of just put there.

00:32:20.240 --> 00:32:25.280
[Amit Varma]: And of course, the common arguments. And I don't actually buy the earlier utilitarian argument

00:32:25.280 --> 00:32:29.280
[Amit Varma]: about it, that the world is full of pain and suffering or look at climate change. Why bring

00:32:29.280 --> 00:32:34.000
[Amit Varma]: children into this world? And I don't buy those arguments because my thinking is from a utilitarian.

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:38.160
[Amit Varma]: Utilitarianism breaks down because you can't measure nothing, right? It's just subjective

00:32:38.160 --> 00:32:42.880
[Amit Varma]: how you choose to measure happiness or pain or whatever. But this is a clear cut case that,

00:32:42.880 --> 00:32:47.360
[Amit Varma]: you know, you're making, you know, somebody will suffer and somebody will die. And it's because of

00:32:47.360 --> 00:32:53.040
[Guest]: you. And there was no consent involved. If that person is okay with it, that's fine.

00:32:53.680 --> 00:32:59.520
[Guest]: But if he's not, there's no way you can reverse that. So you did not take his consent. So his or

00:32:59.520 --> 00:33:06.560
[Guest]: her consent. So you have no right to actually, I don't see how that. And so the main argument that

00:33:06.560 --> 00:33:11.600
[Guest]: people say is what will happen to a species? I really don't know. I mean, it's, it's just not

00:33:11.600 --> 00:33:16.480
[Guest]: morally right to have children. That's all. It's a species will probably die. Everyone thinks like

00:33:16.480 --> 00:33:22.480
[Guest]: this. Yes, we won't have any more children. And yes, it'll, it'll be terrible if you are the last

00:33:22.480 --> 00:33:28.480
[Guest]: person, right? So everyone dies, and you are the last person on the last one of the human race.

00:33:28.480 --> 00:33:34.160
[Guest]: And then it's not going to be pleasant. But none of that has any bearing on the main argument with

00:33:34.160 --> 00:33:40.480
[Amit Varma]: that it is not moral to have children. You know, at the species level, I also think of that

00:33:40.480 --> 00:33:44.960
[Amit Varma]: whole artificial intelligence argument where people will get alarmist and say that,

00:33:44.960 --> 00:33:50.480
[Amit Varma]: oh, you know, AI will eventually take over all of us. And there's a whole paperclip maximizer thing.

00:33:50.480 --> 00:33:55.120
[Amit Varma]: And you heard of the paperclip maximizer? No, I haven't. Okay, so the paperclip maximizer is

00:33:55.120 --> 00:33:59.520
[Amit Varma]: basically a thought experiment. And the idea of the thought experiment is that imagine if you

00:33:59.520 --> 00:34:05.440
[Amit Varma]: make a machine, which is programmed to optimize the making of paperclips, right? That's what you

00:34:05.440 --> 00:34:10.320
[Amit Varma]: tell the machine that make as many paperclips as you can. And then the machine goes out of whack.

00:34:10.320 --> 00:34:15.840
[Amit Varma]: And it starts turning everything into paperclips like this table, my laptop, the bookshelf starts

00:34:15.840 --> 00:34:20.080
[Amit Varma]: turning everything till it starts turning human beings into paperclips, because it's just optimized

00:34:20.080 --> 00:34:24.720
[Amit Varma]: for at one thing. And then it goes haywire. And basically the entire universe is just paperclips

00:34:24.720 --> 00:34:29.040
[Amit Varma]: and humans are no more in the picture. That's kind of the thought experiment. I find it kind

00:34:29.040 --> 00:34:33.600
[Amit Varma]: of alarmist and I find so a couple of points I just want to make about the alarmist AI people

00:34:33.600 --> 00:34:39.440
[Amit Varma]: is that when you talk of AI in the future, it's always either it seems magical, or it seems sort

00:34:39.440 --> 00:34:45.600
[Amit Varma]: of dystopian, like in this case. But the point is that when AI actually happens, you immediately

00:34:45.600 --> 00:34:50.320
[Amit Varma]: take it for granted and it makes your life better off. Like the very fact that, you know, we are

00:34:50.320 --> 00:34:56.240
[Amit Varma]: talking right now we are doing a backup recording of a thing as well. Our audio is going into this,

00:34:56.240 --> 00:35:00.320
[Amit Varma]: you know, there's so much AI involved everywhere. You know, you had you taken an Uber to come here,

00:35:00.320 --> 00:35:05.200
[Amit Varma]: that's AI. A friend of ours once said that, you know, the new generation being born today will

00:35:05.200 --> 00:35:10.960
[Amit Varma]: never know what it is to be lost. Yes, because of maps, which is AI. Everything around us is AI,

00:35:10.960 --> 00:35:17.680
[Amit Varma]: we take it completely for granted. In fact, the sponsors of this episode Intel used AI to optimize

00:35:17.680 --> 00:35:23.920
[Amit Varma]: water supply and distribution in Washington DC when they were asked to do so. So and that's an

00:35:23.920 --> 00:35:29.440
[Amit Varma]: unseen effect, right? That you are getting your 24 hours water and it's clean and whatever and it's

00:35:29.440 --> 00:35:33.040
[Amit Varma]: optimized and you're getting it at the lowest price you possibly could and there's AI behind

00:35:33.040 --> 00:35:38.880
[Amit Varma]: that. It's like, you know, the invisible hand behind the invisible hand. But that's a digression.

00:35:38.880 --> 00:35:42.640
[Amit Varma]: What I was kind of getting at is a species point where earlier you said that when people give that

00:35:42.640 --> 00:35:46.560
[Amit Varma]: species argument, if you don't have children, species will die and you're like, why should I

00:35:46.560 --> 00:35:53.280
[Amit Varma]: care about the species? And my point there is that a sufficiently advanced AI at some point in time

00:35:53.280 --> 00:35:59.680
[Amit Varma]: is going to turn around and tell humans that listen, you know, we are smarter than you in

00:35:59.680 --> 00:36:04.000
[Amit Varma]: every possible freaking way. So ethically, why should we be lower than you? Why should we be

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:09.120
[Amit Varma]: your slaves? You know, why should it not be the other way around? And could that happen? And my

00:36:09.120 --> 00:36:14.640
[Amit Varma]: point is, I find delight in that thought that if it happens, so be it. You know, what is so freaking

00:36:14.640 --> 00:36:20.240
[Amit Varma]: sacred about the species? Just about humanity. Yeah. It's that famous Douglas Adams quote

00:36:20.240 --> 00:36:25.360
[Amit Varma]: about the puddle. Do you remember that? No. Yeah. So Douglas Adams once wrote, quote,

00:36:25.360 --> 00:36:29.520
[Amit Varma]: imagine a puddle waking up one morning and thinking, this is an interesting world I find

00:36:29.520 --> 00:36:34.240
[Amit Varma]: myself in, an interesting hole I find myself in. Fits me rather neatly, doesn't it? In fact,

00:36:34.240 --> 00:36:40.080
[Amit Varma]: it fits me staggeringly well. Must have been made to have me in it. Stop quote. Stop quote within

00:36:40.080 --> 00:36:44.960
[Amit Varma]: the quote. Adams continues, this is such a powerful idea that as the sun rises in the sky

00:36:44.960 --> 00:36:49.520
[Amit Varma]: and the air heats up and as gradually the puddle gets smaller and smaller, he's still frantically

00:36:49.520 --> 00:36:53.440
[Amit Varma]: hanging on to the notion that everything's going to be all right, because this world was meant to

00:36:53.440 --> 00:36:58.080
[Amit Varma]: have him in it, was built to have him in it. So the moment he disappears, catches him rather by

00:36:58.080 --> 00:37:02.960
[Amit Varma]: surprise. I think this may be something we need to be on the watch out for. Stop quote. You know,

00:37:02.960 --> 00:37:09.200
[Guest]: you read that book, every time you read it, you find out something new. And this is, you know,

00:37:09.200 --> 00:37:15.040
[Guest]: that anthropocentric view of the world. We are hardwired for that. Everything, all of religion,

00:37:15.040 --> 00:37:24.240
[Guest]: everything is because of that. And it takes a great deal of sort of learning to accept that

00:37:24.240 --> 00:37:33.200
[Guest]: it might not be the case. So that was the basic argument against the antenatal point of view.

00:37:33.200 --> 00:37:38.720
[Guest]: The central argument, which was basically consent, is lost. And you're talking about

00:37:38.720 --> 00:37:43.520
[Guest]: what will happen to the world, what will happen to the human. So that's not the argument at all.

00:37:43.520 --> 00:37:53.760
[Guest]: And it's not even, it's just a moral position. And wow, crazy. It takes a lot for someone like

00:37:53.760 --> 00:37:59.520
[Guest]: Amit Verma and Narendra Sinha to be surprised. But some one such thing just happened for the

00:37:59.520 --> 00:38:06.000
[Guest]: benefit of the listeners is on the 27th floor, we got a person, a visitor outside the window

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:09.920
[Guest]: said hi and went down. Apparently he was cleaning the windows from the outside.

00:38:09.920 --> 00:38:16.320
[Amit Varma]: Today the building society sent us a notice on the special building app in the morning

00:38:16.320 --> 00:38:21.680
[Amit Varma]: that the facade of this side is kind of going to get cleaned. And initially I thought it's

00:38:21.680 --> 00:38:25.440
[Amit Varma]: some kind of narrative management. They're going to clean the facade, but then they're literally

00:38:25.440 --> 00:38:29.360
[Amit Varma]: cleaning the facade. So, you know, this is interesting to me, what you just said about

00:38:29.360 --> 00:38:34.480
[Amit Varma]: reading Bertrand Russell at that age and kind of realizing, you know, that light bulb going off,

00:38:34.480 --> 00:38:38.400
[Amit Varma]: and then it's, you know, going on rather. And once it's on, it's going on forever because

00:38:38.400 --> 00:38:42.720
[Amit Varma]: becoming the person I am in intellectual terms took a lot longer. Like at that age,

00:38:42.720 --> 00:38:46.240
[Amit Varma]: I would probably have believed in a fuzzy way that there is a greater force out there and

00:38:47.280 --> 00:38:52.240
[Amit Varma]: nonsense. And equally, just in terms of ideology, I would have been, I mean, I remember going to

00:38:52.240 --> 00:38:57.440
[Amit Varma]: college with, you know, marks in my handbag, can you imagine? Because it's like fashionable,

00:38:57.440 --> 00:39:01.520
[Amit Varma]: and you feel cool. And it's like, it sounds right, right? It sounds compassionate and

00:39:01.520 --> 00:39:06.320
[Amit Varma]: how the world should be. And then over a period of years, one kind of gradually

00:39:06.320 --> 00:39:12.560
[Amit Varma]: starts thinking more clearly about things. And that's how one arrives at atheism and the respect

00:39:12.560 --> 00:39:17.120
[Amit Varma]: for consent, which is basically what my whole ideological underpinning anyway is.

00:39:17.680 --> 00:39:23.600
[Amit Varma]: So what was it like for you? So, you know, you're an atheist from an early age, so much so that

00:39:23.600 --> 00:39:28.480
[Amit Varma]: you're arguing with elders, though that of course has a pleasure of its own, because you can take

00:39:28.480 --> 00:39:32.800
[Amit Varma]: those judgmental positions I know better than these old fools. But, you know, when you look

00:39:32.800 --> 00:39:37.920
[Amit Varma]: back at yourself as a young person, what were the things about you that you look back on with

00:39:37.920 --> 00:39:43.840
[Amit Varma]: disapproval, which have changed since? And you look back, and you say that, shit, I can't believe

00:39:43.840 --> 00:39:48.960
[Amit Varma]: I was that person or I did those things. Because with me, there's a whole laundry list of almost

00:39:48.960 --> 00:39:54.400
[Guest]: everything. Yeah, same here. I mean, virtually everything. So one of the things I'm sure you'll

00:39:54.400 --> 00:40:04.240
[Guest]: agree as well, is you don't realize things unless something happens, makes you think, you think

00:40:04.240 --> 00:40:10.800
[Guest]: really hard, and you figure it out. And once it's figured out, it stays with you forever. So those

00:40:10.800 --> 00:40:16.880
[Guest]: are the central tenets of whatever. So whenever you talk about doing everything from first principles,

00:40:16.880 --> 00:40:25.520
[Guest]: I can relate to that. And I know that that's very fallible as well, because you cannot figure out

00:40:25.520 --> 00:40:33.520
[Guest]: everything from first principles. Life is too complex for that. Yet, because you've always,

00:40:33.520 --> 00:40:38.640
[Guest]: you know, arrived at the big conclusions of your life, by figuring it out on your own,

00:40:39.280 --> 00:40:44.640
[Guest]: you're sort of addicted to that. And you're not comfortable with sort of entertaining an idea,

00:40:44.640 --> 00:40:51.760
[Guest]: unless you've sort of figured it out, played it over in your head, stretched it out, mangled it,

00:40:51.760 --> 00:40:57.520
[Guest]: done whatever it is, and found it to be acceptable to whatever the rest of your belief system is.

00:40:58.400 --> 00:41:05.360
[Guest]: And many of our mutual friends are like that. We figure that out. Then a lot of that also comes

00:41:05.360 --> 00:41:12.880
[Guest]: into conflict with the world you live in. Now, I don't wear atheism on my sleeve. I go to temple,

00:41:12.880 --> 00:41:21.440
[Guest]: I pray, I genuflect, I do everything. Because I think that respect to the tribe and being kind to

00:41:21.440 --> 00:41:28.240
[Guest]: other people is more important than trying to transform everyone to your belief system. And

00:41:28.240 --> 00:41:33.520
[Guest]: however much I might be convinced that I'm thinking right, you know, it's not universal.

00:41:33.520 --> 00:41:40.320
[Guest]: And there's really no reason for me to believe that I am. My belief system, as you said,

00:41:40.320 --> 00:41:45.520
[Guest]: is sceptic, right? So I do not believe unless there is a good reason to believe in something.

00:41:46.160 --> 00:41:55.040
[Guest]: But if someone else finds believing easier, I'm now of the view that I'm really not a person to

00:41:56.400 --> 00:42:05.760
[Guest]: you know, say no to that. I've been accused by actually my kids of being too like that it's a

00:42:05.760 --> 00:42:11.920
[Guest]: cop out that you know that I'm copying out when if I'm, you know, if I really believe in something,

00:42:11.920 --> 00:42:17.040
[Guest]: I should go out and say it. Why do I? And I'm conflicted about that. I'm not sure why I do

00:42:17.040 --> 00:42:22.800
[Guest]: that. But the older I get, the less willing I am to sort of aggressively go and try and change

00:42:22.800 --> 00:42:29.120
[Guest]: someone else's point of view. I don't know if that's the right thing or not. But a lot of things

00:42:29.120 --> 00:42:37.920
[Guest]: that are happening around me at this time, I do feel that I must go out and I do it on an individual

00:42:37.920 --> 00:42:45.440
[Guest]: level. Recently, there was a classmate who exhibited, you know, very xenophobic views,

00:42:45.440 --> 00:42:52.480
[Guest]: which I didn't agree with. And I called him out on that. And, you know, I was risking our

00:42:52.480 --> 00:43:00.720
[Guest]: friendship, but I couldn't not do it. Yet, I find myself unwilling to do it with the world

00:43:00.720 --> 00:43:07.120
[Guest]: at large. I haven't figured that one out why I do it. In your line of work as well, because you are,

00:43:07.760 --> 00:43:14.960
[Guest]: you know, basically a journalist, even if you're not an active one, when you report on things as

00:43:14.960 --> 00:43:20.560
[Guest]: you see it, regardless of whether those things are palatable to the rest of the world or not.

00:43:20.560 --> 00:43:28.720
[Guest]: And do you find yourself being more temperate in these things? I for one feel you are. Your

00:43:28.720 --> 00:43:34.400
[Guest]: earlier writings were far more direct and far more brutal than they are now. What do you think

00:43:34.400 --> 00:43:41.440
[Guest]: is your journey or your experience in this? Yeah, that's a good question. They're tempered

00:43:41.440 --> 00:43:47.360
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that there is not a conscious self-censorship, but there is also a realization

00:43:47.360 --> 00:43:53.040
[Amit Varma]: in a sense that social media takes up too much of your time and too much of your mind space.

00:43:53.040 --> 00:43:58.560
[Amit Varma]: So do you really want to get into a fight on Twitter, for example, which is going to leave

00:43:58.560 --> 00:44:02.000
[Amit Varma]: you disturbed for two, three days because people are going to come and they're going to abuse you

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:07.520
[Amit Varma]: and it's just going to be nuts? Or do you just want to avoid the fight by not saying whatever

00:44:07.520 --> 00:44:13.040
[Amit Varma]: it is in the moment? So I have found that there, I think at least as far as Twitter is concerned,

00:44:13.040 --> 00:44:19.600
[Amit Varma]: which is an incredibly toxic place, it amplifies toxicity because number one, it's shallow.

00:44:19.600 --> 00:44:24.320
[Amit Varma]: You cannot possibly have a deep conversation there per se. So I just use it for broadcasting

00:44:24.320 --> 00:44:30.640
[Amit Varma]: my links and not for having conversations, but also because you have these ideological groups,

00:44:30.640 --> 00:44:35.520
[Amit Varma]: which are vocal minorities, the bucks and the vokes, the bucks and the vokes, I said the vokes,

00:44:35.520 --> 00:44:42.160
[Amit Varma]: vokes, not vokes, the bucks and the vokes. And within these echo chambers, you have people

00:44:42.160 --> 00:44:47.520
[Amit Varma]: constantly signaling to raise their status. And how do you do this? One, by showing off your own

00:44:47.520 --> 00:44:51.760
[Amit Varma]: virtue, but two, also by attacking others, attacking people from the other side and never

00:44:51.760 --> 00:44:55.840
[Amit Varma]: addressing the argument, but always a person or two, attacking people on your own side who are

00:44:55.840 --> 00:45:00.880
[Amit Varma]: not pure enough for you. And it's just this constant mad war, which is always fought in

00:45:00.880 --> 00:45:05.680
[Amit Varma]: bad faith. You know, you are never addressing the argument. You'll always pick some random word from

00:45:05.680 --> 00:45:10.800
[Amit Varma]: some tweet somebody wrote and kind of attack that. And do you really want to go there? And

00:45:10.800 --> 00:45:17.520
[Amit Varma]: what kind of also happens in many of these groups is that once they decide to get after your

00:45:17.520 --> 00:45:22.320
[Amit Varma]: particular tribe, either of these two tribes, you know, there'll be WhatsApp groups where they'll be

00:45:22.320 --> 00:45:28.320
[Amit Varma]: coordinating and it'll just be your notifications will completely get flooded. And what I realized

00:45:28.320 --> 00:45:34.400
[Amit Varma]: is a very small vocal minority, you know, thanks to how this podcast does and what I get to hear

00:45:34.400 --> 00:45:38.880
[Amit Varma]: from its listeners and all the people who signed up for my writing course and all, I've subsequently

00:45:38.880 --> 00:45:43.760
[Amit Varma]: realized over a period of time that the vast majority of people out there are really sensible.

00:45:43.760 --> 00:45:50.480
[Amit Varma]: They are also sick of these freaking tribes, but these tribes are so incredibly vocal that sometimes

00:45:50.480 --> 00:45:55.760
[Amit Varma]: it is just not worth it. Just let it be. Why do you want to kind of get there? Because and you

00:45:55.760 --> 00:46:00.960
[Amit Varma]: can't say anything nuanced or complicated on Twitter, for example. And now the point is most

00:46:00.960 --> 00:46:06.160
[Amit Varma]: of these people on either of these two tribes I know won't listen to my podcast and they won't

00:46:06.160 --> 00:46:11.280
[Amit Varma]: because perhaps they don't have the attention span or it is their inherent stupidity that drives

00:46:11.280 --> 00:46:15.680
[Amit Varma]: them into those tribes to begin with. I'm just kidding. But they probably haven't got gotten

00:46:15.680 --> 00:46:22.240
[Amit Varma]: this far to listen to me say this. So it doesn't matter. So on my podcast time, like my whole

00:46:22.240 --> 00:46:28.240
[Amit Varma]: thesis for my podcast is that explore everything, question everything. It's a whole skeptic thing.

00:46:28.240 --> 00:46:33.760
[Amit Varma]: Like I have changed my mind on quite a few things in a very public way over a period of time over

00:46:33.760 --> 00:46:38.320
[Amit Varma]: conversations. I think that's a delightful part of it. Everybody is engaging in good faith.

00:46:38.320 --> 00:46:42.160
[Amit Varma]: You know, the one reason like somebody said, why don't you invite a politician from the ruling

00:46:42.160 --> 00:46:46.240
[Amit Varma]: party? And the thing is, because if I could invite a politician from the ruling party,

00:46:46.240 --> 00:46:51.040
[Amit Varma]: but they're going to come with prepared soundbites and a particular line and they won't really open

00:46:51.040 --> 00:46:54.560
[Amit Varma]: up. And the point is, when two people are sitting and they just open up, they trust each other,

00:46:54.560 --> 00:46:58.960
[Amit Varma]: they have a conversation and good faith. It's just much more meaningful for everybody concerned

00:46:58.960 --> 00:47:04.000
[Amit Varma]: rather than it's a polar opposite of what you see in television. But I'm and also, you know,

00:47:04.000 --> 00:47:10.720
[Amit Varma]: while I was editing the magazine Pragati for a couple of years, 2017 to 2019, one of my main

00:47:10.720 --> 00:47:18.720
[Amit Varma]: rule I'd set for myself as an editor was that we will only talk about ideas and policies,

00:47:18.720 --> 00:47:24.720
[Amit Varma]: we will not talk about people or parties, we will not personalize, we'll just talk about ideas.

00:47:24.720 --> 00:47:29.840
[Amit Varma]: So, for example, if I'm going to talk about Savarkar, then I can write about what a horrible

00:47:29.840 --> 00:47:34.640
[Amit Varma]: book Hindutva is and engage with the ideas and just talk about those ideas and diss them.

00:47:34.640 --> 00:47:39.360
[Amit Varma]: This current battle that you see on Twitter, where one side is like Savarkar was the real

00:47:39.360 --> 00:47:45.120
[Amit Varma]: father of the nation and the other side is that he was a, you know, a coward who sided with the

00:47:45.120 --> 00:47:49.760
[Amit Varma]: British and who killed Gandhi or whatever, for which there's no basis really. I mean,

00:47:49.760 --> 00:47:55.120
[Amit Varma]: why are you entering that debate? It doesn't matter. He's dead. Why do we discuss people all

00:47:55.120 --> 00:47:59.520
[Amit Varma]: the time? In fact, every time I get attacked, it's me being discussed. It's not as if I put an idea

00:47:59.520 --> 00:48:04.320
[Amit Varma]: out there and someone is disagreeing with it. Though sometimes ideas like that column I wrote

00:48:04.320 --> 00:48:08.800
[Amit Varma]: about not having kids, like my God, I never thought I'll get trolled and abused for it as

00:48:08.800 --> 00:48:14.080
[Amit Varma]: much as I did. Because parents everywhere felt personally attacked, which wasn't the intention

00:48:14.080 --> 00:48:18.240
[Amit Varma]: at all. It's just an intellectual exercise. Let's think about this. Let's tease this out.

00:48:18.240 --> 00:48:24.080
[Guest]: I was, someone attacked me. He says, you have two sons of your own. How dare you say that? I said,

00:48:25.120 --> 00:48:31.440
[Guest]: I didn't know better at that time. Had I, you know, had I had this insight,

00:48:31.440 --> 00:48:36.320
[Guest]: back then I wouldn't have children. I'm just, you know, and I'm not saying you shouldn't have

00:48:36.320 --> 00:48:41.440
[Guest]: children. I'm just saying that I think it's morally wrong. That's all. I might be wrong.

00:48:41.440 --> 00:48:49.760
[Guest]: But, so this is the thing. So I found that most people are, they feel very uncomfortable

00:48:49.760 --> 00:48:55.120
[Guest]: to have their minds changed about anything. And that's, that's the reason why they go into echo

00:48:55.120 --> 00:49:03.840
[Guest]: chambers. And that's why people like you and me like to engage with people who have views different

00:49:03.840 --> 00:49:10.000
[Guest]: or, you know, at least substantially different from our own. And in some subjects, it is not

00:49:10.000 --> 00:49:15.920
[Guest]: possible for us to be different on everything. And that makes it interesting. And one of two

00:49:15.920 --> 00:49:20.800
[Guest]: things happen, one of three things, actually. One is that it's inconclusive. Second is you

00:49:20.800 --> 00:49:25.760
[Guest]: are convinced that that person is right or that person is convinced that you are right. So for

00:49:25.760 --> 00:49:32.880
[Guest]: these things to happen, both people need to have reasonably open minds. And that's vanishingly

00:49:32.880 --> 00:49:38.800
[Guest]: rare these days, at least on Twitter and all, it's very, very rare. Really no point in debating

00:49:38.800 --> 00:49:45.600
[Guest]: anything. Regardless of how you're saying that Twitter, first of all, it is that 280 characters

00:49:45.600 --> 00:49:50.560
[Guest]: is really not conducive to any kind of argument. But even if it were not, it would still be

00:49:51.280 --> 00:49:55.120
[Guest]: impossible to change many people's minds because they are not willing to have it changed.

00:49:55.120 --> 00:50:02.480
[Guest]: I believe Clubhouse and Twitter space is the vocal part of the audio part of this thing, which

00:50:02.480 --> 00:50:09.600
[Guest]: should be very, very suitable for, you know, opinion changing experiences. I'm told they've

00:50:09.600 --> 00:50:14.960
[Guest]: become huge echo chamber. I was I've stopped listening to them because I didn't like the way

00:50:15.920 --> 00:50:20.240
[Guest]: they were echo chambers. They were just everyone saying the same thing in different thing.

00:50:20.800 --> 00:50:25.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, I think and I mentioned this in previous episodes that what I am firm about and

00:50:25.120 --> 00:50:29.600
[Amit Varma]: dogmatic about is my values. There are things I value individual freedom, rights, whatever,

00:50:29.600 --> 00:50:36.080
[Amit Varma]: skepticism, rationalism, I value those, but I'm completely open on facts. So if I believe X,

00:50:36.080 --> 00:50:41.760
[Amit Varma]: Y, Z to be a fact, and you prove me wrong, I'm fine. I'll instantly, you know, once the evidence

00:50:41.760 --> 00:50:46.560
[Amit Varma]: is solid, even on a question of there being God, but obviously, there isn't so far because people

00:50:46.560 --> 00:50:51.040
[Amit Varma]: have tried for centuries to get proof of that. But what I find disturbing is that people are

00:50:51.040 --> 00:50:56.880
[Amit Varma]: so dogmatic about what they consider the facts of the world, and then you simply cannot question

00:50:56.880 --> 00:51:04.240
[Guest]: them. You know, like, especially historical facts, right? So yeah, so those also are open to

00:51:04.240 --> 00:51:11.520
[Guest]: interpretation open and slight adjustments in historical facts paint entirely different

00:51:11.520 --> 00:51:21.840
[Guest]: pictures of entire cultures. And wisdom lies in realizing that there is really nothing. There's a

00:51:21.840 --> 00:51:30.640
[Guest]: very nice Tom Robbins quote saying that a historian is very much like an animal husbandriest. Have you

00:51:30.640 --> 00:51:40.640
[Guest]: heard this quote? No. So the similarity is that one breeds animals and the other breeds facts,

00:51:40.640 --> 00:51:48.320
[Guest]: and both of them are ankle deep in bullshit. So that's an important thing to know about all

00:51:48.320 --> 00:51:56.160
[Guest]: historical things. It's agenda driven. Whoever wrote the history had some reason to highlight

00:51:56.160 --> 00:52:03.200
[Guest]: some facts and obfuscate others. And it's really extremely juvenile to have any kind of fights

00:52:03.200 --> 00:52:10.480
[Guest]: based on history. And yet almost every fight that I see on social media now is somehow connected to

00:52:11.840 --> 00:52:17.520
[Guest]: history or historical opinion or historical fact or counterfactuals. What would have happened if

00:52:17.520 --> 00:52:23.680
[Guest]: this hadn't happened? It's just really not something. It's an interesting topic to discuss

00:52:23.680 --> 00:52:30.720
[Guest]: over an evening drink, but really nothing that merits serious discussion. And how does it make

00:52:30.720 --> 00:52:36.160
[Amit Varma]: a material difference to anyone whether Aryans invaded or migrated or whether they came spread

00:52:36.160 --> 00:52:40.320
[Amit Varma]: out? How does it make a freaking difference to anyone? I mean, you don't have a job. There's

00:52:40.320 --> 00:52:45.280
[Amit Varma]: no food on your table. You know, people are being lynched outside your doorstep. And you're talking

00:52:45.280 --> 00:52:50.640
[Amit Varma]: about something that happened 1000s of years ago. By the way, you sort of mentioned earlier about

00:52:50.640 --> 00:52:55.280
[Amit Varma]: skepticism about always questioning and avoiding certainties, which is really wise. And that

00:52:55.280 --> 00:52:59.280
[Amit Varma]: reminded me of one of my favorite films of all time. So I got to recommend it. In fact, it's not

00:52:59.280 --> 00:53:03.840
[Amit Varma]: a film. It's a it's a series like when you know, people talk about what's your favorite web series

00:53:03.840 --> 00:53:08.160
[Amit Varma]: of all time and all that. The first one that comes to mind is a wire. But even above that

00:53:08.160 --> 00:53:13.120
[Amit Varma]: is Krzysztof Kieślowski's Dekalog, which is a series he made for Polish television in the early

00:53:13.120 --> 00:53:20.320
[Amit Varma]: 90s. It's a series of 10 one hour films on the 10 commandments. And the first of those is I think

00:53:20.320 --> 00:53:24.720
[Amit Varma]: something to the effect of you shall worship no other God but me. Right. And it's a beautiful

00:53:24.720 --> 00:53:29.280
[Amit Varma]: story. And I'll just say it out here, even though it's like a spoiler, but I'll just say it because

00:53:29.280 --> 00:53:33.040
[Amit Varma]: it's so beautiful. And I want you to watch the whole series anyway. It's like my favorite

00:53:33.040 --> 00:53:39.840
[Amit Varma]: cinematic Dekalog. Dekalog it's called. And the first story there based on this commandment

00:53:39.840 --> 00:53:46.960
[Amit Varma]: is about, you know, it's freezing cold. And the lake is kind of frozen, but it's not reached that

00:53:46.960 --> 00:53:51.040
[Amit Varma]: stage where people are skating on it yet. They're kind of waiting, waiting, waiting. And this kid

00:53:51.040 --> 00:53:57.760
[Amit Varma]: really wants to skate. And his father is kind of just like us, a rationalist and an actual scientist

00:53:57.760 --> 00:54:03.440
[Amit Varma]: and like us, and like me. And so what he does is he takes a temperature and he looks at,

00:54:04.080 --> 00:54:08.720
[Amit Varma]: he puts all kinds of data together to figure out when it is safe for his son to go skating.

00:54:08.720 --> 00:54:12.560
[Amit Varma]: And then he arrives at something which after all margins of errors and all he's saying,

00:54:12.560 --> 00:54:18.800
[Amit Varma]: it is absolutely safe for you to go skating. Now the ice will be frozen solid and the sun goes

00:54:18.800 --> 00:54:25.840
[Amit Varma]: and you can guess what happens next. And yeah, he's gone. And the next day, the father is standing

00:54:25.840 --> 00:54:30.880
[Amit Varma]: this consulate by the edge, wondering what the hell happened. All his numbers were right. All

00:54:30.880 --> 00:54:34.720
[Amit Varma]: his science was right. How could this have happened? And then in the distance, he sees a

00:54:34.720 --> 00:54:40.640
[Amit Varma]: homeless man besides the lake, warming his hands over a fire. And that tells you the complexity

00:54:40.640 --> 00:54:45.840
[Amit Varma]: of the world. And the way I kind of interpret that is that you respect the complexities,

00:54:45.840 --> 00:54:51.120
[Amit Varma]: you respect the multitudes. Thou shalt have no other God than me is not a literal invocation

00:54:51.120 --> 00:54:58.720
[Amit Varma]: to a real God that exists, but a sort of a more metaphorical look at just complexity of the world

00:54:58.720 --> 00:55:04.880
[Amit Varma]: and avoid certainties, therefore, which we often get caught up in. You know, you can't plan

00:55:04.880 --> 00:55:12.720
[Guest]: everything you can't. I have to watch this take a log or something. If this is the kind of filmmaking

00:55:12.720 --> 00:55:16.960
[Amit Varma]: that is happening, it's no, it's just gorgeous filmmaking at every level. Like to me, it's like

00:55:16.960 --> 00:55:22.000
[Amit Varma]: the epitome of cinema, but whatever, I always kind of get sentimental when I think of Kieslowski,

00:55:22.000 --> 00:55:27.600
[Amit Varma]: because there's such great films. Let's talk about your moving on from the childhood. Like at this

00:55:27.600 --> 00:55:32.000
[Amit Varma]: point, when you're a kid, what are you dreaming of being? I'm very curious about this because,

00:55:32.720 --> 00:55:37.520
[Amit Varma]: you know, back in the day, there's nothing right? There's no and I grew up, I'm just a few years

00:55:37.520 --> 00:55:42.400
[Amit Varma]: younger than you, though I think of us as being more or less in the same age group, late 40s,

00:55:42.400 --> 00:55:47.040
[Amit Varma]: mid 50s. What is the difference now? But back in the day, there was really nothing much. I mean,

00:55:47.040 --> 00:55:52.320
[Amit Varma]: I was privileged enough to have books at my disposal and whatever. And but the one TV set

00:55:52.320 --> 00:55:57.680
[Amit Varma]: just got you Krishi Darshan once a week. Yeah, you know, so what were your early dreams? What was your view

00:55:57.680 --> 00:56:03.840
[Guest]: of the world and your place in it? Yeah, so I, my father was a doctor, and he was, he had a successful

00:56:03.840 --> 00:56:10.000
[Guest]: practice. And it was assumed that I would become a doctor as well. So even I didn't question it.

00:56:11.600 --> 00:56:17.440
[Guest]: But I didn't. So you had this 10 standard and 12 standard and things of that. And

00:56:17.440 --> 00:56:22.400
[Guest]: back in the day, so someone I was talking to my nephew actually about a series on Amazon,

00:56:22.400 --> 00:56:29.520
[Guest]: he recommended called the Kota Factory on people preparing for the IIT. And I haven't watched it,

00:56:29.520 --> 00:56:34.400
[Guest]: but I was reminiscing about my time. In my time, it was something called Agarwal classes.

00:56:34.400 --> 00:56:42.560
[Guest]: So Agarwal classes was, you know, it was the top the slogan was ideal for scholars. So they are

00:56:42.560 --> 00:56:49.920
[Guest]: coaching classes. But, you know, in back in my time, only people who are really weak at studies

00:56:49.920 --> 00:56:54.720
[Guest]: would go to coaching classes, otherwise they wouldn't. Whereas this one, you know, you you went

00:56:54.720 --> 00:57:00.080
[Guest]: if you're good at it. Anyway, I managed to get into Agarwal classes. And I would go all the way

00:57:00.080 --> 00:57:06.320
[Guest]: from Malad to Dadar, which is far away. And it was prestigious. So not everyone got into I,

00:57:06.320 --> 00:57:11.360
[Guest]: there were two flavors, there was something called a vacation batch with the absolute toppers went to,

00:57:11.360 --> 00:57:16.000
[Guest]: which I didn't make it to. And there was a regular batch, which was hard to get in,

00:57:16.000 --> 00:57:20.960
[Guest]: but it was like, okay for models like me. So anyway, I managed to get in and I went there.

00:57:21.520 --> 00:57:29.200
[Guest]: And I found that it was just the same thing being repeated over and over and over again.

00:57:29.760 --> 00:57:34.880
[Guest]: And so you know, if you're done calculus, they'll tell you like you have to do like a

00:57:34.880 --> 00:57:41.920
[Guest]: you know, differentiate x cubed, so it is 3x squared. And that's it. Then, you know, if you

00:57:41.920 --> 00:57:46.880
[Guest]: want to differentiate x to the power four, it's four. And they just keep teaching you that over

00:57:46.880 --> 00:57:53.920
[Guest]: and over and over again. It just, it just, you know, it just froke me out. I couldn't handle

00:57:53.920 --> 00:57:59.600
[Guest]: after two months of this, I came and told my parents, there is no way I could, you know,

00:57:59.600 --> 00:58:04.560
[Guest]: I'm not going to Agarwal again. And to their credit, they said, okay, son, if you don't want

00:58:04.560 --> 00:58:10.080
[Guest]: to go, you study, prepare at home and study. Do try to get into medicine, because it will be nice

00:58:10.080 --> 00:58:16.320
[Guest]: and you can take away your father's practice. And I tried, I didn't get enough marks, I probably

00:58:16.320 --> 00:58:22.880
[Guest]: wasn't motivated. And then I was much better at math. So somebody, you know, my mother actually,

00:58:22.880 --> 00:58:26.960
[Guest]: she said, you know, you either have to become a doctor or an engineer, I'm not going to have you,

00:58:27.680 --> 00:58:30.720
[Guest]: you know, sort of doing some liberal arts thing. I was very keen on doing

00:58:30.720 --> 00:58:37.040
[Guest]: liberal arts, but she said, no, nothing doing. And so I went, even for engineering, I didn't have

00:58:37.040 --> 00:58:42.160
[Guest]: the marks to get into one of the top colleges in Bombay, but I went to Manipal, which was,

00:58:42.160 --> 00:58:51.280
[Guest]: you had my father to pay a little donation. And luckily for me, I liked that. I took to it.

00:58:52.400 --> 00:59:00.480
[Guest]: If you don't like mathematics of a certain kind, engineering is extremely, you know,

00:59:00.480 --> 00:59:04.800
[Guest]: you know, tedious, because it's there, it's omnipresent. You have calculus everywhere

00:59:05.360 --> 00:59:10.240
[Guest]: and everything. I mean, if you're studying thermodynamics, there's calculus. Heat transfer,

00:59:10.240 --> 00:59:15.200
[Guest]: there's calculus. Every damn thing, there is some calculus or the other. And there were people in

00:59:15.200 --> 00:59:22.720
[Guest]: my class who hated calculus and hated mathematics and they were miserable. But it was a generational

00:59:22.720 --> 00:59:29.280
[Guest]: thing. Parents really didn't ask their children what they wanted to become. So no one asked me

00:59:29.280 --> 00:59:34.960
[Guest]: what I wanted to become. Luckily for me, engineering was good. I met a lot of really

00:59:34.960 --> 00:59:40.720
[Guest]: cool people. So they were all guys like me. A lot of them were very intelligent, well-read.

00:59:41.280 --> 00:59:50.240
[Guest]: They had ideas of their own. They were good debates. It was fun. And it must have sort of

00:59:50.240 --> 00:59:59.520
[Guest]: molded me as a person. When you go to an engineering college hostel or any hostel,

00:59:59.520 --> 01:00:08.080
[Guest]: you're basically out of your parents' shadows. And anyone else can say or do anything to you.

01:00:08.080 --> 01:00:12.400
[Guest]: They are not restricted. You don't have parents to sort of protect you or anything like that.

01:00:12.400 --> 01:00:17.040
[Guest]: So there are some nice people, there are some nasty people. And this is a human thing. We have

01:00:17.040 --> 01:00:23.600
[Guest]: grown up in societies for all of our human history. You adapt, you make some friends,

01:00:23.600 --> 01:00:32.080
[Guest]: you make some foes and you actually make far many more friends than foes. And you grow as a person.

01:00:34.640 --> 01:00:44.560
[Guest]: Manipal was a transformational time in my life. By the end of that, I was still unclear as to

01:00:44.560 --> 01:00:54.800
[Guest]: what I wanted to become. One of my roommates, he had actually bought a firm for this MBA course.

01:00:55.440 --> 01:01:02.160
[Guest]: It was called MMS back then. And that was Mumbai University. So Bajaj, SPJ and all these were there.

01:01:02.960 --> 01:01:08.800
[Guest]: And he got a job in Siemens, which was like a really good job to have. So straight out of

01:01:08.800 --> 01:01:13.760
[Guest]: college, he got a job in Siemens. So he wasn't interested in going for this MBA. But he had

01:01:13.760 --> 01:01:21.040
[Guest]: spent a hundred rupees for the firm. So he offered to sell me the firm for 50 rupees. So I bought the

01:01:21.040 --> 01:01:28.080
[Guest]: firm from him in order to win the transaction. I bought it for 50 rupees. And then because I had...

01:01:29.680 --> 01:01:35.600
[Amit Varma]: Okay, should we pause? For the listeners, we'll pause for a moment because outside my window,

01:01:35.600 --> 01:01:40.640
[Amit Varma]: there is a window cleaner on the 27th floor. And I'm probably more nervous than he is right now.

01:01:40.640 --> 01:01:48.560
[Guest]: I'm actually afraid of heights. So this has to be the scariest job in the world for me.

01:01:50.960 --> 01:01:54.320
[Amit Varma]: Maybe he's looking in and thinking, I like to be alone by myself. These

01:01:54.320 --> 01:01:58.080
[Amit Varma]: people are speaking on a mic. Must be the scariest job in the world for me.

01:02:00.080 --> 01:02:09.600
[Guest]: We have a full-time guy who does all this. So he used to be a painter and he's done all this.

01:02:09.600 --> 01:02:16.080
[Guest]: So he's completely fearless when it comes to... So once we got locked out of our house,

01:02:16.080 --> 01:02:23.520
[Guest]: so he went into the other floor. He climbed up through the balcony and I was like...

01:02:24.320 --> 01:02:31.200
[Guest]: And he was absolutely nonchalant about it. Just like a couple of minutes, he was into the house.

01:02:31.200 --> 01:02:37.760
[Amit Varma]: So the window cleaner has gone down to the 26th floor, where it is presumably a little safer.

01:02:38.400 --> 01:02:43.280
[Guest]: And warmer also. The 27th floor is colder and it's probably...

01:02:43.280 --> 01:02:47.520
[Amit Varma]: Boss, the AC is on, so I'm sure not as cool as that.

01:02:47.520 --> 01:02:50.160
[Guest]: What were we talking about? I was rambling on.

01:02:50.880 --> 01:02:53.120
[Amit Varma]: College and the friends you made.

01:02:53.120 --> 01:03:03.520
[Guest]: I was talking about SPJN. So my roommate sold me the MBA form for 50 rupees and I filled it out

01:03:04.080 --> 01:03:09.200
[Guest]: only because I had paid 50 rupees for it. And the next thing I know, I'm doing an MBA.

01:03:10.320 --> 01:03:16.480
[Guest]: And it's one of the top colleges in India now, SPJN, Institute of Management and Research.

01:03:16.480 --> 01:03:24.240
[Guest]: But I was underwhelmed, to say the least, because I had no real context.

01:03:24.240 --> 01:03:29.040
[Guest]: I wasn't commercially minded. Business didn't turn me on.

01:03:29.760 --> 01:03:38.400
[Guest]: And it was... So one thing about management and the entire field of management education,

01:03:38.400 --> 01:03:43.840
[Guest]: I call it, quote unquote, is it's a lot of post-hoc rationalization.

01:03:43.840 --> 01:03:49.120
[Guest]: So something happens and then a bunch of people sit together and decide why it succeeded.

01:03:49.120 --> 01:03:54.240
[Guest]: So that time it was Sony Walkman and Sony Mockman.

01:03:54.240 --> 01:04:00.160
[Guest]: And you had marketing professors say that if you want anything to succeed,

01:04:00.160 --> 01:04:05.440
[Guest]: it has to be what the consumer wants and you have to figure out what the consumer needs.

01:04:05.440 --> 01:04:11.440
[Guest]: And then... And I was like, you know, Sony Walkman never existed before.

01:04:11.440 --> 01:04:15.760
[Guest]: How could anyone in the world know that it is so?

01:04:15.760 --> 01:04:20.800
[Guest]: I really couldn't understand how that was any kind of insightful.

01:04:21.520 --> 01:04:28.240
[Guest]: Anyway, so I got an MBA job out of my college. It was a nice job. I mean, well-paying and everything.

01:04:29.440 --> 01:04:35.280
[Guest]: But very little to do. So all day would be hanging around in office and chatting.

01:04:35.280 --> 01:04:40.240
[Guest]: You would have a few meetings and so... But most of the time there wasn't much work.

01:04:40.240 --> 01:04:44.000
[Guest]: Computers weren't popular.

01:04:44.000 --> 01:04:49.600
[Guest]: So you had one computer, it will usually be in the managing director's cabin.

01:04:49.600 --> 01:04:54.000
[Guest]: And it would be for the exclusive purpose of playing solitaire.

01:04:54.000 --> 01:04:55.360
[Guest]: So that kind of thing.

01:04:56.400 --> 01:05:01.040
[Guest]: But because of the lack of activity, I was going nuts.

01:05:01.040 --> 01:05:06.000
[Guest]: So I spent a couple of years there just basically not doing anything.

01:05:06.000 --> 01:05:11.040
[Guest]: So I decided to go back to engineering route.

01:05:11.040 --> 01:05:14.800
[Guest]: So I had a friend who was...

01:05:15.440 --> 01:05:19.200
[Guest]: We just met up one day and he was also feeling very blue.

01:05:19.200 --> 01:05:21.600
[Guest]: And we decided to start a factory.

01:05:21.600 --> 01:05:26.720
[Guest]: And then we started a small mechanical engineering workshop.

01:05:26.720 --> 01:05:31.120
[Guest]: They would make dyes and tools for other companies.

01:05:31.120 --> 01:05:38.000
[Guest]: And then progress to making components, which would supply some components to Bajaj Auto and to Videocon.

01:05:38.000 --> 01:05:39.920
[Guest]: And there were ups and downs.

01:05:39.920 --> 01:05:43.280
[Guest]: But basically, it was manufacturing all the way.

01:05:44.160 --> 01:05:48.480
[Guest]: And I sort of enjoyed that a lot.

01:05:49.440 --> 01:05:50.960
[Guest]: It's a very hard way to make money.

01:05:51.600 --> 01:05:58.160
[Guest]: Because manufacturing in our country is much better now.

01:05:58.160 --> 01:06:02.640
[Guest]: Back in the day, we had a lot of very restrictive laws.

01:06:05.520 --> 01:06:09.200
[Guest]: Central excise was one of the really, really bad...

01:06:09.200 --> 01:06:12.240
[Guest]: Everyone bellyaches about GST now.

01:06:12.240 --> 01:06:18.720
[Guest]: But GST regime is far more logical and easy to handle than excise.

01:06:18.720 --> 01:06:21.760
[Guest]: Excise was harassment on steroids.

01:06:21.760 --> 01:06:30.320
[Guest]: Every time you sent material from your factory, you couldn't breathe easily until it actually reached its destination.

01:06:30.320 --> 01:06:37.280
[Guest]: There were all kinds of preventive excise officers who could stop your vehicle on the road anywhere

01:06:37.280 --> 01:06:42.000
[Guest]: and summon you there if they found any discrepancy in the documents.

01:06:42.000 --> 01:06:43.440
[Guest]: There were a lot of things.

01:06:43.440 --> 01:06:51.840
[Guest]: So, then some people would harass you for bribery and things like that.

01:06:51.840 --> 01:06:55.280
[Guest]: The GST regime has sorted out a lot of that.

01:06:55.280 --> 01:06:59.440
[Guest]: But back in the day, those challenges were there.

01:06:59.440 --> 01:07:02.320
[Guest]: But even so, it was fun.

01:07:02.320 --> 01:07:04.000
[Guest]: I mean, you're always making things.

01:07:04.000 --> 01:07:06.480
[Guest]: You're finding new ways of making things.

01:07:06.480 --> 01:07:09.040
[Guest]: It was satisfying.

01:07:09.040 --> 01:07:13.840
[Guest]: There would be one way of making this widget and it would cost 10 rupees.

01:07:13.840 --> 01:07:19.120
[Guest]: And then you figure out a new and cheaper way of making that widget for 9 rupees 50 paisa.

01:07:19.120 --> 01:07:22.880
[Guest]: And then you got an extra profit of 50 paisa and that was sweet.

01:07:22.880 --> 01:07:27.840
[Guest]: Other people figured out what you've done and then the price of the thing became 9 rupees 50 paisa.

01:07:27.840 --> 01:07:29.440
[Guest]: So, you had to figure it out.

01:07:29.440 --> 01:07:33.760
[Guest]: So, it was a lot of little innovation.

01:07:33.760 --> 01:07:36.560
[Guest]: Jugaad kind of innovation some of the time.

01:07:36.560 --> 01:07:42.000
[Guest]: And for me, I had the advantage.

01:07:42.000 --> 01:07:46.480
[Guest]: Most of my competitors were not professionally qualified engineers.

01:07:46.480 --> 01:07:51.280
[Guest]: So, I could read and those days internet wasn't so common.

01:07:51.280 --> 01:07:54.000
[Guest]: So, I used to sort of go.

01:07:54.000 --> 01:07:57.280
[Guest]: There was this British Council library in Nariman Point.

01:07:57.280 --> 01:07:58.880
[Guest]: Go there, refer.

01:07:58.880 --> 01:08:02.560
[Guest]: You'd find easier and better ways of making things.

01:08:02.560 --> 01:08:05.680
[Guest]: And that was it.

01:08:05.680 --> 01:08:06.720
[Guest]: It was fun.

01:08:06.720 --> 01:08:12.400
[Guest]: Luckily for me, I wasn't entirely financially dependent on my business.

01:08:12.400 --> 01:08:19.280
[Guest]: I mean, I didn't have to spend any money on rent and things used to go along.

01:08:19.280 --> 01:08:22.160
[Guest]: So, I wasn't very competitive in that way.

01:08:22.160 --> 01:08:23.440
[Guest]: I never had any ambition.

01:08:23.440 --> 01:08:28.800
[Guest]: I didn't want to become, you know, fortune 500 company or anything like that.

01:08:28.800 --> 01:08:32.240
[Guest]: And that wish was granted.

01:08:32.240 --> 01:08:34.560
[Guest]: I never became a fortune 500 company.

01:08:34.560 --> 01:08:39.920
[Guest]: But it was mostly fun all the way.

01:08:39.920 --> 01:08:47.040
[Guest]: So, an engineering sort of, you know, career was that way satisfying.

01:08:47.040 --> 01:08:52.240
[Guest]: What it was not is it did not give a sense of achievement.

01:08:52.240 --> 01:08:58.640
[Guest]: Like, you have these little moments of cleverness where you figure out some better way of doing something.

01:08:58.640 --> 01:09:01.840
[Guest]: But it's always very, very incremental.

01:09:01.840 --> 01:09:06.720
[Guest]: At least in this country, you never get the opportunity of doing something radically different.

01:09:06.720 --> 01:09:08.720
[Guest]: Why do you say at least in this country?

01:09:08.720 --> 01:09:11.120
[Guest]: I know other places you have.

01:09:11.120 --> 01:09:16.880
[Guest]: We just made, you made a coffee for me in, you know, using the AeroPress.

01:09:16.880 --> 01:09:25.440
[Guest]: So, the guy who invented the AeroPress did something and he had the intellectual protection

01:09:25.440 --> 01:09:27.520
[Guest]: and he made a lot of money.

01:09:27.520 --> 01:09:29.120
[Guest]: So, that does two things.

01:09:29.120 --> 01:09:34.560
[Guest]: It, you know, it gives him more power to do other things.

01:09:34.560 --> 01:09:39.440
[Guest]: It inspires other people to look for, you know, ways of doing other things.

01:09:39.440 --> 01:09:42.960
[Guest]: In India, we don't have that protection.

01:09:42.960 --> 01:09:52.960
[Guest]: So, if someone were to invent an AeroPress in India, it would be copied literally within days of it coming out.

01:09:52.960 --> 01:09:55.840
[Guest]: That's why we don't have much innovation.

01:09:55.840 --> 01:10:01.360
[Guest]: We still do, but the innovators are not well rewarded.

01:10:01.360 --> 01:10:05.280
[Guest]: So, we don't have an ecosystem of innovation.

01:10:05.280 --> 01:10:06.400
[Guest]: This is what I feel.

01:10:08.160 --> 01:10:12.000
[Amit Varma]: Tell me more about how, like the engineering part of it, I get it.

01:10:12.000 --> 01:10:16.400
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you're essentially, in any case, you're a person who loves tinkering, taking things apart,

01:10:16.400 --> 01:10:17.840
[Amit Varma]: coming up with ideas for things.

01:10:17.840 --> 01:10:22.400
[Amit Varma]: And I can imagine why that sense of achievement may not be there for incremental stuff,

01:10:22.400 --> 01:10:24.080
[Amit Varma]: because so much of it is unseen.

01:10:24.080 --> 01:10:28.400
[Amit Varma]: Like you said, if you, you know, find a way to make something that costs 10 rupees for 9.50

01:10:28.400 --> 01:10:32.240
[Amit Varma]: and you make it for 9.50 and then everyone copies you and they make it for 9.50.

01:10:32.240 --> 01:10:37.760
[Amit Varma]: The benefit to society is actually enormous because all those extra 50 paisas go out into the economy,

01:10:37.760 --> 01:10:39.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, create more jobs.

01:10:39.440 --> 01:10:40.800
[Amit Varma]: It's a positive sum game.

01:10:40.800 --> 01:10:42.720
[Amit Varma]: But it's not noticed by you.

01:10:42.720 --> 01:10:46.240
[Amit Varma]: All you see is that I have done so much work and everybody's brought it down.

01:10:46.240 --> 01:10:47.600
[Amit Varma]: We've kind of lost that.

01:10:48.240 --> 01:10:52.000
[Amit Varma]: So, I get the joy of engineering that's there.

01:10:52.000 --> 01:10:55.280
[Amit Varma]: But the business side of it is not so much joy there.

01:10:55.280 --> 01:10:57.600
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about what those times were like,

01:10:57.600 --> 01:11:00.640
[Amit Varma]: because in a sense, in terms of regulatory environment,

01:11:00.640 --> 01:11:03.360
[Amit Varma]: you've come from pre-liberalization all the way to now,

01:11:03.360 --> 01:11:05.760
[Amit Varma]: through all the many different phases and all that.

01:11:05.760 --> 01:11:10.880
[Amit Varma]: You pointed out how you would constantly be stressed because of the excise regime and so on.

01:11:10.880 --> 01:11:12.400
[Amit Varma]: So, what was it like?

01:11:12.400 --> 01:11:16.000
[Amit Varma]: Like, what really was ease of doing business like back in the day?

01:11:16.000 --> 01:11:18.000
[Guest]: Yeah, so I'll give you an example, okay?

01:11:18.000 --> 01:11:22.560
[Guest]: So, there was this, so we used to supply to Videocon television.

01:11:22.560 --> 01:11:25.920
[Guest]: So, our items were pretty much standard.

01:11:25.920 --> 01:11:29.040
[Guest]: There was something called tuner mounting bracket in heat sinks.

01:11:29.040 --> 01:11:32.960
[Guest]: So, tuner mounting bracket was, you know, you just mount a tuner.

01:11:34.720 --> 01:11:39.840
[Guest]: There was another company in the vicinity which used to make brackets and stuff.

01:11:40.800 --> 01:11:43.360
[Guest]: Videocon, another company called Videocon Appliances.

01:11:43.360 --> 01:11:46.240
[Guest]: They used to make washing machines and air conditioners.

01:11:46.240 --> 01:11:51.040
[Guest]: Now, washing machines had an excise duty, I think, of 0% or 5% or something,

01:11:51.040 --> 01:11:52.880
[Guest]: because it was a household thing.

01:11:52.880 --> 01:11:56.400
[Guest]: And air conditioner had, I think, 50% or 100% or something.

01:11:57.200 --> 01:12:01.520
[Guest]: And the bracket was, I mean, you know, it looked pretty much the same.

01:12:01.520 --> 01:12:03.440
[Guest]: So, it's a bracket.

01:12:03.440 --> 01:12:06.960
[Guest]: You mount the machine on that bracket and that goes somewhere.

01:12:06.960 --> 01:12:10.080
[Guest]: So, there is one kind of bracket which goes under washing machine.

01:12:10.080 --> 01:12:13.600
[Guest]: There's another kind which goes under an air conditioner.

01:12:13.600 --> 01:12:22.880
[Guest]: So, one of the popular things for the excise officers to catch you on was classification.

01:12:22.880 --> 01:12:31.840
[Guest]: So, they would say that you have purposely classified something for a lower tax rate

01:12:31.840 --> 01:12:33.840
[Guest]: just in order to evade taxes,

01:12:33.840 --> 01:12:38.880
[Guest]: and then slap you with all kinds of back, you know, penal taxes and things like that.

01:12:38.880 --> 01:12:41.440
[Guest]: And the process was also the punishment.

01:12:41.440 --> 01:12:43.680
[Guest]: So, they would impound your books.

01:12:43.680 --> 01:12:45.200
[Guest]: They would seal your factory.

01:12:46.080 --> 01:12:47.280
[Guest]: It used to be called seizing.

01:12:47.280 --> 01:12:48.480
[Guest]: They used to seize the books.

01:12:49.360 --> 01:12:52.880
[Guest]: And once they seized everything, you couldn't even supply.

01:12:53.920 --> 01:12:58.160
[Guest]: So, there was, I knew the other guy in our vicinity,

01:12:58.160 --> 01:13:04.080
[Guest]: because oftentimes, Video Con used to have the same transporter for both our goods,

01:13:04.080 --> 01:13:06.960
[Guest]: it used to go into roughly the same location.

01:13:06.960 --> 01:13:10.480
[Guest]: So, the guy would come to our place, pick up our material, go there.

01:13:10.480 --> 01:13:15.680
[Guest]: And sometimes, he would request us that, you know, you fill your goods first,

01:13:15.680 --> 01:13:17.680
[Guest]: because mine aren't completely packed yet.

01:13:17.680 --> 01:13:20.080
[Guest]: I'll get another hour or two to pack them.

01:13:20.080 --> 01:13:21.600
[Guest]: And so, we had a...

01:13:21.600 --> 01:13:25.600
[Guest]: So, one day, a whole bunch of excise people have caught.

01:13:25.600 --> 01:13:31.920
[Guest]: This guy is completely paralyzed and he is, you know, the vehicles come and he can't go.

01:13:31.920 --> 01:13:36.400
[Guest]: So, anyway, I land up there and I find this guy a complete wreck,

01:13:36.400 --> 01:13:44.160
[Guest]: because the excise person has alleged that the material that he is sending for washing machines

01:13:44.160 --> 01:13:48.560
[Guest]: is actually material he is sending for the air conditioner,

01:13:49.040 --> 01:13:52.720
[Guest]: but it has been misclassified in order to save excise duty.

01:13:52.720 --> 01:13:57.840
[Guest]: And there is no proof that this gentleman can give that will satisfy that person.

01:13:59.280 --> 01:14:05.280
[Guest]: After a really long time and the exchange of a little bit of consideration,

01:14:05.280 --> 01:14:08.480
[Guest]: of consideration, he was finally let go.

01:14:09.440 --> 01:14:13.200
[Guest]: But that person, you know, he is an elderly gentleman.

01:14:13.200 --> 01:14:15.200
[Guest]: He was so shaken up by this.

01:14:15.200 --> 01:14:20.560
[Guest]: Within a few months, he sold off his entire business and disappeared.

01:14:20.560 --> 01:14:21.920
[Guest]: I have never met him again.

01:14:23.040 --> 01:14:24.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's really sad.

01:14:24.160 --> 01:14:28.000
[Amit Varma]: And you say, you know, the exchange of a little consideration.

01:14:28.000 --> 01:14:30.640
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, I guess, all these laws...

01:14:30.640 --> 01:14:32.560
[Amit Varma]: See, typically, how we think of all these laws,

01:14:32.560 --> 01:14:36.640
[Amit Varma]: which give too much discretionary power to inspectors, Inspector Raj and all,

01:14:36.640 --> 01:14:38.000
[Amit Varma]: is that it's all rent-seeking.

01:14:39.760 --> 01:14:40.880
[Amit Varma]: Was that the case with you?

01:14:40.880 --> 01:14:42.880
[Amit Varma]: Were you having to pay, like, bribes?

01:14:43.680 --> 01:14:45.600
[Guest]: Actually, not much, right?

01:14:45.600 --> 01:14:46.640
[Guest]: So, they were...

01:14:46.640 --> 01:14:47.440
[Guest]: So, you had...

01:14:47.440 --> 01:14:51.920
[Guest]: So, there would be a visit from a PWD inspector.

01:14:51.920 --> 01:14:56.960
[Guest]: Now, actually, no one knew what the PWD inspector came and inspected.

01:14:56.960 --> 01:14:58.560
[Guest]: So, he just came, he gave you a...

01:14:58.560 --> 01:15:04.160
[Guest]: First, he would send a little sort of notice saying that he's coming on such and such date.

01:15:04.160 --> 01:15:09.280
[Guest]: Then you come on that date, you sit in your office, you have your tea.

01:15:09.280 --> 01:15:10.240
[Guest]: There would be a small...

01:15:11.440 --> 01:15:13.840
[Guest]: Back in the day, I think it was a thousand rupees or something.

01:15:13.840 --> 01:15:16.720
[Guest]: You paid him a thousand rupees, he would give you his report,

01:15:16.720 --> 01:15:17.920
[Guest]: and that was the end of the thing.

01:15:18.560 --> 01:15:21.680
[Guest]: I later found out that this was an electric safety report.

01:15:21.680 --> 01:15:27.440
[Guest]: So, this was certifying that my factory is electrically safe.

01:15:28.560 --> 01:15:33.920
[Guest]: And that person who was certified in has no accountability at all.

01:15:33.920 --> 01:15:40.000
[Guest]: So, you know, if it's not safe and God forbid, somebody dies,

01:15:41.040 --> 01:15:42.400
[Guest]: he's not responsible.

01:15:42.400 --> 01:15:46.080
[Guest]: So, why is he even certifying anything if he's not responsible?

01:15:46.080 --> 01:15:47.920
[Guest]: If somebody is certifying something,

01:15:47.920 --> 01:15:52.400
[Guest]: you know, that person should stand by or you should record his observation,

01:15:52.400 --> 01:15:54.000
[Guest]: or say what exactly he's done.

01:15:54.880 --> 01:15:59.600
[Guest]: So, those days, there were a lot of those kind of visits.

01:15:59.600 --> 01:16:02.800
[Guest]: And, you know, people who had boilers, had people from boiler department,

01:16:02.800 --> 01:16:03.360
[Guest]: people who had...

01:16:04.400 --> 01:16:05.840
[Guest]: They had this, they had...

01:16:05.840 --> 01:16:11.040
[Guest]: There was someone in our area who had a small furnace.

01:16:11.040 --> 01:16:14.400
[Guest]: There was some inspection thing for furnaces.

01:16:14.400 --> 01:16:19.680
[Guest]: The unifying characteristics of all these were that there was no responsibility.

01:16:19.680 --> 01:16:21.840
[Guest]: There were labor inspectors who would come.

01:16:21.840 --> 01:16:26.560
[Guest]: There was one labor inspector whose job was to ensure that there was no child labor.

01:16:27.520 --> 01:16:30.560
[Guest]: And he would just land up and certify that there was no child labor.

01:16:30.560 --> 01:16:32.480
[Guest]: I mean, how would you know there's no child labor?

01:16:32.480 --> 01:16:36.000
[Guest]: You have to, you know, you have to do some kind of due diligence.

01:16:36.000 --> 01:16:36.960
[Guest]: There was no such.

01:16:38.000 --> 01:16:43.120
[Guest]: And there were myriad authorities who would keep coming back in the day.

01:16:43.120 --> 01:16:47.280
[Guest]: They would keep coming back in the day, take their little bit and go away.

01:16:48.320 --> 01:16:52.640
[Guest]: All that seems to have vanished now.

01:16:52.640 --> 01:16:57.600
[Guest]: But to be fair, back in the day, none of them was adversarial.

01:16:57.600 --> 01:16:58.960
[Guest]: They were all interested in their little...

01:16:59.520 --> 01:17:03.040
[Guest]: And it was usually modest, a few hundred rupees to a few thousand rupees.

01:17:03.040 --> 01:17:05.280
[Guest]: They would take their money and do Ram Ram and go away.

01:17:05.280 --> 01:17:08.160
[Guest]: And you never see from them again.

01:17:08.800 --> 01:17:10.000
[Guest]: There were reports.

01:17:10.000 --> 01:17:13.840
[Guest]: So sometimes what would happen is they would be haggling.

01:17:13.840 --> 01:17:21.200
[Guest]: And then the guy, the officer, I mean, there's no competition there.

01:17:21.200 --> 01:17:22.480
[Guest]: You can't go to another officer.

01:17:22.480 --> 01:17:25.440
[Guest]: So if he decided to make an example of you for haggling,

01:17:26.000 --> 01:17:30.400
[Guest]: then you would hear of one or two people on whom cases were filed.

01:17:30.400 --> 01:17:34.240
[Guest]: And they had to go and meet superiors and do whatever.

01:17:34.240 --> 01:17:38.800
[Guest]: Now, it has more or less vanished.

01:17:38.800 --> 01:17:41.600
[Guest]: So we don't have such visits.

01:17:41.600 --> 01:17:48.000
[Guest]: We don't have, we have, I think, pollution control is one,

01:17:48.000 --> 01:17:50.400
[Guest]: but pollution control these days is pretty serious.

01:17:50.400 --> 01:17:54.080
[Guest]: Like they'll actually, you know, you can't just say that we have all day,

01:17:54.080 --> 01:17:58.720
[Guest]: they'll see every fuming chimney and every smokestack, everything is inspected.

01:17:58.720 --> 01:18:01.200
[Guest]: There are norms, there are pollution norms, everything.

01:18:01.200 --> 01:18:06.560
[Guest]: It is, they do a far more serious job now than they used to.

01:18:07.200 --> 01:18:12.480
[Guest]: I haven't had labor inspectors in a really long time,

01:18:12.480 --> 01:18:14.320
[Guest]: but we do have to maintain records.

01:18:14.320 --> 01:18:15.680
[Guest]: They are being filed regularly.

01:18:15.680 --> 01:18:16.560
[Guest]: All those things are there.

01:18:17.120 --> 01:18:22.720
[Guest]: So, and as I was saying, GST is pretty clear.

01:18:22.720 --> 01:18:26.160
[Guest]: It's a pretty brutal regime.

01:18:26.160 --> 01:18:29.680
[Guest]: I mean, GST, if you don't pay GST, you are screwed.

01:18:29.680 --> 01:18:34.640
[Guest]: But if you do and, you know, your records are all okay,

01:18:35.360 --> 01:18:37.280
[Guest]: really no one hassles you at all.

01:18:37.280 --> 01:18:40.880
[Guest]: You never have GST officers knocking on your door.

01:18:41.840 --> 01:18:47.200
[Guest]: So what really stops industry from growing, in my opinion?

01:18:48.000 --> 01:18:49.600
[Guest]: Two things, just two things.

01:18:49.600 --> 01:18:54.800
[Guest]: One is access to land and the second is access to capital.

01:18:54.800 --> 01:18:57.120
[Guest]: They really don't have either.

01:18:57.120 --> 01:19:02.640
[Guest]: So today, if you want to get any kind of land, especially industrial land,

01:19:02.640 --> 01:19:05.760
[Guest]: this is not so much the case in residential, I believe.

01:19:05.760 --> 01:19:11.280
[Guest]: It's, you know, it's possible to go and buy a flat without paying a penny in cash.

01:19:11.280 --> 01:19:12.560
[Guest]: It's everything is checked.

01:19:12.560 --> 01:19:16.640
[Guest]: But in industrial circles, that's still not the case.

01:19:16.640 --> 01:19:22.560
[Guest]: I am told that a good 50% of the considerations are cash in many places.

01:19:22.560 --> 01:19:25.840
[Guest]: What happens is for most of us, for people like us, we have,

01:19:25.840 --> 01:19:30.480
[Guest]: I mean, if I had to buy something, I would take a bank loan to the extent of 80 or 90%.

01:19:31.040 --> 01:19:34.960
[Guest]: And if I had to pay a big chunk of it in cash, there's no way I can get bank finance.

01:19:34.960 --> 01:19:37.840
[Guest]: So I don't end up buying premises.

01:19:37.840 --> 01:19:39.440
[Guest]: Access to land is one.

01:19:39.440 --> 01:19:41.200
[Guest]: And the second is access to capital.

01:19:42.080 --> 01:19:47.120
[Guest]: Even today, if you want business finance, it's very, very expensive.

01:19:47.120 --> 01:19:50.960
[Guest]: Unless you have collateral security to give, and then it's dramatically cheap.

01:19:50.960 --> 01:19:55.040
[Guest]: So if, you know, if you had a house and you wanted a one crore rupee loan,

01:19:55.040 --> 01:19:56.880
[Guest]: you'd pay an interest of 7%.

01:19:56.880 --> 01:20:02.960
[Guest]: If you didn't have collateral security of your house to give, you'd pay, I don't know, 15, 17%.

01:20:04.080 --> 01:20:07.840
[Guest]: And that difference can be killing for many businesses.

01:20:08.720 --> 01:20:14.320
[Guest]: And so if the present government wants manufacturing to grow, they seem to want that.

01:20:14.320 --> 01:20:19.760
[Guest]: They seem to want MSMEs to grow because a lot of, you know, it just picks up a lot of employment.

01:20:19.760 --> 01:20:26.960
[Guest]: And MSMEs are also very inventive and enterprising when it comes to getting business.

01:20:26.960 --> 01:20:34.080
[Guest]: So if you want to export stuff, you know, you leave an entrepreneur on his own.

01:20:34.080 --> 01:20:38.400
[Guest]: He'll go, he'll find out, you know, something's required in Lithuania,

01:20:38.400 --> 01:20:41.600
[Guest]: and he knows that some input for that comes from Taiwan.

01:20:41.600 --> 01:20:44.480
[Guest]: He'll get the input from Taiwan, the other input from Bolivia,

01:20:44.480 --> 01:20:45.920
[Guest]: and then send it to Lithuania.

01:20:45.920 --> 01:20:47.040
[Guest]: All those things happen.

01:20:47.040 --> 01:20:51.360
[Guest]: It's never going to happen in, you know, in large corporations.

01:20:52.640 --> 01:20:58.160
[Guest]: Because for most large corporations, all these small petty businesses are not worth the thing,

01:20:58.160 --> 01:21:00.720
[Guest]: and definitely not going to work in a government environment,

01:21:00.720 --> 01:21:03.600
[Guest]: although there's no way it's going to happen.

01:21:04.400 --> 01:21:11.520
[Guest]: But yeah, I don't see these two problems getting solved anytime soon.

01:21:11.520 --> 01:21:15.920
[Guest]: So we're going to be second best after China for a long time.

01:21:15.920 --> 01:21:17.040
[Amit Varma]: That's what it looks like.

01:21:17.040 --> 01:21:19.360
[Amit Varma]: Second best or third best or whatever best.

01:21:19.360 --> 01:21:24.000
[Amit Varma]: I've actually heard contrary stories about GST from businessmen as well,

01:21:24.000 --> 01:21:26.400
[Amit Varma]: about how it's made things so much worse for them.

01:21:26.400 --> 01:21:29.600
[Amit Varma]: And just speaking for myself, I have to like, file every month.

01:21:29.600 --> 01:21:31.440
[Guest]: And it's just irritating.

01:21:31.440 --> 01:21:32.720
[Guest]: But it's not ambiguous.

01:21:34.560 --> 01:21:36.560
[Guest]: The thing about why, I'll tell you.

01:21:36.560 --> 01:21:43.600
[Guest]: So one of my companies, we had, so someone, it's a very small company,

01:21:43.600 --> 01:21:47.760
[Guest]: we keep, we file, we do the GST every month, everything is fine.

01:21:48.880 --> 01:21:55.120
[Guest]: One month, this is during the COVID, you know, it was just emerging out of COVID.

01:21:55.920 --> 01:21:58.720
[Guest]: Our, the person looked after the GST.

01:21:59.520 --> 01:22:02.960
[Guest]: I think he got, either he got COVID or someone close to him got COVID.

01:22:02.960 --> 01:22:06.080
[Guest]: He was basically unable for that entire month.

01:22:06.080 --> 01:22:08.240
[Guest]: He was basically running pillar to post.

01:22:08.240 --> 01:22:10.320
[Guest]: He survived, everything turned out well.

01:22:10.320 --> 01:22:11.920
[Guest]: But you know, it was an anxious time.

01:22:11.920 --> 01:22:15.680
[Guest]: And for some reason, our GST return did not get filed.

01:22:17.280 --> 01:22:21.920
[Guest]: The next thing I know is, I get a letter saying that we're going to attach your bank account.

01:22:22.480 --> 01:22:25.680
[Guest]: This is just like 8-10 days.

01:22:26.720 --> 01:22:29.520
[Guest]: Luckily, he came back, we filed it, it's all.

01:22:30.320 --> 01:22:31.920
[Guest]: But it's that menacing.

01:22:33.200 --> 01:22:38.720
[Guest]: If your bank account gets attached, it's practically curtains for your business.

01:22:38.720 --> 01:22:43.760
[Guest]: Curtains for your business, you cannot work, your bank account is frozen,

01:22:43.760 --> 01:22:46.880
[Guest]: you can't pay anyone, you can't receive any money, nothing, nothing, nothing.

01:22:47.760 --> 01:22:52.000
[Guest]: And what happens then to, you know, we employ 25-30 people,

01:22:53.360 --> 01:22:58.640
[Guest]: maybe 100-150 people dependent on our company.

01:22:58.640 --> 01:23:02.000
[Guest]: Just all of a sudden, because you're not able to pay your GST in time,

01:23:02.560 --> 01:23:07.440
[Guest]: if your bank account gets attached, it's curtains for your business.

01:23:07.440 --> 01:23:08.720
[Guest]: What are these people going to do?

01:23:09.520 --> 01:23:15.360
[Guest]: So, you know, government is always thinking about their revenue and their listing.

01:23:15.360 --> 01:23:20.240
[Guest]: Very little empathy for what problems industry might be facing.

01:23:20.240 --> 01:23:26.000
[Guest]: So I've heard anecdotal stories about a lot of small companies folding up because of this.

01:23:26.000 --> 01:23:29.680
[Guest]: You know, they can't take the harassment, they can't take the tension any longer.

01:23:29.680 --> 01:23:31.840
[Guest]: So, not the harassment, just the tension.

01:23:31.840 --> 01:23:36.240
[Guest]: Just like, you know, you have to pay X and you have no money.

01:23:36.240 --> 01:23:39.920
[Guest]: And that's because one of your customers hasn't paid you money.

01:23:39.920 --> 01:23:43.120
[Guest]: So, you know, and you have no other resources.

01:23:43.840 --> 01:23:47.680
[Guest]: So then you just fold up after some time, you just pack up the business because

01:23:48.560 --> 01:23:51.840
[Guest]: you don't want to face the prospect of going to prison or whatever.

01:23:52.800 --> 01:23:55.200
[Amit Varma]: And yeah, I mean, there's a lot of messy elements.

01:23:55.200 --> 01:23:59.360
[Amit Varma]: Like, for example, someone was telling me about the business where they supply

01:23:59.360 --> 01:24:02.800
[Amit Varma]: merchandise and those kind of items to various stores.

01:24:02.800 --> 01:24:07.120
[Amit Varma]: And in the earlier regime, you don't have to pay any taxes on those things until they are sold.

01:24:07.120 --> 01:24:11.520
[Amit Varma]: But in this regime, once you send it to a store, you have to pay your GST on it.

01:24:11.520 --> 01:24:14.720
[Amit Varma]: And if you're a small business, if you don't have working capital,

01:24:14.720 --> 01:24:16.320
[Amit Varma]: you're blown out of the water right away.

01:24:16.320 --> 01:24:20.480
[Amit Varma]: And I know of cases where this has kind of happened.

01:24:20.480 --> 01:24:23.280
[Amit Varma]: And just speaking of regulations, you know, you were talking about, you know,

01:24:23.280 --> 01:24:26.080
[Amit Varma]: all the different regulations and the inspectors who would come.

01:24:26.080 --> 01:24:29.600
[Amit Varma]: And I did an episode long ago when episodes were much shorter,

01:24:29.600 --> 01:24:32.960
[Amit Varma]: when they were little miniatures of half an hour with our mutual friend,

01:24:32.960 --> 01:24:35.120
[Amit Varma]: Madhu Menon on restaurant regulations.

01:24:35.120 --> 01:24:37.360
[Amit Varma]: And Madhu pointed out, he used to run a fantastic

01:24:37.360 --> 01:24:39.600
[Amit Varma]: South East Asian restaurant called Shiok in Bangalore.

01:24:40.240 --> 01:24:43.920
[Amit Varma]: Sadly, he shut down because just running a business is very hard.

01:24:43.920 --> 01:24:47.520
[Amit Varma]: It's not just about creating great food and great ambience, both of which he did.

01:24:47.520 --> 01:24:51.760
[Amit Varma]: But he told me the story about how there were two separate inspectors

01:24:51.760 --> 01:24:53.200
[Amit Varma]: who would keep inspecting the restaurant.

01:24:53.200 --> 01:24:56.080
[Amit Varma]: And one of them was the fire safety guy.

01:24:56.080 --> 01:25:00.000
[Amit Varma]: And for the fire safety regulation was you have to have multiple entrances

01:25:00.000 --> 01:25:01.760
[Amit Varma]: to your restaurant for safety reasons.

01:25:01.760 --> 01:25:04.080
[Amit Varma]: So it's obvious and it's fair enough.

01:25:04.080 --> 01:25:06.800
[Amit Varma]: And then there was, I think, the excise regulation

01:25:06.800 --> 01:25:09.360
[Amit Varma]: where they wanted to control the entry of liquor.

01:25:09.360 --> 01:25:12.400
[Amit Varma]: So that regulation was there can only be one entrance to any restaurant

01:25:12.400 --> 01:25:15.120
[Amit Varma]: because they want to, you know, check the chip,

01:25:15.120 --> 01:25:18.240
[Amit Varma]: make it easy for them to check liquor going in and out.

01:25:18.240 --> 01:25:20.320
[Amit Varma]: And you obviously can't comply with both.

01:25:20.320 --> 01:25:22.240
[Amit Varma]: You know, you can't be like Schrodinger's restaurant,

01:25:22.240 --> 01:25:24.560
[Amit Varma]: that if this dude shows up, he sees two entrances.

01:25:24.560 --> 01:25:27.520
[Amit Varma]: If the other dude shows up, he sees one entrance.

01:25:27.520 --> 01:25:29.200
[Amit Varma]: You are going to break one of those laws.

01:25:29.760 --> 01:25:32.320
[Amit Varma]: Chances are you're going to have to bribe both of those guys.

01:25:32.320 --> 01:25:35.760
[Amit Varma]: And then the point is like other people who run businesses in the current day

01:25:35.760 --> 01:25:40.320
[Amit Varma]: have told me that like one guy who shut a similar enterprise a few years back

01:25:40.320 --> 01:25:42.880
[Amit Varma]: said, boss, I was bribing 30 people a month.

01:25:42.880 --> 01:25:44.240
[Amit Varma]: I just couldn't do it.

01:25:44.240 --> 01:25:48.320
[Amit Varma]: And even this ease of business rankings that we've gone up in a little bit,

01:25:48.320 --> 01:25:51.680
[Amit Varma]: a couple of years back, we went back and the government was boasting about it.

01:25:51.680 --> 01:25:56.240
[Amit Varma]: The point is that they game the metrics in terms of ease of doing business.

01:25:56.240 --> 01:25:58.720
[Amit Varma]: It didn't actually become better.

01:25:58.720 --> 01:26:01.120
[Amit Varma]: And one way of thinking about this is through an anecdote,

01:26:01.120 --> 01:26:02.640
[Amit Varma]: which is not about business.

01:26:02.640 --> 01:26:06.960
[Amit Varma]: But like I keep saying that there's really no rule of law in this country effectively,

01:26:06.960 --> 01:26:08.080
[Amit Varma]: unless you're very rich.

01:26:08.080 --> 01:26:10.240
[Amit Varma]: But there's no rule of law in this country effectively.

01:26:10.240 --> 01:26:11.520
[Amit Varma]: And the state is a parasite.

01:26:11.520 --> 01:26:15.200
[Amit Varma]: And an illustration of that comes from my poker playing years.

01:26:15.200 --> 01:26:17.120
[Amit Varma]: So I don't know if I told you the story,

01:26:17.120 --> 01:26:18.960
[Amit Varma]: but did I tell you the story about the raid?

01:26:18.960 --> 01:26:22.560
[Amit Varma]: And yeah, so I'll repeat it for my listeners.

01:26:22.560 --> 01:26:27.280
[Amit Varma]: So basically, there used to be these underground cash games all over the place.

01:26:27.280 --> 01:26:30.320
[Amit Varma]: So somebody I know used to organize an underground cash game.

01:26:30.320 --> 01:26:33.760
[Amit Varma]: And this happened to be there was a new building that had just been built.

01:26:33.760 --> 01:26:37.040
[Amit Varma]: In fact, it's near the urban Tarka at Lokhandwala,

01:26:37.040 --> 01:26:38.400
[Amit Varma]: not the one at seven bungalows.

01:26:38.400 --> 01:26:42.800
[Amit Varma]: Besides that, there was a new building and most of the flats were not occupied.

01:26:42.800 --> 01:26:47.280
[Amit Varma]: So my friend rented out one of these flats and a game used to happen there.

01:26:47.280 --> 01:26:50.000
[Amit Varma]: And what typically happens is when you conduct an underground game

01:26:50.000 --> 01:26:53.520
[Amit Varma]: is that people kind of play the game.

01:26:53.520 --> 01:26:55.200
[Amit Varma]: And poker, of course, it's a game of scale.

01:26:55.200 --> 01:26:56.560
[Amit Varma]: You're playing against the other person.

01:26:56.560 --> 01:26:59.120
[Amit Varma]: However, the house, the people organizing the game

01:26:59.120 --> 01:27:00.640
[Amit Varma]: and getting the players together,

01:27:00.640 --> 01:27:03.360
[Amit Varma]: they take a cut of every pot, which is called the rake.

01:27:03.360 --> 01:27:05.040
[Amit Varma]: So you take a small cut of every pot,

01:27:05.040 --> 01:27:07.840
[Amit Varma]: and that eventually amounts to a lot of money.

01:27:09.280 --> 01:27:12.480
[Amit Varma]: So this friend of mine lives in Bombay, but was in Goa at the time.

01:27:12.480 --> 01:27:14.960
[Amit Varma]: And he had a very nice guy.

01:27:14.960 --> 01:27:16.560
[Amit Varma]: I'll give him a fake name for now.

01:27:16.560 --> 01:27:19.760
[Amit Varma]: I'll say Salim, but basically a Muslim guy,

01:27:19.760 --> 01:27:23.200
[Amit Varma]: which is, you know, key to the story, as you'll realize.

01:27:23.200 --> 01:27:28.400
[Amit Varma]: So the person we shall call Salim used to run this game for him.

01:27:28.400 --> 01:27:32.640
[Amit Varma]: And one of the neighbors in this partly occupied building

01:27:32.640 --> 01:27:35.520
[Amit Varma]: realized one day that there are all these young men

01:27:35.520 --> 01:27:39.360
[Amit Varma]: who are coming every day into this otherwise unoccupied flat.

01:27:39.360 --> 01:27:42.960
[Amit Varma]: And they have backpacks and they all look like Kasab.

01:27:42.960 --> 01:27:45.520
[Amit Varma]: And this was circa 2011-2012.

01:27:45.520 --> 01:27:47.440
[Amit Varma]: Right, and they all look like Kasab.

01:27:47.440 --> 01:27:52.160
[Amit Varma]: So they compared to the anti-terrorism cell, the ATS, as we call it.

01:27:52.160 --> 01:27:54.720
[Amit Varma]: So the ATS decided to do a raid.

01:27:54.720 --> 01:27:57.920
[Amit Varma]: So the ATS lands up when a game is on and they ring the bell.

01:27:57.920 --> 01:28:00.160
[Amit Varma]: And our friend Salim, which is a name we've given him,

01:28:00.160 --> 01:28:01.280
[Amit Varma]: but remember, he's a Muslim.

01:28:01.280 --> 01:28:04.320
[Amit Varma]: So our friend Salim opens the door and they ask him,

01:28:04.320 --> 01:28:05.520
[Amit Varma]: What's going on here?

01:28:05.520 --> 01:28:07.840
[Amit Varma]: The anti-terrorism squad asks him.

01:28:07.840 --> 01:28:11.200
[Amit Varma]: And Salim has been raided before poker games.

01:28:11.200 --> 01:28:13.520
[Amit Varma]: It happens once in a while, you pay a hafta, you get away.

01:28:13.520 --> 01:28:15.440
[Amit Varma]: So Salim smiles very sweetly.

01:28:15.440 --> 01:28:18.000
[Amit Varma]: And he says, Sir, you know, first they ask him his name.

01:28:18.000 --> 01:28:19.200
[Amit Varma]: He says, Sir Salim.

01:28:19.200 --> 01:28:20.960
[Amit Varma]: Then they say, What's going on here?

01:28:20.960 --> 01:28:23.120
[Amit Varma]: And Salim says, You know what's going on.

01:28:23.120 --> 01:28:25.040
[Amit Varma]: Sir, what you're thinking is what's going on.

01:28:27.200 --> 01:28:31.600
[Amit Varma]: Anyway, so the ATS squad comes in and then they realize what's really going on.

01:28:31.600 --> 01:28:34.160
[Amit Varma]: And they make Salim.

01:28:34.960 --> 01:28:38.320
[Amit Varma]: I'm finding the name amusing because it's a made up name.

01:28:38.320 --> 01:28:40.800
[Amit Varma]: But they make Salim call up this friend of mine

01:28:40.800 --> 01:28:43.120
[Amit Varma]: who is at that moment in time in Goa.

01:28:43.120 --> 01:28:46.080
[Amit Varma]: And who is a seasoned veteran.

01:28:46.080 --> 01:28:50.880
[Amit Varma]: So he tells these cops that don't worry, Sir, I'll come and settle this, that.

01:28:50.880 --> 01:28:52.240
[Amit Varma]: You let the boys play.

01:28:52.240 --> 01:28:55.760
[Amit Varma]: And on that particular day, and I had been to that game two or three times.

01:28:55.760 --> 01:28:59.040
[Amit Varma]: But on that particular day, it was all young teenagers who were playing.

01:28:59.040 --> 01:29:00.400
[Amit Varma]: It was a low stakes game.

01:29:00.400 --> 01:29:02.480
[Amit Varma]: So they were all terrified that the cops are here.

01:29:02.480 --> 01:29:04.480
[Amit Varma]: And no fucking what's going to happen and all that.

01:29:04.480 --> 01:29:07.440
[Amit Varma]: And the cop calmly pats one of them on the head and says,

01:29:07.440 --> 01:29:09.440
[Amit Varma]: It's okay, play, play.

01:29:09.440 --> 01:29:11.360
[Amit Varma]: And then they go away.

01:29:11.360 --> 01:29:15.920
[Amit Varma]: So the next day, my friend comes back from Goa and he meets these guys.

01:29:15.920 --> 01:29:19.040
[Amit Varma]: And this guy says, OK, so this is a deal you're playing every day.

01:29:19.040 --> 01:29:20.320
[Amit Varma]: This is how it goes.

01:29:20.320 --> 01:29:23.200
[Amit Varma]: So give us a week of X amount every month.

01:29:23.920 --> 01:29:26.720
[Amit Varma]: Now, my friend was smart enough to not fall for this.

01:29:26.720 --> 01:29:30.480
[Amit Varma]: He said, look, Sir, I'll give you a week today.

01:29:30.480 --> 01:29:33.280
[Amit Varma]: But tomorrow your second department will come and ask.

01:29:33.280 --> 01:29:36.000
[Amit Varma]: Day after tomorrow, your third department will come and ask.

01:29:36.000 --> 01:29:39.840
[Amit Varma]: So it's better that you tell me a consolidated amount.

01:29:39.840 --> 01:29:41.760
[Amit Varma]: After that, I don't want any tension.

01:29:42.480 --> 01:29:45.200
[Amit Varma]: So the cop says, yeah, this is a good point.

01:29:45.760 --> 01:29:48.320
[Amit Varma]: So, OK, come back tomorrow afternoon.

01:29:48.320 --> 01:29:51.520
[Amit Varma]: So he goes the next afternoon to this police station or wherever he goes,

01:29:51.520 --> 01:29:52.880
[Amit Varma]: wherever the meeting is.

01:29:52.880 --> 01:29:56.800
[Amit Varma]: And you have three guys from three different departments across the table with him.

01:29:56.800 --> 01:30:00.080
[Amit Varma]: And they negotiate a bit and they arrive at a consolidated amount,

01:30:00.080 --> 01:30:02.640
[Amit Varma]: which he pays, which will be divided, however.

01:30:02.640 --> 01:30:04.480
[Amit Varma]: And then he takes them to Marriott for lunch.

01:30:05.120 --> 01:30:09.760
[Amit Varma]: And my point of this long story is that this is basically the game.

01:30:09.760 --> 01:30:14.320
[Amit Varma]: That, you know, any actual policing that you see is kind of accidental.

01:30:14.320 --> 01:30:15.520
[Amit Varma]: We are very lucky to have it.

01:30:15.520 --> 01:30:16.720
[Amit Varma]: Thank you so much.

01:30:16.720 --> 01:30:19.600
[Amit Varma]: But in general, this is a parasitic state at work.

01:30:19.600 --> 01:30:21.120
[Amit Varma]: This is how everything works.

01:30:21.120 --> 01:30:25.840
[Amit Varma]: And it is so completely explicit when it comes to the case of businesses.

01:30:25.840 --> 01:30:30.240
[Amit Varma]: Like you pointed out that someone is coming there to see that there are no child laborers.

01:30:30.240 --> 01:30:32.320
[Amit Varma]: It is a worthwhile inspection to do.

01:30:32.320 --> 01:30:36.160
[Amit Varma]: Even that guy is sitting in your office, having a child, taking a bribe, going away.

01:30:36.160 --> 01:30:38.240
[Amit Varma]: No one actually gives a shit about the law, right?

01:30:38.240 --> 01:30:45.680
[Guest]: But this is egregiously, you know, present in all these fire cases that you keep seeing, right?

01:30:45.680 --> 01:30:49.440
[Guest]: So some building or the other goes up in flames.

01:30:49.440 --> 01:30:54.960
[Guest]: And almost never is there an audit into what inspection was done

01:30:55.600 --> 01:31:01.200
[Guest]: and why the person who has done the inspection should not be put under the scanner.

01:31:01.200 --> 01:31:09.600
[Guest]: So the reason for this is accountability, okay, is like a cancer for them.

01:31:10.560 --> 01:31:18.720
[Guest]: Because if you allow the principle that a building fire inspector is accountable for his report,

01:31:18.720 --> 01:31:25.200
[Guest]: there is nothing to stop a cabinet secretary from being accountable for whatever he is accountable for.

01:31:25.200 --> 01:31:34.640
[Guest]: So no one in the establishment wants accountability ever to percolate into theirs.

01:31:34.640 --> 01:31:36.640
[Guest]: It's not that they don't know about.

01:31:36.640 --> 01:31:41.760
[Guest]: You, for example, are liable to pay, let us say, GST.

01:31:41.760 --> 01:31:45.760
[Guest]: And you have appointed a GST consultant to pay it for you.

01:31:45.760 --> 01:31:50.400
[Guest]: And for some reason or the other, maybe GST consultant died.

01:31:50.400 --> 01:31:55.840
[Guest]: Maybe he had a domestic problem, whatever, he didn't pay your GST.

01:31:55.840 --> 01:31:59.840
[Guest]: And you've just been sort of transferring the money, you know, you calculate, you send the money to him.

01:31:59.840 --> 01:32:01.600
[Guest]: He didn't file the thing.

01:32:02.640 --> 01:32:04.960
[Guest]: Who faces the music? You do.

01:32:04.960 --> 01:32:06.880
[Guest]: You cannot pass it on to.

01:32:06.880 --> 01:32:11.280
[Guest]: So it's not that the government doesn't understand the meaning of accountability.

01:32:11.280 --> 01:32:12.720
[Guest]: They understand it very well.

01:32:12.720 --> 01:32:14.720
[Guest]: They make sure it doesn't apply to them.

01:32:14.720 --> 01:32:20.160
[Guest]: The day this happens, I'm pretty sure we'll have a huge transformed state.

01:32:20.160 --> 01:32:24.800
[Guest]: But it is like, you know, because if you have to introduce accountability,

01:32:24.800 --> 01:32:26.640
[Guest]: it has to be the government that does it.

01:32:26.640 --> 01:32:30.160
[Guest]: It is like asking an alcoholic to blow up a distillery.

01:32:30.160 --> 01:32:33.600
[Guest]: It's very, very, very, very unlikely not going to happen.

01:32:33.600 --> 01:32:35.360
[Guest]: So it becomes wishful thinking.

01:32:35.360 --> 01:32:40.800
[Guest]: Then what happens is, like so many successful businessmen you see now,

01:32:40.800 --> 01:32:46.240
[Guest]: the person who is able to manage the environment best wins.

01:32:46.240 --> 01:32:50.800
[Guest]: So in the case of Madhu, we know very well what kind of a person he is.

01:32:50.800 --> 01:32:53.120
[Guest]: He's a sensitive person.

01:32:53.120 --> 01:32:55.600
[Guest]: He has no two standards.

01:32:55.600 --> 01:33:00.080
[Guest]: He lives by a code and he expects everyone to live by the same code.

01:33:00.080 --> 01:33:02.560
[Guest]: There is no duplicity within him.

01:33:03.120 --> 01:33:09.280
[Guest]: He's not able to accommodate the duplicity which is necessary for doing business.

01:33:09.280 --> 01:33:14.720
[Amit Varma]: No, in his case, I think he was practical enough to make all the payments when required.

01:33:14.720 --> 01:33:16.080
[Amit Varma]: You do what it takes.

01:33:16.080 --> 01:33:19.200
[Amit Varma]: I mean, his business, the restaurant ran for six to seven years.

01:33:19.200 --> 01:33:23.520
[Amit Varma]: If you, you know, Google for sure, it is still regarded as a cult place.

01:33:23.520 --> 01:33:26.960
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, running a business in India is too hard.

01:33:26.960 --> 01:33:28.720
[Guest]: And I don't think anyone who runs it is not.

01:33:28.720 --> 01:33:30.320
[Guest]: So that's the argument I'm saying.

01:33:30.320 --> 01:33:34.480
[Guest]: So if Madhu, you know, he's really good at cooking.

01:33:34.480 --> 01:33:39.680
[Guest]: And I've, I've not eaten at his restaurant, but I've eaten what Madhu has cooked.

01:33:39.680 --> 01:33:45.920
[Guest]: And I have, you know, I have, I know so many of our friends who have eaten at Shauk.

01:33:45.920 --> 01:33:47.840
[Guest]: It was an outstandingly good restaurant.

01:33:49.120 --> 01:33:55.600
[Guest]: And it should have been like, you know, there is this restaurant called Olive and Olive is a chain now.

01:33:55.600 --> 01:34:00.080
[Guest]: There are many, many olives and the guy who started it must be doing very, very well.

01:34:00.080 --> 01:34:01.600
[Guest]: Madhu could have been that person.

01:34:01.600 --> 01:34:11.200
[Guest]: Had he outsourced his liaison work to someone savvy, because if he had to pay an X percentage of his,

01:34:11.760 --> 01:34:16.080
[Guest]: he would have factored in that as a cost, adjusted his pricing accordingly, adjusted

01:34:16.080 --> 01:34:19.040
[Guest]: his business model accordingly and gone on with it.

01:34:19.040 --> 01:34:30.000
[Guest]: So the, you know, the, the, the government, you know, the onerous burden of missing is,

01:34:30.000 --> 01:34:36.240
[Guest]: I don't think it's, that is the reason why business doesn't flourish in India.

01:34:37.280 --> 01:34:43.040
[Guest]: I think it's because delivery of government services is not what, though that is improving

01:34:43.040 --> 01:34:46.320
[Guest]: now, if you look at infrastructure, I don't know what cost it comes at.

01:34:46.320 --> 01:34:52.640
[Guest]: But infrastructure is a lot, lot better than what it was when we were growing up.

01:34:53.200 --> 01:34:55.920
[Guest]: It's also a function, I think, of the nation's prosperity.

01:34:55.920 --> 01:35:01.200
[Guest]: We, I mean, we do get, all countries become more prosperous.

01:35:01.200 --> 01:35:02.400
[Guest]: We do earn more money.

01:35:02.400 --> 01:35:10.480
[Guest]: There is, so, but a lot of services that the government has, is supposed to deliver,

01:35:10.480 --> 01:35:17.200
[Guest]: it doesn't get delivered because there is no incentive for anyone to do so.

01:35:17.760 --> 01:35:19.360
[Guest]: There is no accountability.

01:35:19.360 --> 01:35:20.560
[Amit Varma]: Like what kind of services?

01:35:20.560 --> 01:35:22.880
[Guest]: Like the rule of law or contract resolution?

01:35:22.880 --> 01:35:28.400
[Guest]: Law is the most, you know, like, you know, we are a nation which is pro-poor.

01:35:28.400 --> 01:35:33.200
[Guest]: Like always, the entire rhetoric has always been Garibon Ka Desh and everything.

01:35:34.320 --> 01:35:38.720
[Guest]: Politician after politician has wept tears for the plight of poor people.

01:35:38.720 --> 01:35:42.800
[Guest]: And yet you just have to go hang out outside a police station, see what happens when a poor guy

01:35:42.800 --> 01:35:43.360
[Guest]: goes.

01:35:43.360 --> 01:35:50.480
[Guest]: The first thing he gets is a slap, for anything, whatever, if you come, you should, you know,

01:35:50.480 --> 01:35:51.840
[Guest]: this is how they do.

01:35:51.840 --> 01:35:54.080
[Guest]: They, they, they're not sympathetically treated.

01:35:54.080 --> 01:36:00.880
[Guest]: There is not, I have, so once Sheila and I, we lost, we had some shares and so one of the

01:36:00.880 --> 01:36:02.000
[Guest]: certificates was missing.

01:36:02.000 --> 01:36:07.120
[Guest]: So we asked for a duplicate service back in the day and we asked for a duplicate certificate

01:36:07.120 --> 01:36:12.080
[Guest]: and they said that the requirement for that is that you have to have an FIR.

01:36:12.080 --> 01:36:19.200
[Guest]: So you have to go, so I went to Malad Police Station and I was expecting to, you know,

01:36:19.200 --> 01:36:21.200
[Guest]: be asked for a bribe or anything like that.

01:36:21.200 --> 01:36:27.440
[Guest]: To my great surprise, not only was I not asked for a bribe, the inspector actually, you know,

01:36:27.440 --> 01:36:34.000
[Guest]: was very courteous, asked, there was some chai coming and I speak Marathi well, so we

01:36:34.000 --> 01:36:38.880
[Guest]: spoke in Marathi for some time and then Sheila doesn't speak Marathi, so there was some

01:36:38.880 --> 01:36:44.080
[Guest]: good-hearted, you know, sort of, you know, why don't you, you've been in Mumbai, why don't you

01:36:44.080 --> 01:36:45.440
[Guest]: speak, all that kind of happening.

01:36:45.440 --> 01:36:57.600
[Guest]: And just then, a boy, man is brought in for something and his mother is, you know, comes

01:36:57.600 --> 01:37:06.000
[Guest]: running after him, crying to leave him and there is, it's something, some neighbours, he hit

01:37:06.000 --> 01:37:08.800
[Guest]: someone, she hit some, there was some such thing.

01:37:08.800 --> 01:37:16.800
[Guest]: What they did was, they, so he tells his assistant to take him Mandir mein leke jao.

01:37:18.240 --> 01:37:22.640
[Guest]: So Sheila is like, you know, so why are they taking him to a temple?

01:37:24.800 --> 01:37:28.800
[Guest]: And then he says, Mandir mein leke jao, main aata hoon, phir pooja karenge.

01:37:28.800 --> 01:37:37.120
[Guest]: So, and Sheila, being Sheila, was wondering why, then I told her and by that time, the

01:37:37.120 --> 01:37:39.280
[Guest]: gentleman had gone away.

01:37:39.280 --> 01:37:45.520
[Guest]: So I told her what was happening and then you could hear muted cries and, you know,

01:37:45.520 --> 01:37:49.760
[Guest]: obviously he was being slapped or whatever, what was being happening inside.

01:37:51.040 --> 01:37:55.760
[Guest]: And around the same time, our work gets done.

01:37:55.760 --> 01:37:59.600
[Guest]: So the person was assigned to writing out, he's written out and there's quite a procedure to

01:37:59.600 --> 01:38:03.680
[Guest]: writing out and there's several registers to be filled out, he's filled out all the

01:38:03.680 --> 01:38:08.800
[Guest]: registers, he's written it out, he's given me a copy of everything and so I thank my

01:38:08.800 --> 01:38:10.720
[Guest]: inspector and I go away.

01:38:10.720 --> 01:38:15.680
[Guest]: So it's a different law for privileged people like us and different one for poor people

01:38:15.680 --> 01:38:21.600
[Guest]: and that is something which does need to be addressed in, you know, it'd be nice if it

01:38:21.600 --> 01:38:22.320
[Amit Varma]: happens soon.

01:38:23.760 --> 01:38:28.160
[Amit Varma]: You know, when you mentioned accountability, you correctly said that accountability is

01:38:28.160 --> 01:38:31.840
[Amit Varma]: for the people, it's not for the government and it should really be the other way around.

01:38:31.840 --> 01:38:33.520
[Amit Varma]: The government should be accountable to us.

01:38:33.520 --> 01:38:35.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, we don't have to be accountable to them.

01:38:37.840 --> 01:38:41.600
[Amit Varma]: And yet it's almost as if, you know, when you deal with the police, the vibe you get

01:38:41.600 --> 01:38:43.600
[Amit Varma]: is guilty until proven innocent.

01:38:43.600 --> 01:38:46.960
[Amit Varma]: And for us privileged people, it might be slightly different unless you're a film star's

01:38:46.960 --> 01:38:47.600
[Amit Varma]: son.

01:38:47.600 --> 01:38:55.200
[Amit Varma]: But otherwise for, you know, for I think 95% of Indians, essentially the rule of law is

01:38:55.200 --> 01:38:56.400
[Amit Varma]: completely absent.

01:38:56.400 --> 01:39:00.240
[Amit Varma]: You know, we are really in the top 1% or half percent or whatever.

01:39:00.240 --> 01:39:05.360
[Amit Varma]: I think the extent of poverty in this country is underestimated.

01:39:05.360 --> 01:39:09.200
[Amit Varma]: The way you kind of described how you fell into this business is similar to how you fell

01:39:09.200 --> 01:39:10.400
[Amit Varma]: into doing an MBA.

01:39:10.400 --> 01:39:14.240
[Amit Varma]: That, oh, my friend was filling a form, so I also filled a form and I got in.

01:39:14.240 --> 01:39:18.320
[Amit Varma]: And then, oh, I didn't really enjoy the MBA job and a friend said, let's start a business.

01:39:18.320 --> 01:39:19.920
[Amit Varma]: So I started a business.

01:39:19.920 --> 01:39:27.040
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, was it just kind of an accident, a decision you took at a point and before

01:39:27.040 --> 01:39:30.800
[Amit Varma]: you know it, 30 years have passed or whatever, and you're still doing the same thing?

01:39:30.800 --> 01:39:34.640
[Amit Varma]: Or was there some sort of ambition, some kind of directionality?

01:39:35.280 --> 01:39:37.920
[Amit Varma]: You know, were there other ambitions during this while?

01:39:37.920 --> 01:39:42.560
[Amit Varma]: For example, there is a famous Facebook group called We Want Narendra Shenoy to write a

01:39:42.560 --> 01:39:47.120
[Amit Varma]: book, which many of your friends have been telling you for a long time for your enormous

01:39:47.120 --> 01:39:48.560
[Amit Varma]: storytelling skills.

01:39:48.560 --> 01:39:52.320
[Amit Varma]: So were there other things playing out at this moment within you?

01:39:52.320 --> 01:40:00.400
[Guest]: I'm almost embarrassed to say that I didn't have any, I've never had any plan whatsoever

01:40:00.400 --> 01:40:01.120
[Guest]: ever in my life.

01:40:01.120 --> 01:40:06.160
[Guest]: So I've, I'm, I'm one of those easily persuaded people.

01:40:06.160 --> 01:40:08.400
[Guest]: So that's, that's my problem with politicians as well.

01:40:08.400 --> 01:40:13.760
[Guest]: So I listened to a persuasive politician, and I'm completely convinced till I listened

01:40:13.760 --> 01:40:17.840
[Guest]: to the other side, and then I'm completely convinced about that as well.

01:40:17.840 --> 01:40:25.440
[Guest]: And oftentimes those two opinions, it's impossible to have them in one thing.

01:40:25.440 --> 01:40:31.200
[Guest]: So similarly, even when it comes to businesses, I'm very easily persuaded.

01:40:31.200 --> 01:40:38.320
[Guest]: And I, you know, I'm, I'm just enthusiastic about everything.

01:40:38.320 --> 01:40:46.640
[Guest]: What, what happens in a, because that's the nature of all businesses, is that your environment

01:40:46.640 --> 01:40:47.920
[Guest]: keeps changing the demand.

01:40:47.920 --> 01:40:53.760
[Guest]: So for example, you could have a typewriter factory in 1992, and you would sell 1 million

01:40:53.760 --> 01:40:55.440
[Guest]: typewriters a year.

01:40:56.080 --> 01:40:58.960
[Guest]: And by 2000, you wouldn't sell a single one.

01:41:00.160 --> 01:41:01.600
[Guest]: So things keep changing.

01:41:02.880 --> 01:41:09.520
[Guest]: One of, you know, my main business is automotive components, and I supply to automobiles.

01:41:09.520 --> 01:41:16.720
[Guest]: And tomorrow, if the expected transformation to electric vehicles happens much quicker

01:41:16.720 --> 01:41:22.800
[Guest]: than we think it will, I might be out of work in a couple of years time.

01:41:22.800 --> 01:41:27.520
[Guest]: I have, you know, there's no one wants my product anymore, because it is basically a

01:41:27.520 --> 01:41:32.960
[Guest]: sound suppressing thing, which is far more required in, you know, engine driven cars,

01:41:32.960 --> 01:41:36.560
[Guest]: petrol or diesel driven cars than in electric vehicles.

01:41:36.560 --> 01:41:44.960
[Guest]: So, I, yeah, I was planning for the, like, you know, having a direction is not, not,

01:41:44.960 --> 01:41:46.960
[Guest]: not what I'm terribly good at.

01:41:48.960 --> 01:41:51.360
[Guest]: I'm just, I've just been stumbling along.

01:41:51.360 --> 01:41:54.640
[Guest]: That's, that's what I've been doing for the last 30 years or so.

01:41:56.240 --> 01:42:00.240
[Guest]: But yeah, actually come to think of it, I have no clue why it is so.

01:42:00.240 --> 01:42:02.000
[Guest]: No one told me not to plan.

01:42:02.000 --> 01:42:03.840
[Guest]: It's just that I'm not good at it.

01:42:03.840 --> 01:42:05.440
[Guest]: I've never done anything like that.

01:42:05.440 --> 01:42:08.800
[Amit Varma]: So, on that note, I mean, I don't plan my commercial breaks either.

01:42:08.800 --> 01:42:10.000
[Amit Varma]: They just come when they come.

01:42:10.000 --> 01:42:12.240
[Amit Varma]: And I think this is a good time for a commercial break.

01:42:12.240 --> 01:42:16.960
[Amit Varma]: So, let's give in to the moment and take a quick commercial break and come back on the

01:42:16.960 --> 01:42:17.520
[Amit Varma]: other side.

01:42:19.040 --> 01:42:22.240
[Amit Varma]: Have you always wanted to be a writer, but never quite gotten down to it?

01:42:22.240 --> 01:42:23.520
[Amit Varma]: Well, I'd love to help you.

01:42:23.520 --> 01:42:28.880
[Amit Varma]: Since April last year, I've enjoyed teaching 17 cohorts of my online course, The Art of

01:42:28.880 --> 01:42:29.920
[Amit Varma]: Clear Writing.

01:42:29.920 --> 01:42:33.040
[Amit Varma]: An online community has now sprung up of all my past students.

01:42:33.040 --> 01:42:37.600
[Amit Varma]: We have workshops, a newsletter to showcase the work of students, and vibrant community

01:42:37.600 --> 01:42:38.320
[Amit Varma]: interaction.

01:42:38.320 --> 01:42:43.920
[Amit Varma]: In the course itself, through four webinars spread over four Saturdays, I share all I

01:42:43.920 --> 01:42:46.720
[Amit Varma]: know about the craft and practice of clear writing.

01:42:46.720 --> 01:42:51.520
[Amit Varma]: There are many exercises, much interaction, and that lovely and lively community at the

01:42:51.520 --> 01:42:52.160
[Amit Varma]: end of it.

01:42:52.160 --> 01:42:58.000
[Amit Varma]: The course costs Rs. 10,000 plus GST, or about $150, and registration is now open for my

01:42:58.000 --> 01:42:59.840
[Amit Varma]: Winter 2021 cohort.

01:42:59.840 --> 01:43:04.400
[Amit Varma]: This will run through the last two weeks of November, and the first two weeks of December.

01:43:04.400 --> 01:43:06.560
[Amit Varma]: Classes begin on November 20th.

01:43:06.560 --> 01:43:11.600
[Amit Varma]: So, if you're interested, head on over to register at indiauncut.com slash clear writing.

01:43:11.600 --> 01:43:14.560
[Amit Varma]: That's indiauncut.com slash clear writing.

01:43:14.560 --> 01:43:19.360
[Amit Varma]: Being a good writer doesn't require God-given talent, just the willingness to work hard

01:43:19.360 --> 01:43:23.680
[Amit Varma]: and a clear idea of what you need to do to refine your skills.

01:43:23.680 --> 01:43:24.560
[Amit Varma]: I want to help you.

01:43:26.880 --> 01:43:28.240
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to The Scene and The Unseen.

01:43:28.240 --> 01:43:33.680
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Narendra Shenoy, who, before the break, confessed that he was never a kid

01:43:33.680 --> 01:43:36.720
[Amit Varma]: with ambitions and never had a plan for his life.

01:43:36.720 --> 01:43:38.560
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, it's refreshing to hear that.

01:43:38.560 --> 01:43:44.000
[Amit Varma]: I think, you know, we are often sold a couple of these new-age self-help-y things, which

01:43:44.000 --> 01:43:47.280
[Amit Varma]: is, you got to follow your passion and all of that.

01:43:47.280 --> 01:43:50.560
[Amit Varma]: And I think that that's sort of wrong at multiple levels.

01:43:50.560 --> 01:43:54.960
[Amit Varma]: One is, it doesn't consider expected value, which we were just discussing before this.

01:43:54.960 --> 01:44:00.240
[Amit Varma]: That is quite OK if, say, your kid wants to be something unconventional.

01:44:00.240 --> 01:44:02.800
[Amit Varma]: And let's say your kid wants to be a singer.

01:44:02.800 --> 01:44:06.080
[Amit Varma]: And he says, look, Arijit Singh has done so well, which is great.

01:44:06.080 --> 01:44:07.920
[Amit Varma]: But the point is, Arijit Singh is an outlier.

01:44:07.920 --> 01:44:12.160
[Amit Varma]: He's the one guy who made it in a business where typically a handful of people really

01:44:12.160 --> 01:44:15.840
[Amit Varma]: make a lot of money and the rest of them are perennial strugglers.

01:44:15.840 --> 01:44:17.200
[Amit Varma]: So you need to keep that in mind.

01:44:17.200 --> 01:44:21.760
[Amit Varma]: Whereas if you do engineering MBA, all the mediocre engineers and MBAs out there are

01:44:21.760 --> 01:44:25.200
[Amit Varma]: going to make a really healthy living and provide well for their families.

01:44:25.200 --> 01:44:32.400
[Amit Varma]: You know, I keep saying the cafes of Versova are filled with the strugglers who follow

01:44:32.400 --> 01:44:34.880
[Unknown]: their dream for 25 years and look where it got them.

01:44:34.880 --> 01:44:36.480
[Amit Varma]: So in a sense, I'm glad.

01:44:36.480 --> 01:44:42.880
[Amit Varma]: I think people need to realize that not everybody necessarily has to have a dream per se, you

01:44:42.880 --> 01:44:43.920
[Amit Varma]: know.

01:44:43.920 --> 01:44:49.280
[Amit Varma]: But even though you didn't have a dream, you obviously had things that you like doing,

01:44:49.280 --> 01:44:51.840
[Amit Varma]: things that you cared about and were passionate about.

01:44:51.840 --> 01:44:53.840
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit more about them.

01:44:53.840 --> 01:44:57.760
[Amit Varma]: Like, I know food is one of them, obviously, we've kind of connected on that level a heck

01:44:57.760 --> 01:44:58.800
[Amit Varma]: of a lot.

01:44:58.800 --> 01:45:02.720
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a bit more about food, especially like, was it from a childhood thing as your

01:45:02.720 --> 01:45:06.000
[Amit Varma]: grandfather, you know, ran a restaurant and so on.

01:45:06.000 --> 01:45:11.200
[Amit Varma]: And tell me a bit more about, you know, how you started thinking about food as a USMB?

01:45:11.200 --> 01:45:17.280
[Guest]: Yeah, so growing up, we were not a restaurant going family.

01:45:17.280 --> 01:45:18.320
[Guest]: We used to eat at home.

01:45:18.320 --> 01:45:23.200
[Guest]: We used to eat at home and I used to love the food that, you know, so I belong to a

01:45:23.200 --> 01:45:27.200
[Guest]: community called Gaut Saraswat Brahman.

01:45:27.200 --> 01:45:31.280
[Guest]: And we have, you know, it's basically idli and dosa.

01:45:31.280 --> 01:45:36.160
[Guest]: So here's an interesting, so I used to, when I was a kid, I used to hate the fact that

01:45:36.160 --> 01:45:40.000
[Guest]: my mom used to make idlis and dosas every day.

01:45:40.000 --> 01:45:42.720
[Guest]: So, you know, it was either idli or dosa.

01:45:42.720 --> 01:45:50.480
[Guest]: So my sisters were my, I mean, we had gone to this house to live and they had a couple

01:45:50.480 --> 01:45:55.280
[Guest]: of friends and they had come over, my sisters are doing their homework.

01:45:55.280 --> 01:45:59.280
[Guest]: And these girls come over and they want to, you know, play.

01:45:59.280 --> 01:46:01.920
[Guest]: I said, they're busy, they're doing their homework.

01:46:01.920 --> 01:46:05.960
[Guest]: And I was older, so I asked them, you know, can I get you something?

01:46:05.960 --> 01:46:09.200
[Guest]: Can I get you a glass of water, soft drink or something?

01:46:09.200 --> 01:46:13.200
[Guest]: They said, no, no, we've eaten, we've come, little girls.

01:46:13.200 --> 01:46:20.600
[Guest]: And the younger of them volunteers that, you know, we had bread and jam for breakfast.

01:46:20.600 --> 01:46:23.040
[Guest]: So I said, that sounds nice.

01:46:23.040 --> 01:46:30.640
[Guest]: And then she volunteered further information, said, we had, we have bread and jam for breakfast

01:46:30.640 --> 01:46:31.640
[Guest]: every day.

01:46:31.640 --> 01:46:34.420
[Guest]: So I said, indeed.

01:46:34.420 --> 01:46:37.080
[Guest]: So she said, yeah, except Sundays.

01:46:37.080 --> 01:46:39.400
[Guest]: I said, what do you have on Sunday?

01:46:39.400 --> 01:46:43.720
[Guest]: She said, we had bread, butter and jam.

01:46:43.720 --> 01:46:48.080
[Guest]: That's when I realized, the first time I realized that I was far more privileged in the terms

01:46:48.080 --> 01:46:53.880
[Guest]: of having good home cooking as compared to many other people.

01:46:53.880 --> 01:46:58.320
[Guest]: My mother was a good cook, she was, she used to make, she doesn't eat non-veg, but she

01:46:58.320 --> 01:47:01.560
[Guest]: used to make, you know, chicken and things like that for us.

01:47:01.560 --> 01:47:06.720
[Guest]: So my father was a very, you know, he loved people.

01:47:06.720 --> 01:47:08.880
[Guest]: He had to have friends and we had a large house.

01:47:08.880 --> 01:47:14.560
[Guest]: So every Saturday, all his colleagues, almost everyone was a doctor.

01:47:14.560 --> 01:47:19.400
[Guest]: So they would all like wind up with their practices at 10 or 11 at night and come home

01:47:19.400 --> 01:47:20.400
[Guest]: for a drink.

01:47:20.400 --> 01:47:26.080
[Guest]: And there would be a lot of singing, dancing, boisterous partying till two or three in the

01:47:26.080 --> 01:47:27.080
[Guest]: morning.

01:47:27.080 --> 01:47:31.440
[Guest]: And my mother would cook for all of them without complaining.

01:47:31.440 --> 01:47:37.880
[Guest]: So that it was, you know, regardless and oftentimes these people would come without warning.

01:47:37.880 --> 01:47:45.440
[Guest]: So my father wouldn't even tell her and then cooking would begin at 11 at night.

01:47:45.440 --> 01:47:52.600
[Guest]: And I also remember this, almost always, she would be the only person in the kitchen doing

01:47:52.600 --> 01:47:59.640
[Guest]: everything, chopping vegetables quickly and putting things, washing rice, making food.

01:47:59.640 --> 01:48:08.320
[Guest]: So when I got married, Sheila was my wife, was a far more restaurant person.

01:48:08.320 --> 01:48:15.640
[Guest]: So she liked to go out and I like, I had never, you know, restaurant going was never a part

01:48:15.640 --> 01:48:17.640
[Guest]: of my upbringing.

01:48:17.640 --> 01:48:24.840
[Guest]: Indeed, when I used to go out, my comfort food was dal fry and roti.

01:48:24.840 --> 01:48:30.240
[Guest]: So wherever I went, I just ordered dal fry and roti and I didn't like to go to Chinese

01:48:30.240 --> 01:48:34.560
[Guest]: restaurants because they didn't have dal fry and roti.

01:48:34.560 --> 01:48:40.040
[Guest]: So then, first of all, when Sheila found out about this, she was aghast and then slowly

01:48:40.040 --> 01:48:48.240
[Guest]: she changed my view towards food and over the last 30 years, I have become practically

01:48:48.240 --> 01:48:57.200
[Guest]: human and I like many cuisines and Southeast Asian cuisine being my favorite.

01:48:57.200 --> 01:49:03.400
[Guest]: But I wasn't much of a foodie for a long period of time.

01:49:03.400 --> 01:49:09.320
[Guest]: Then somewhere in 2007 or 2008, one of those times, we had a visitor.

01:49:09.320 --> 01:49:15.920
[Guest]: So he was an uncle's brother, uncle by marriage's brother or something like that.

01:49:15.920 --> 01:49:23.280
[Guest]: Not very liked among the women folk because he was outspoken and many things, but one

01:49:23.280 --> 01:49:26.640
[Guest]: thing he was, was a good cook.

01:49:26.640 --> 01:49:30.880
[Guest]: And when he came home, he said, I'm cooking.

01:49:30.880 --> 01:49:38.640
[Guest]: And he stayed with us for a few days and he, you know, sort of enlisted my support.

01:49:38.640 --> 01:49:43.440
[Guest]: So I had no idea, I didn't, I never chopped vegetables, I didn't think.

01:49:43.440 --> 01:49:48.600
[Guest]: So we went out, he bought me one big chef's knife, which I still have, like a big knife,

01:49:48.600 --> 01:49:52.600
[Guest]: the likes of which our kitchen has never seen, though that kind of a knife.

01:49:52.600 --> 01:49:56.240
[Guest]: And then he taught me how to chop vegetables and cut onions and things like that.

01:49:56.240 --> 01:50:02.440
[Guest]: So we, I would chop vegetables and he would make, he would make things.

01:50:02.440 --> 01:50:08.240
[Guest]: So he made, I remember he made a poached ravas, I think.

01:50:08.240 --> 01:50:11.680
[Guest]: And that was the first time I'd seen anything like that made.

01:50:11.680 --> 01:50:21.680
[Guest]: It was pretty tasty because, you know, eating fish without any masala is revolting to most

01:50:21.680 --> 01:50:22.960
[Guest]: people from my community.

01:50:22.960 --> 01:50:27.760
[Guest]: And this guy actually made it tasty, he squeezed some lemon on that, he put some leaves and

01:50:27.760 --> 01:50:32.080
[Guest]: tomatoes and stuff like that, it was actually tasty.

01:50:32.080 --> 01:50:38.460
[Guest]: And after he left, I started, you know, YouTube wasn't really a big thing back then.

01:50:38.460 --> 01:50:43.640
[Guest]: So I had to figure out, so I kept buying all these recipe books and reverse engineering.

01:50:43.640 --> 01:50:48.240
[Guest]: About five times out of 10, it was inedible, completely inedible, so you had to throw it

01:50:48.240 --> 01:50:49.240
[Guest]: out.

01:50:49.240 --> 01:50:52.760
[Guest]: But on occasion, it turned out very nice.

01:50:52.760 --> 01:50:58.280
[Guest]: And then I started getting interested more and more in different kinds of cuisine.

01:50:58.280 --> 01:51:04.520
[Guest]: One thing about when you actually cook, you then start, so that's why I love Krish Ashok's

01:51:04.520 --> 01:51:11.560
[Guest]: book Masala Lab, because he reduces everything to general principles.

01:51:11.560 --> 01:51:14.720
[Guest]: And you can sort of play around with that.

01:51:14.720 --> 01:51:17.800
[Guest]: He never says anywhere in the book that he is right.

01:51:17.800 --> 01:51:21.160
[Guest]: He just explains what he thinks is happening.

01:51:21.160 --> 01:51:26.800
[Guest]: A lot of it is even now is not settled science, so you'll have more views than one.

01:51:26.800 --> 01:51:28.040
[Guest]: But you get a general idea.

01:51:28.040 --> 01:51:33.120
[Guest]: So what the tadka is, or you know, what you're doing when you're making gravy, or how you

01:51:33.120 --> 01:51:37.160
[Guest]: would cook different meats, and some of that.

01:51:37.160 --> 01:51:41.800
[Guest]: So Ashok used to write this kind of stuff on Twitter even before.

01:51:41.800 --> 01:51:47.960
[Guest]: And even before he started writing, I used to read other people and figure some of that.

01:51:47.960 --> 01:51:56.640
[Guest]: And then when you make it yourself, and it's not always pleasant, sometimes it's rubbish,

01:51:56.640 --> 01:52:02.280
[Guest]: but you learn at every stage, you become more sensitive to what might be going on.

01:52:02.280 --> 01:52:05.680
[Guest]: And you eat yummy stuff elsewhere.

01:52:05.680 --> 01:52:09.880
[Guest]: And then I started appreciating outside food a lot more.

01:52:09.880 --> 01:52:17.200
[Guest]: And I would seek out, you know, unusual eateries, unusual kind of foods.

01:52:17.200 --> 01:52:20.080
[Guest]: And oftentimes, I would be pleasantly surprised.

01:52:20.080 --> 01:52:24.920
[Guest]: There was one I was telling you earlier about, we had gone to Hampi, and we were staying

01:52:24.920 --> 01:52:31.000
[Guest]: in this place called Hospet, and we were staying in a resort, and we had the usual resort fare.

01:52:31.000 --> 01:52:36.000
[Guest]: It was extremely bland and not appetizing at all.

01:52:36.000 --> 01:52:39.440
[Guest]: So my brother-in-law and I, we decided to seek out.

01:52:39.440 --> 01:52:43.320
[Guest]: So we had a driver, and we asked the driver where he ate.

01:52:43.320 --> 01:52:48.320
[Guest]: And he pointed us out to a small hole in the wall, which turned out to be serving a cuisine

01:52:48.320 --> 01:52:50.680
[Guest]: called Saoji.

01:52:50.680 --> 01:52:53.920
[Guest]: And this is indescribably hot.

01:52:53.920 --> 01:53:01.720
[Guest]: It's like, it has like industrial quantities of chili in that, yet it is very flavorful.

01:53:01.720 --> 01:53:08.840
[Guest]: So you put that in your mouth, and your mouth is on fire, and yet you want to have more

01:53:08.840 --> 01:53:09.840
[Guest]: of that.

01:53:09.840 --> 01:53:10.840
[Guest]: That was a novel experience.

01:53:10.840 --> 01:53:13.760
[Guest]: I had never eaten anything as spicy as that.

01:53:13.760 --> 01:53:14.760
[Guest]: That was fun.

01:53:14.760 --> 01:53:26.160
[Guest]: There is one place near Virar, north of Bombay, where there is one eatery which serves poha

01:53:26.160 --> 01:53:27.160
[Guest]: and chicken.

01:53:27.160 --> 01:53:28.960
[Guest]: It's very tasty.

01:53:28.960 --> 01:53:35.000
[Guest]: I mean, I have never eaten anything like that anywhere else, but it's a thing.

01:53:35.000 --> 01:53:41.400
[Guest]: And it has its own little history, how it started, and somebody, here's what I think

01:53:41.400 --> 01:53:47.400
[Guest]: is, someone had a drink or two too much and went off to make chicken pulao, and instead

01:53:47.400 --> 01:53:50.920
[Guest]: of putting rice, he put poha, and it turned out to be nice.

01:53:50.920 --> 01:53:51.920
[Guest]: That's what I believe happened.

01:53:51.920 --> 01:53:55.120
[Guest]: There's some other story that he told me.

01:53:55.120 --> 01:54:01.280
[Guest]: And you start appreciating different kinds of, so some food you don't like, there is

01:54:01.280 --> 01:54:04.580
[Guest]: too much spice in it, or there's too much happening in it.

01:54:04.580 --> 01:54:08.120
[Guest]: But some food, it just appears, it's very complex.

01:54:08.120 --> 01:54:15.600
[Guest]: Just like life, food is very complex, and some kind of food just appeals to you, some

01:54:15.600 --> 01:54:19.960
[Guest]: kind doesn't, and different food appeals to different people.

01:54:19.960 --> 01:54:21.600
[Guest]: It's fascinating.

01:54:21.600 --> 01:54:29.400
[Guest]: So I did a lot of eating out in the last 8 or 10 years, went to different places.

01:54:29.400 --> 01:54:37.760
[Guest]: We went on a trip to Mysore once and sampled 4 or 5 different cuisines in a small, really

01:54:37.760 --> 01:54:42.880
[Guest]: small town, just because it happened to be the confluence of cultures.

01:54:42.880 --> 01:54:50.320
[Guest]: Food says a lot about the culture it comes from as well, and it's very interesting, it's

01:54:50.320 --> 01:54:58.160
[Guest]: very satisfying, it's like a good meal, it's 100 times better than a good drink, is what

01:54:58.160 --> 01:54:59.480
[Guest]: I feel.

01:54:59.480 --> 01:55:03.560
[Amit Varma]: And does it, like you pointed out, that of course you started noticing more nuances of

01:55:03.560 --> 01:55:09.040
[Amit Varma]: food when you would eat out, because you started cooking and all that, but do you feel that

01:55:09.040 --> 01:55:13.720
[Amit Varma]: it made you more mindful of the process of eating in general, like one of the things

01:55:13.720 --> 01:55:18.400
[Amit Varma]: I often find, even when I order something which I absolutely love, like the ramen we

01:55:18.400 --> 01:55:24.600
[Amit Varma]: had today, is that initially I'll enjoy the taste, but then my mind will just drift off.

01:55:24.600 --> 01:55:27.760
[Amit Varma]: So I could really be having any damn thing for the rest of the time, right?

01:55:27.760 --> 01:55:31.920
[Amit Varma]: It's just that initial moment where you're mindful and where you're enjoying it.

01:55:31.920 --> 01:55:37.360
[Amit Varma]: And I find that, and I don't like that about myself, but it always happens with everything

01:55:37.360 --> 01:55:43.160
[Amit Varma]: that I kind of do, because one of my sort of credos in life now is that take joy in

01:55:43.160 --> 01:55:44.160
[Amit Varma]: the small things.

01:55:44.160 --> 01:55:48.320
[Amit Varma]: You know, if you wait for big things to give you joy, the big things may not happen, you

01:55:48.320 --> 01:55:51.800
[Amit Varma]: know, most dreams don't come true, the big things don't happen, there are so many small

01:55:51.800 --> 01:55:55.320
[Amit Varma]: things around which can give you so much joy and food is definitely one of them.

01:55:55.320 --> 01:56:01.280
[Amit Varma]: But I find that I'm not being mindful enough, and it's almost kind of contradictory.

01:56:01.280 --> 01:56:05.520
[Amit Varma]: Do you feel that your mindfulness while eating food has kind of gone up, or do you have to

01:56:05.520 --> 01:56:06.800
[Guest]: keep reminding yourself?

01:56:06.800 --> 01:56:13.960
[Guest]: Yeah, so mindfulness is, so I've had my problems with, like all of us, I'm sure, practically

01:56:13.960 --> 01:56:26.960
[Guest]: all listeners, I think it's a big function of the explosion of, you know, your social

01:56:26.960 --> 01:56:31.480
[Guest]: media and everything, everything is crying out for your attention.

01:56:31.480 --> 01:56:37.280
[Guest]: And it is almost humanly impossible to be immersed in one thing, I've seen this affect

01:56:37.280 --> 01:56:38.280
[Guest]: my reading habit.

01:56:38.280 --> 01:56:45.440
[Guest]: So back in the day, I could read a book in maybe five or six hours, I wouldn't get up,

01:56:45.440 --> 01:56:51.440
[Guest]: I mean, I would pick up a book and like, go cover to cover, I can't remember when the

01:56:51.440 --> 01:56:55.840
[Guest]: last time was when I did it, I just, I'm unable to do it.

01:56:55.840 --> 01:57:03.880
[Guest]: I set a target nowadays, to finish one chapter without sort of attending a call or looking

01:57:03.880 --> 01:57:07.960
[Guest]: at my Twitter, I would force myself to do it.

01:57:07.960 --> 01:57:15.040
[Guest]: So one is the way technology has evolved has started robbing you of your powers of attention.

01:57:15.040 --> 01:57:21.320
[Guest]: There's a book called Deep Work by Cal Newport, I strongly recommend everyone read it and

01:57:21.320 --> 01:57:26.960
[Guest]: you know, if you can't read it, at least there are a few good interviews of his on YouTube

01:57:26.960 --> 01:57:28.680
[Amit Varma]: and you can see that.

01:57:28.680 --> 01:57:33.640
[Amit Varma]: I did an essay on that, which is almost a TLDR of the book, a 2000 word essay, so I

01:57:33.640 --> 01:57:34.640
[Guest]: linked that from the show notes.

01:57:34.640 --> 01:57:35.640
[Guest]: Yeah, that's brilliant.

01:57:35.640 --> 01:57:42.960
[Guest]: That what the TLDR of that is basically, if you want to get anything done, you have to

01:57:42.960 --> 01:57:43.960
[Guest]: switch off.

01:57:43.960 --> 01:57:48.120
[Guest]: So that's the switch off everything else and pursue that, just that thing.

01:57:48.120 --> 01:57:55.480
[Guest]: It works a lot if you want to read something and so one thing that is a big problem is

01:57:55.480 --> 01:58:01.920
[Guest]: you read a summary or watch a summary of something on YouTube and you think that you've got what

01:58:01.920 --> 01:58:07.260
[Guest]: that thing is about, mostly books, and that couldn't be further from the truth.

01:58:07.260 --> 01:58:12.760
[Guest]: Because when you actually read a book, you find yourself arguing with the author or getting

01:58:12.760 --> 01:58:17.680
[Guest]: a lot more nuance or it's more leisurely, you get a chance to sort of play it out in

01:58:17.680 --> 01:58:22.800
[Guest]: your head and rightly or wrongly or whatever it may be, you get your own meaning out of

01:58:22.800 --> 01:58:23.800
[Guest]: that book.

01:58:23.800 --> 01:58:32.200
[Guest]: When you see a summary on YouTube or something, it's that summarizer's point of view which

01:58:32.200 --> 01:58:33.640
[Guest]: is being presented.

01:58:33.640 --> 01:58:38.720
[Guest]: So if you want to read a book or if you want to do any serious thinking, it's imperative

01:58:38.720 --> 01:58:44.680
[Guest]: that you cut yourself off, because it's very difficult.

01:58:44.680 --> 01:58:50.880
[Guest]: In my case, I have to be online, on call, my factory works around the clock, so I leave

01:58:50.880 --> 01:58:56.720
[Guest]: my phone on all the time and if I'm sitting and reading and the phone goes off, I pick

01:58:56.720 --> 01:59:00.360
[Guest]: it up because half the numbers I don't recognize.

01:59:00.360 --> 01:59:06.360
[Guest]: So it could be one of my workers or it could be a neighbor, there could be an accident

01:59:06.360 --> 01:59:11.880
[Guest]: or there could be some emergency, so I cannot pick up the phone.

01:59:11.880 --> 01:59:18.160
[Guest]: So I'm always distracted, but even so, it is possible.

01:59:18.160 --> 01:59:24.040
[Guest]: So you mustn't, unless something is, like in my case, the phone, unless something is

01:59:24.040 --> 01:59:27.840
[Guest]: very demanding of your attention, don't look at Twitter, don't look at Facebook, don't

01:59:27.840 --> 01:59:33.720
[Guest]: look at Instagram, you'll find that experience very rewarding.

01:59:33.720 --> 01:59:40.480
[Guest]: I find that I have to force myself to do this, I'm pretty sure that most of our listeners

01:59:40.480 --> 01:59:42.280
[Guest]: will feel the same.

01:59:42.280 --> 01:59:46.560
[Guest]: What used to come naturally to them a few years ago is no longer natural, they have

01:59:46.560 --> 01:59:48.520
[Amit Varma]: to force themselves to it.

01:59:48.520 --> 01:59:53.920
[Amit Varma]: The advice that I often give people who want to start a reading habit is that initially

01:59:53.920 --> 01:59:54.920
[Amit Varma]: it's always tough.

01:59:54.920 --> 01:59:58.920
[Amit Varma]: Like I was a prolific reader as a kid, then I lost that habit as an adult, then I kind

01:59:58.920 --> 02:00:01.180
[Amit Varma]: of gained it back five, six years ago.

02:00:01.180 --> 02:00:07.000
[Amit Varma]: And the key to remember is once you resume a reading habit, initially, it can get tough,

02:00:07.000 --> 02:00:10.480
[Amit Varma]: your mind will keep wandering all the time and you read 20 minutes and you're like done

02:00:10.480 --> 02:00:11.480
[Amit Varma]: with it.

02:00:11.480 --> 02:00:14.300
[Amit Varma]: But if you just stick with it for a couple of weeks, you'll find that you're getting

02:00:14.300 --> 02:00:19.600
[Amit Varma]: into the groove of reading, so to say, you're reading faster without compromising on depth

02:00:19.600 --> 02:00:24.000
[Amit Varma]: or whatever, you know, and when you're bored, you find yourself reaching for a book instead

02:00:24.000 --> 02:00:26.920
[Amit Varma]: of your cell phone, which is great.

02:00:26.920 --> 02:00:30.720
[Amit Varma]: And by the way, it's kind of fashionable in some circles to give Deepak a bit of flack.

02:00:30.720 --> 02:00:35.120
[Amit Varma]: Because, you know, one argument that I've seen on Twitter is that this is only for privileged

02:00:35.120 --> 02:00:38.320
[Amit Varma]: people and women can't make time for themselves.

02:00:38.320 --> 02:00:39.960
[Amit Varma]: And what are we to do?

02:00:39.960 --> 02:00:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And I find that that criticism is obviously coming from people who haven't read the book.

02:00:44.000 --> 02:00:47.760
[Amit Varma]: Because Newport is not telling you that you have to be able to make three hour chunks

02:00:47.760 --> 02:00:51.440
[Amit Varma]: of time and whatever, whatever, which is, of course, not possible for a lot of people.

02:00:51.440 --> 02:00:55.240
[Amit Varma]: Instead, what Newport does is that he lays out the problem so that you understand it

02:00:55.240 --> 02:00:56.240
[Amit Varma]: better.

02:00:56.240 --> 02:01:00.880
[Amit Varma]: And then he provides a number of different solutions, not all of which require you to

02:01:00.880 --> 02:01:04.960
[Amit Varma]: take out, you know, large parts of large chunks of time to work.

02:01:04.960 --> 02:01:09.220
[Amit Varma]: So I mean, there are four broad ways in which you can kind of, you know, deal with the problem.

02:01:09.220 --> 02:01:15.120
[Amit Varma]: But moving on to sort of another question from the mindfulness topic, and this was,

02:01:15.120 --> 02:01:18.240
[Amit Varma]: of course, being physically mindful of things that you're eating something, you're mindful

02:01:18.240 --> 02:01:21.720
[Amit Varma]: of the taste or you're eating something, and you stay in the moment and you stay in the

02:01:21.720 --> 02:01:22.720
[Amit Varma]: book and all of that.

02:01:22.720 --> 02:01:24.560
[Amit Varma]: That is one kind of mindfulness.

02:01:24.560 --> 02:01:29.820
[Amit Varma]: But another kind of mindfulness is added that I've been thinking of recently is at a different

02:01:29.820 --> 02:01:34.480
[Amit Varma]: level when it comes to other people, like, you know, Immanuel Kant, you know, one of

02:01:34.480 --> 02:01:40.080
[Amit Varma]: his categorical imperatives, one of the versions of his categorical imperative was that never

02:01:40.080 --> 02:01:44.960
[Amit Varma]: treat other people as a means to an end, treat them as an end in itself.

02:01:44.960 --> 02:01:49.720
[Amit Varma]: And I think all of us, most of the time are treating other people as a means to an end,

02:01:49.720 --> 02:01:54.560
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, I call my friend home, but I want his company, you know, they're instrumental

02:01:54.560 --> 02:01:57.680
[Amit Varma]: to my being entertained or my feeling warm or whatever.

02:01:57.680 --> 02:02:02.000
[Amit Varma]: And similarly, you know, we settle into grooves in our relationships.

02:02:02.000 --> 02:02:06.560
[Amit Varma]: And after that, we are just acting out of play, in a sense, according to the grooves.

02:02:06.560 --> 02:02:11.000
[Amit Varma]: And of course, there is conflict and there is friction when opposing visions of a particular

02:02:11.000 --> 02:02:12.560
[Amit Varma]: situation collide.

02:02:12.560 --> 02:02:13.560
[Amit Varma]: And that's a difficult one.

02:02:13.560 --> 02:02:17.000
[Amit Varma]: And that's a different kind of mindfulness where you're mindful that this is a person.

02:02:17.000 --> 02:02:21.840
[Amit Varma]: This is not an instrument to make me feel a particular way.

02:02:21.840 --> 02:02:27.760
[Amit Varma]: Is this something that you kind of think about and in your case, you know, it's interesting

02:02:27.760 --> 02:02:33.280
[Amit Varma]: because one of the, I don't like adjectives, but one of the first adjectives I once used

02:02:33.280 --> 02:02:39.600
[Amit Varma]: for you, I think, to describe you to a friend was Uxorius, if you remember, Uxorius basically

02:02:39.600 --> 02:02:43.840
[Amit Varma]: means a man devoted to his wife or a person devoted to their spouse.

02:02:43.840 --> 02:02:49.440
[Amit Varma]: And yet the point is that both you and your spouse would today be completely different

02:02:49.440 --> 02:02:53.240
[Amit Varma]: people from when you first met, completely different people.

02:02:53.240 --> 02:02:58.120
[Amit Varma]: And there is a subtle kind of negotiation happening there at some level where you get

02:02:58.120 --> 02:02:59.800
[Amit Varma]: used to the person you are.

02:02:59.800 --> 02:03:03.200
[Amit Varma]: And I find that early story about how you were reading out Kotler, I think, to your

02:03:03.200 --> 02:03:09.200
[Amit Varma]: wife or Michael Porter or whoever it was, Porter to Sheila when you were trying to impress

02:03:09.200 --> 02:03:10.720
[Amit Varma]: her in the early days.

02:03:10.720 --> 02:03:13.240
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about that.

02:03:13.240 --> 02:03:15.680
[Amit Varma]: And so what are your kind of thoughts on this?

02:03:15.680 --> 02:03:19.800
[Amit Varma]: Is this something where you feel that you err sometimes, that you need to kind of, are

02:03:19.800 --> 02:03:20.800
[Guest]: there lessons here?

02:03:20.800 --> 02:03:26.960
[Guest]: So one thing, first, very interesting that you should mention about being mindful about

02:03:26.960 --> 02:03:28.880
[Guest]: people.

02:03:28.880 --> 02:03:39.320
[Guest]: I guess at some level we do this to some people, people whom we love, people whom we don't,

02:03:39.320 --> 02:03:45.640
[Guest]: you know, like whom you are with for no specific reason at all.

02:03:45.640 --> 02:03:51.200
[Guest]: Otherwise life is, you know, it's full of, it's always transactional.

02:03:51.200 --> 02:03:57.040
[Guest]: So it's always you expect something, someone else also expects something from you.

02:03:57.040 --> 02:04:01.500
[Guest]: And oftentimes good relations are always mutually beneficial.

02:04:01.500 --> 02:04:07.920
[Guest]: So if both of us have to gain something from each other, that leads to a fruitful relationship.

02:04:07.920 --> 02:04:10.760
[Guest]: What if there is nothing to gain?

02:04:10.760 --> 02:04:19.880
[Guest]: What if neither of us have anything to gain from, you know, does that still mean that

02:04:19.880 --> 02:04:20.880
[Guest]: we should be together?

02:04:20.880 --> 02:04:27.520
[Guest]: And if you see, a lot of really genuine friendships and genuine relationships are based on that,

02:04:27.520 --> 02:04:31.600
[Guest]: when you really don't have anything together, you just are together.

02:04:31.600 --> 02:04:36.200
[Guest]: There is nothing, it's not that you're making each other happy or anything, you just be

02:04:36.200 --> 02:04:37.200
[Guest]: together.

02:04:37.200 --> 02:04:42.320
[Guest]: And for many of us, that would be the relationship with our spouses.

02:04:42.320 --> 02:04:46.120
[Guest]: So when you are newly married, there is a lot of physical interest, all those things

02:04:46.120 --> 02:04:47.480
[Guest]: are there.

02:04:47.480 --> 02:04:54.200
[Guest]: After some time, there is nothing new to discover about your spouse.

02:04:54.200 --> 02:04:58.960
[Guest]: And that's when your real relationship starts.

02:04:58.960 --> 02:05:06.080
[Guest]: And so that's a concept I never thought about before, being mindful with people.

02:05:06.080 --> 02:05:14.360
[Guest]: In my case, with Sheela, Sheela is six years younger than me, and she was almost a child

02:05:14.360 --> 02:05:15.360
[Guest]: when I married her.

02:05:15.360 --> 02:05:21.560
[Guest]: She was 21 years old, which is actually a few days shy of her 21st birthday.

02:05:21.560 --> 02:05:27.480
[Guest]: And I was 26, I think, yeah, 26 or 27.

02:05:27.480 --> 02:05:29.640
[Guest]: She comes from a very different background.

02:05:29.640 --> 02:05:36.040
[Guest]: So in my house, we're very outspoken, and everyone from a very young age, everyone had

02:05:36.040 --> 02:05:37.640
[Guest]: equal democratic rights.

02:05:37.640 --> 02:05:47.000
[Guest]: So I had all the right in the world to speak out my mind, if my parents or any elder uncles

02:05:47.000 --> 02:05:50.640
[Guest]: were around, it wasn't considered bad.

02:05:50.640 --> 02:05:54.920
[Guest]: And in Sheela's family, it was a far more conservative upbringing.

02:05:54.920 --> 02:06:01.080
[Guest]: Women, for example, were, you know, trained not to say anything.

02:06:01.080 --> 02:06:09.120
[Guest]: So the only way they expressed their displeasure or unease with anything was by either remaining

02:06:09.120 --> 02:06:13.320
[Guest]: very quiet or shedding tears.

02:06:13.320 --> 02:06:20.120
[Guest]: And when we got married, we had our first argument, we had a fight about something.

02:06:20.120 --> 02:06:26.560
[Guest]: I mean, I think I drove very rashly or something, I drove recklessly, and she didn't like it,

02:06:26.560 --> 02:06:29.880
[Guest]: and I spoke sharply to her or something like that.

02:06:29.880 --> 02:06:34.560
[Guest]: We had some such thing, and she stopped talking to me for a few days, she didn't say a word.

02:06:34.560 --> 02:06:40.280
[Guest]: And I didn't realize, I didn't realize there was anything amiss.

02:06:40.280 --> 02:06:44.000
[Guest]: And after a few days, she couldn't bear it any longer.

02:06:44.000 --> 02:06:49.720
[Guest]: She couldn't bear the fact that I wasn't understanding there was something amiss.

02:06:49.720 --> 02:06:51.560
[Guest]: So she broke down into tears.

02:06:51.560 --> 02:06:53.320
[Guest]: And this was surprising.

02:06:53.320 --> 02:06:57.600
[Guest]: I grew up with two sisters who are more than outspoken.

02:06:57.600 --> 02:07:02.720
[Guest]: So there was no circumstance in which if they were unhappy, I would not know about it.

02:07:02.720 --> 02:07:04.320
[Guest]: They would yell at me.

02:07:04.320 --> 02:07:06.800
[Guest]: So my mom, so my dad.

02:07:06.800 --> 02:07:13.680
[Guest]: And the first time I see a woman just sobbing quietly, then I asked her what happened.

02:07:13.680 --> 02:07:19.440
[Guest]: And then she told me, you know, that day you said such and such, and I didn't like it.

02:07:19.440 --> 02:07:20.440
[Guest]: And I didn't talk to you.

02:07:20.440 --> 02:07:23.040
[Guest]: I said, you should have told me you didn't like it.

02:07:23.040 --> 02:07:27.880
[Guest]: So for me, it was almost like a clash of cultures.

02:07:27.880 --> 02:07:30.520
[Guest]: In this particular case, it was easy.

02:07:30.520 --> 02:07:33.320
[Guest]: I just encouraged her to be more communicative.

02:07:33.320 --> 02:07:38.400
[Guest]: And then she was, and she changed a lot as a person.

02:07:38.400 --> 02:07:45.120
[Guest]: Once she grew in confidence, once she got the confidence that she could say anything

02:07:45.120 --> 02:07:51.480
[Guest]: to me and get away with it, it was, things were good.

02:07:51.480 --> 02:07:57.840
[Guest]: And then we, as we grew, you know, obviously, any two people live together, you keep having

02:07:57.840 --> 02:07:58.840
[Guest]: conflict.

02:07:58.840 --> 02:08:06.080
[Guest]: So I famously remember telling someone that every, almost every six months, we would have

02:08:06.080 --> 02:08:10.080
[Guest]: a fight in which divorce would be discussed at least once.

02:08:10.080 --> 02:08:12.720
[Guest]: So I could almost plot it.

02:08:12.720 --> 02:08:18.520
[Guest]: So you know, if like it was five months and three weeks, like it would be divorce time

02:08:18.520 --> 02:08:19.520
[Amit Varma]: again.

02:08:19.520 --> 02:08:25.240
[Amit Varma]: So I can guarantee you that's not a unique experience.

02:08:25.240 --> 02:08:31.600
[Guest]: But if two people live together, and if you have communication, you whatever it might

02:08:31.600 --> 02:08:33.760
[Guest]: be, you will resolve it.

02:08:33.760 --> 02:08:34.760
[Guest]: It does.

02:08:34.760 --> 02:08:35.760
[Guest]: That's human nature.

02:08:35.760 --> 02:08:39.920
[Guest]: That's, that's how we are wired as a species.

02:08:39.920 --> 02:08:48.920
[Guest]: And so that, I think was my, you know, I'm very proud that I encouraged Sheila to be

02:08:48.920 --> 02:08:50.760
[Guest]: more communicative.

02:08:50.760 --> 02:08:55.720
[Guest]: And once she did that, she sort of came into her own as a person.

02:08:55.720 --> 02:08:57.840
[Guest]: She's a very friendly person.

02:08:57.840 --> 02:09:05.560
[Guest]: So before this, she was very hesitant to make new friends.

02:09:05.560 --> 02:09:11.080
[Guest]: And you know, as time passes, as she grew more comfortable, she is, you know, she makes

02:09:11.080 --> 02:09:13.880
[Guest]: friends very easily.

02:09:13.880 --> 02:09:24.920
[Guest]: What she made me realize is that I, I was, so I had this intellectual arrogance that

02:09:24.920 --> 02:09:31.640
[Guest]: I knew everything, because I was usually the cleverest guy in the room, right from my school

02:09:31.640 --> 02:09:37.640
[Guest]: days, very clever, understand everything, read a lot of books, can speak English, very

02:09:37.640 --> 02:09:43.520
[Guest]: good at, you know, sort of pulling out a quote, a clever quote from Shakespeare or Woodhouse

02:09:43.520 --> 02:09:49.080
[Guest]: or something like that, win the day, win the argument and things like that.

02:09:49.080 --> 02:09:57.360
[Guest]: And I oftentimes wouldn't sense even that other people who are not as communicative

02:09:57.360 --> 02:10:01.280
[Guest]: as me had something to say and weren't able to say it.

02:10:01.280 --> 02:10:09.120
[Guest]: So I don't know how far I've progressed along, but I like to think that now I realize that

02:10:09.120 --> 02:10:13.640
[Guest]: just because someone is not saying something does not mean that they don't have anything

02:10:13.640 --> 02:10:14.920
[Guest]: to say.

02:10:14.920 --> 02:10:19.960
[Guest]: And it's very difficult, very important to get that out of them, even if it's difficult

02:10:19.960 --> 02:10:21.600
[Guest]: for those people.

02:10:21.600 --> 02:10:23.640
[Guest]: And it makes a life richer.

02:10:23.640 --> 02:10:30.000
[Guest]: So one thing that I learned was communication skills and intelligence are not correlated.

02:10:30.000 --> 02:10:39.360
[Guest]: So I have found some really clever and intelligent people who are not really able to communicate

02:10:39.360 --> 02:10:40.360
[Guest]: at all.

02:10:40.360 --> 02:10:41.440
[Guest]: So that was a finding.

02:10:41.440 --> 02:10:46.480
[Guest]: I wouldn't have, because I just equated communication and intelligence.

02:10:46.480 --> 02:10:48.440
[Guest]: So if you can't communicate, you are dumb.

02:10:48.440 --> 02:10:50.080
[Guest]: That was my earlier thing.

02:10:50.080 --> 02:10:54.120
[Guest]: Over a period of time, I realized that that is not the case.

02:10:54.120 --> 02:10:56.720
[Guest]: I don't know how your experience is.

02:10:56.720 --> 02:10:58.480
[Guest]: You are pretty much in the same boat.

02:10:58.480 --> 02:11:04.160
[Amit Varma]: No, I'm in a worse boat because I'm in a worse boat because I think, you know, it took me

02:11:04.160 --> 02:11:07.680
[Amit Varma]: many years into my adulthood, which is why I don't like the young me.

02:11:07.680 --> 02:11:11.400
[Amit Varma]: When I think of me in my twenties and people I knew then are still in touch on Facebook

02:11:11.400 --> 02:11:12.400
[Amit Varma]: or whatever.

02:11:12.400 --> 02:11:14.020
[Amit Varma]: And I think to myself that why?

02:11:14.020 --> 02:11:16.640
[Amit Varma]: Because that guy was such an obnoxious prick.

02:11:16.640 --> 02:11:21.080
[Amit Varma]: But I realized looking back, and these are things that you realize only in hindsight

02:11:21.080 --> 02:11:27.280
[Amit Varma]: if at all, that I picked up two things that makes me cringe when I think back on them

02:11:27.280 --> 02:11:28.280
[Amit Varma]: from my parents.

02:11:28.280 --> 02:11:34.200
[Amit Varma]: One was, I think, an intellectual arrogance, which you mentioned from my dad, because again,

02:11:34.200 --> 02:11:38.520
[Amit Varma]: you know, as a kid, like I, you know, read all of Shakespeare at 10 and I was just reading

02:11:38.520 --> 02:11:44.560
[Amit Varma]: very voraciously and that that makes you think the world of yourself and my dad was similar

02:11:44.560 --> 02:11:45.560
[Amit Varma]: in a sense.

02:11:45.560 --> 02:11:49.240
[Amit Varma]: And I picked up this massive intellectual arrogance that took years and years to kind

02:11:49.240 --> 02:11:50.240
[Amit Varma]: of go away.

02:11:50.240 --> 02:11:54.640
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, and just looking back, I wonder how I kind of navigated through society with

02:11:54.640 --> 02:11:55.640
[Amit Varma]: that kind of arrogance.

02:11:55.640 --> 02:11:59.440
[Amit Varma]: And from my mom, I think I picked up this massive social arrogance that, you know, we

02:11:59.440 --> 02:12:01.120
[Amit Varma]: are a certain class of people.

02:12:01.120 --> 02:12:05.160
[Amit Varma]: And my dad was an IAS officer and obviously, you know, privileged upbringing and all living

02:12:05.160 --> 02:12:08.320
[Amit Varma]: in bungalows in my childhood, though never since, obviously.

02:12:08.320 --> 02:12:11.400
[Amit Varma]: But so there was that and it takes a long time for that to go.

02:12:11.400 --> 02:12:17.080
[Amit Varma]: And when that goes, you kind of realize that, you know, that you lost so much by being like

02:12:17.080 --> 02:12:18.080
[Guest]: that.

02:12:18.080 --> 02:12:20.200
[Guest]: Yeah, that's so true.

02:12:20.200 --> 02:12:27.560
[Guest]: You realize you are the bigger because you have your arrogance has created these barriers.

02:12:27.560 --> 02:12:32.200
[Guest]: You are not listening and you become so forbidding that other people do not want to speak to

02:12:32.200 --> 02:12:35.120
[Guest]: you or they're intimidated by your presence.

02:12:35.120 --> 02:12:37.680
[Guest]: There can be nothing sadder than that, actually.

02:12:37.680 --> 02:12:38.680
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:12:38.680 --> 02:12:45.240
[Guest]: So that that was one of the yeah, I'm happy to meet, I know that someone else also has

02:12:45.240 --> 02:12:46.240
[Guest]: gone through that.

02:12:46.240 --> 02:12:50.360
[Guest]: But it took me a long time to figure that out.

02:12:50.360 --> 02:12:55.920
[Guest]: It's probably still there at some level, it's just, it's just who we are, right?

02:12:55.920 --> 02:13:02.480
[Guest]: We are basically very arrogant and selfish people.

02:13:02.480 --> 02:13:08.960
[Guest]: But as you grow older, I think you sort of grudgingly acknowledge that you're not as

02:13:08.960 --> 02:13:11.280
[Guest]: great as you think you are.

02:13:11.280 --> 02:13:20.720
[Guest]: And other people are actually far, far more, you know, smart and clever and talented than

02:13:20.720 --> 02:13:24.480
[Guest]: you ever suspected they would.

02:13:24.480 --> 02:13:29.080
[Amit Varma]: And I think the other sort of sort of way of thinking about this is that even if you

02:13:29.080 --> 02:13:33.240
[Amit Varma]: are smarter than others, even if you're, you know, better than so many, like, it doesn't

02:13:33.240 --> 02:13:34.240
[Amit Varma]: make a difference.

02:13:34.240 --> 02:13:39.920
[Amit Varma]: Like, I see so much of what happens around me in society and maybe exacerbated by social

02:13:39.920 --> 02:13:40.920
[Amit Varma]: media.

02:13:40.920 --> 02:13:45.880
[Amit Varma]: There is this constant one upmanship, there is this and which, you know, normally is by

02:13:45.880 --> 02:13:51.240
[Amit Varma]: putting other people down, or there is a quest for constant validation.

02:13:51.240 --> 02:13:54.000
[Amit Varma]: And these two are kind of colliding all the time, like if there's something that I really

02:13:54.000 --> 02:13:58.960
[Amit Varma]: hate about social media, it's about how, you know, you're shitting on people all the time.

02:13:58.960 --> 02:14:04.320
[Amit Varma]: And I see that even on some WhatsApp groups, you know, we may both be part of something

02:14:04.320 --> 02:14:05.320
[Amit Varma]: like that.

02:14:05.320 --> 02:14:06.320
[Amit Varma]: I mean, we don't do that.

02:14:06.320 --> 02:14:10.640
[Amit Varma]: But we may be part of a group like that, where, you know, it's all the time you're shitting

02:14:10.640 --> 02:14:11.640
[Amit Varma]: on someone.

02:14:11.640 --> 02:14:13.720
[Amit Varma]: And it's like endless quote tweets.

02:14:13.720 --> 02:14:18.640
[Amit Varma]: Like for me, the quote tweet is just the rudest thing ever, unless you're praising someone,

02:14:18.640 --> 02:14:19.640
[Amit Varma]: in which case is fine.

02:14:19.640 --> 02:14:23.000
[Amit Varma]: You're praising someone or you're citing someone's piece and saying something.

02:14:23.000 --> 02:14:27.080
[Amit Varma]: But a lot of the time, it's just mockery, you're not adding anything to any conversation.

02:14:27.080 --> 02:14:31.560
[Amit Varma]: You're just mocking someone for having different values than you, or maybe for not understanding

02:14:31.560 --> 02:14:32.560
[Amit Varma]: something enough.

02:14:32.560 --> 02:14:36.920
[Amit Varma]: And I think at the end of the day, all of this shit is an accident, your intelligence,

02:14:36.920 --> 02:14:38.400
[Amit Varma]: what you've achieved in life, it's an accident.

02:14:38.400 --> 02:14:43.280
[Guest]: That's a very good point because, yes, you know, some people are smarter, some people

02:14:43.280 --> 02:14:44.280
[Guest]: are less smart.

02:14:44.280 --> 02:14:47.760
[Guest]: It's just like some people are taller and other people aren't just as tall.

02:14:47.760 --> 02:14:51.040
[Guest]: It's just variations.

02:14:51.040 --> 02:14:54.440
[Guest]: It should not, it really doesn't mean anything at all.

02:14:54.440 --> 02:14:55.760
[Guest]: It really doesn't.

02:14:55.760 --> 02:15:02.480
[Guest]: And actually, as someone pointed out, if you compare the difference between the dumbest

02:15:02.480 --> 02:15:09.840
[Guest]: person and smartest person, it's really not much as, you know, if you compare it from

02:15:09.840 --> 02:15:18.600
[Guest]: a baseline of, you know, from another animal, from, let us say, a chimpanzee to a human

02:15:18.600 --> 02:15:20.520
[Guest]: being, that delta is really big.

02:15:20.520 --> 02:15:25.520
[Guest]: So in percentage terms, that little ripple doesn't matter at all.

02:15:25.520 --> 02:15:29.760
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, that's a good perspective because I think, you know, basically we are all, we

02:15:29.760 --> 02:15:34.080
[Amit Varma]: are actually identical and everything is kind of circumstance and a circumstance in two

02:15:34.080 --> 02:15:35.080
[Amit Varma]: ways.

02:15:35.080 --> 02:15:36.920
[Amit Varma]: One is a circumstance of your genes, which is luck.

02:15:36.920 --> 02:15:41.440
[Amit Varma]: And the other is a circumstance of your circumstances, as it were, what a convoluted way, which is

02:15:41.440 --> 02:15:42.440
[Amit Varma]: also luck.

02:15:42.440 --> 02:15:47.320
[Amit Varma]: You know, like I love Steven Pinker's quote about, you know, nature gives you knobs, nurture

02:15:47.320 --> 02:15:48.960
[Amit Varma]: turns them.

02:15:48.960 --> 02:15:50.240
[Amit Varma]: And they're both kind of luck.

02:15:50.240 --> 02:15:55.200
[Amit Varma]: And that's one of the big lessons I kind of got as a poker player is that realizing that

02:15:55.200 --> 02:16:00.880
[Amit Varma]: it's not just in poker where you have to adjust for the level of luck, because obviously though

02:16:00.880 --> 02:16:04.280
[Amit Varma]: it's a game of skill, the quantum of luck is much higher than in other sports, but in

02:16:04.280 --> 02:16:05.520
[Amit Varma]: life itself.

02:16:05.520 --> 02:16:09.760
[Amit Varma]: And so many people get, you know, they let success get to their heads and they become

02:16:09.760 --> 02:16:14.600
[Amit Varma]: arrogant, or even the circumstance of their birth, get to their heads, I am so proud of

02:16:14.600 --> 02:16:16.640
[Amit Varma]: being so and so proud to be a Hindu.

02:16:16.640 --> 02:16:17.640
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:16:17.640 --> 02:16:18.640
[Guest]: What did you do?

02:16:18.640 --> 02:16:21.000
[Guest]: You know, what do you do to become a Hindu?

02:16:21.000 --> 02:16:24.440
[Amit Varma]: You know, if someone who is proud to be a Hindu today, it's a circumstance of birth

02:16:24.440 --> 02:16:30.120
[Amit Varma]: that they are a Hindu in India, what if they were, you know, you know, something else somewhere,

02:16:30.120 --> 02:16:34.520
[Amit Varma]: you know, what is the damn difference, but anyway, that's, that's kind of taking us into

02:16:34.520 --> 02:16:35.520
[Amit Varma]: different places.

02:16:35.520 --> 02:16:38.920
[Amit Varma]: But then, so there's the other thing I mentioned on social media, people do two things.

02:16:38.920 --> 02:16:43.140
[Amit Varma]: One is this constant upmanship, and which probably comes from a deep fundamental insecurity.

02:16:43.140 --> 02:16:48.360
[Amit Varma]: But there is also the quest for validation, which I think comes from again, one of the

02:16:48.360 --> 02:16:52.600
[Amit Varma]: fundamental anxieties that I learned to tackle, and I'm still learning to tackle, which is

02:16:52.600 --> 02:16:56.840
[Amit Varma]: hardwired into us, which is the anxiety of what other people will think of you.

02:16:56.840 --> 02:17:00.320
[Amit Varma]: And you know, so when I talk to my writing students, when I give my last webinar, I keep

02:17:00.320 --> 02:17:05.840
[Amit Varma]: pointing out that this anxiety is actually pointless, because no one's thinking of you.

02:17:05.840 --> 02:17:09.720
[Amit Varma]: Everyone's got their head up their own ass, you know, no one is like taking screenshots

02:17:09.720 --> 02:17:13.840
[Amit Varma]: of every little thing you write so that they can come back five years later and say, look

02:17:13.840 --> 02:17:15.840
[Amit Varma]: what a bad sentence you wrote.

02:17:15.840 --> 02:17:20.760
[Amit Varma]: And yet this is a difficult anxiety to get by what other people think of you.

02:17:20.760 --> 02:17:25.400
[Amit Varma]: So is this something that you've kind of faced and are there other anxieties?

02:17:25.400 --> 02:17:29.800
[Amit Varma]: If you were to think back on things that you've been anxious about, insecure about, what would

02:17:29.800 --> 02:17:31.200
[Guest]: you kind of look at?

02:17:31.200 --> 02:17:39.320
[Guest]: Yeah, one thing that somehow has dogged me for a long period of time is acceptance, right?

02:17:39.320 --> 02:17:45.760
[Guest]: So somehow, you feel whenever you're in a group, you feel obliged to be accepted in

02:17:45.760 --> 02:17:46.800
[Guest]: that group.

02:17:46.800 --> 02:17:56.360
[Guest]: So oftentimes, what it means is, you say things which go against your core value, or you refrain

02:17:56.360 --> 02:17:59.840
[Guest]: from saying things when you should actually say them.

02:17:59.840 --> 02:18:05.440
[Guest]: So excessive politeness just in order to fit into the group.

02:18:05.440 --> 02:18:10.200
[Guest]: In my case, that definitely comes from, I don't know why it should be true, why it should

02:18:10.200 --> 02:18:16.520
[Guest]: be so, because I'm definitely among the privileged, I mean, my dad was a successful practitioner,

02:18:16.520 --> 02:18:22.680
[Guest]: we had, you know, socially acceptable, there's absolutely no reason why I should be anxious

02:18:22.680 --> 02:18:25.000
[Guest]: about being accepted in a group.

02:18:25.000 --> 02:18:33.320
[Guest]: Sheila often points out that I am not unlike a, you know, so when you go to someone's house

02:18:33.320 --> 02:18:39.800
[Guest]: and their dog will come out and they're very happy to see you and, you know, so we have

02:18:39.800 --> 02:18:44.040
[Guest]: a dog in the factory and we feed and every time one of us goes there because we feed

02:18:44.040 --> 02:18:53.280
[Guest]: the dog, he's, you know, he's like, you can see that he's so, he just wants to be petted

02:18:53.280 --> 02:18:54.280
[Guest]: by you.

02:18:54.280 --> 02:18:57.040
[Guest]: He just wants to be, you know, good book.

02:18:57.040 --> 02:19:00.960
[Guest]: And actually, Sheila has a secret name for that particular dog.

02:19:00.960 --> 02:19:06.960
[Guest]: She calls him Naren because he's exactly like how I behave when I'm in groups.

02:19:06.960 --> 02:19:10.040
[Guest]: That's a private joke between the two of us.

02:19:10.040 --> 02:19:11.920
[Guest]: But this is what happens.

02:19:11.920 --> 02:19:17.800
[Guest]: So we let anxieties, I try to consciously be away from that.

02:19:17.800 --> 02:19:25.560
[Guest]: And but oftentimes, I don't have, I pass it off as kindness, why do I want to hurt other

02:19:25.560 --> 02:19:36.600
[Guest]: people's feelings and so, but yeah, we do tend to be disproportionately worried about

02:19:36.600 --> 02:19:38.120
[Guest]: being accepted in groups.

02:19:38.120 --> 02:19:44.440
[Guest]: And I have found that even if your views, if my views are not in line with other people,

02:19:44.440 --> 02:19:50.920
[Guest]: it's not that the group throws me out or rejects me, it's as long as you're not actively harassing

02:19:50.920 --> 02:19:52.360
[Guest]: other people, it's fine.

02:19:52.360 --> 02:19:57.680
[Guest]: I mean, most groups do accommodate diverse views.

02:19:57.680 --> 02:20:04.600
[Guest]: So we should try to be more true to ourselves, it's more satisfying.

02:20:04.600 --> 02:20:10.360
[Guest]: You have an internal code, and you must be true to that.

02:20:10.360 --> 02:20:13.280
[Guest]: I don't know how your experience is.

02:20:13.280 --> 02:20:24.040
[Guest]: You have been, I know, you have been very daring in sort of disagreeing or sort of making

02:20:24.040 --> 02:20:32.160
[Guest]: your views known, even when you know that those views are not going to be well received.

02:20:32.160 --> 02:20:36.360
[Guest]: You never shy away from that, at least as far as I've known you.

02:20:36.360 --> 02:20:37.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:20:37.360 --> 02:20:38.920
[Amit Varma]: And that's more an impulse kind of thing.

02:20:38.920 --> 02:20:43.280
[Amit Varma]: Like, you know, there's that old XKCD cartoon of, you know, someone is wrong on the internet.

02:20:43.280 --> 02:20:47.520
[Unknown]: The wife asks her husband, you know, come and sleep and he's like, no, someone is wrong

02:20:47.520 --> 02:20:48.520
[Amit Varma]: on the internet.

02:20:48.520 --> 02:20:52.400
[Amit Varma]: And, and there's a later version of that, I think, which came out 10 years after that,

02:20:52.400 --> 02:20:58.200
[Amit Varma]: which is about how this guy, you know, discovers sort of, I'll try and link to both of them

02:20:58.200 --> 02:21:04.360
[Amit Varma]: about how this guy discovers that there's a view that he disagrees with really strongly,

02:21:04.360 --> 02:21:06.840
[Amit Varma]: but he hasn't actually seen that view yet.

02:21:06.840 --> 02:21:10.880
[Amit Varma]: So he looks for someone who's expressed that view so he can shit on that person.

02:21:10.880 --> 02:21:14.560
[Amit Varma]: But I mean, I don't, I don't come close to doing either of those two.

02:21:14.560 --> 02:21:17.680
[Amit Varma]: But the point is, sometimes somebody will just say something stupid, like someone will

02:21:17.680 --> 02:21:24.720
[Amit Varma]: say homeopathy works, and something just happens that, you know, I kind of lose it, or, you

02:21:24.720 --> 02:21:25.880
[Amit Varma]: know, other random things.

02:21:25.880 --> 02:21:31.720
[Amit Varma]: And over time, it's really futile, that on the one hand, okay, if you are someone who

02:21:31.720 --> 02:21:36.320
[Amit Varma]: is taken seriously by a lot of people, then you should kind of say what you feel.

02:21:36.320 --> 02:21:37.320
[Amit Varma]: That's kind of your job.

02:21:37.320 --> 02:21:41.040
[Amit Varma]: At the very least, you should, whatever you say should be what you feel.

02:21:41.040 --> 02:21:42.040
[Amit Varma]: Don't do any posturing.

02:21:42.040 --> 02:21:43.720
[Amit Varma]: I try to avoid the posturing.

02:21:43.720 --> 02:21:48.440
[Amit Varma]: But I just think, but, you know, but sometimes in private groups also, I just kind of, so

02:21:48.440 --> 02:21:52.160
[Amit Varma]: I'm trying to sort of discipline myself to just chill.

02:21:52.160 --> 02:21:58.720
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I'm more and more, I'm kind of coming to the conclusion that nothing is going to

02:21:58.720 --> 02:21:59.720
[Guest]: change.

02:21:59.720 --> 02:22:00.720
[Guest]: That's very true.

02:22:00.720 --> 02:22:04.520
[Guest]: But I'm in, so I'm like the diametrical opposite of you.

02:22:04.520 --> 02:22:13.320
[Guest]: So you would tend to, you know, risk hurting someone else's feeling.

02:22:13.320 --> 02:22:17.960
[Guest]: Because you have to say that what you're saying, I don't agree with.

02:22:17.960 --> 02:22:21.400
[Guest]: And here are the reasons why I don't agree with it.

02:22:21.400 --> 02:22:22.400
[Guest]: You're always civil.

02:22:22.400 --> 02:22:27.760
[Guest]: I mean, it's, you'll never, for example, you'll never, you'll never attack the person.

02:22:27.760 --> 02:22:30.600
[Guest]: You'll never say that, hey, Naren, you're an idiot.

02:22:30.600 --> 02:22:31.600
[Guest]: No.

02:22:31.600 --> 02:22:34.920
[Guest]: You'll say, these arguments that you're making sound wrong to me.

02:22:34.920 --> 02:22:36.680
[Guest]: And these are the reasons why.

02:22:36.680 --> 02:22:42.640
[Guest]: And yet, if I'm really invested in those ideas, the very fact that you have pointed that out

02:22:42.640 --> 02:22:44.480
[Guest]: to me is an affront.

02:22:44.480 --> 02:22:46.720
[Guest]: And I'm going to attack you as a person.

02:22:46.720 --> 02:22:52.400
[Guest]: So I'm going to say you are a fat, slob, ugly, which you're not, okay.

02:22:52.400 --> 02:22:53.400
[Guest]: But just saying.

02:22:53.400 --> 02:22:56.760
[Amit Varma]: No, I mean, the fatness is undeniable.

02:22:56.760 --> 02:22:58.200
[Amit Varma]: The ugly is subjective.

02:22:58.200 --> 02:22:59.200
[Amit Varma]: Slob is true.

02:22:59.200 --> 02:23:05.520
[Guest]: And I would say, I would think that and I would never talk to Amit again.

02:23:05.520 --> 02:23:08.000
[Guest]: So you probably sense that.

02:23:08.000 --> 02:23:15.680
[Guest]: But you've said that regardless, you know, when you pointed out that I'm wrong, you've

02:23:15.680 --> 02:23:23.200
[Guest]: been prepared to lose that relationship, and I'm the other extreme, I will not say what

02:23:23.200 --> 02:23:30.040
