[Guest]: And I'm sure a mindful person, you know, for a mindful person, that wouldn't.

02:37:17.360 --> 02:37:21.320
[Amit Varma]: It wouldn't, but it would also be tough, because it's a question of attentional capacity, in

02:37:21.320 --> 02:37:25.120
[Amit Varma]: the sense that, like, this is something I realized while podcasting, that why do, how

02:37:25.120 --> 02:37:28.360
[Amit Varma]: can people listen at double speed or 3x speed so easily?

02:37:28.360 --> 02:37:33.000
[Amit Varma]: And the reason is the brain can comprehend words spoken at 500 words a minute or more,

02:37:33.000 --> 02:37:38.200
[Amit Varma]: while we actually speak at, you know, 150 to 200 words a minute.

02:37:38.200 --> 02:37:42.360
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, you know, when you're listening to someone speaking at that horrifyingly slow

02:37:42.360 --> 02:37:45.200
[Amit Varma]: speed, like, I can't listen to myself at normal speed, it's torture.

02:37:45.200 --> 02:37:46.200
[Guest]: Same with me.

02:37:46.200 --> 02:37:52.800
[Guest]: I, you know, in fact, I whenever I listen to your podcast, I listen to it at 1.5x, that's

02:37:52.800 --> 02:37:55.000
[Guest]: my standard thing.

02:37:55.000 --> 02:37:56.640
[Guest]: And you sound normal.

02:37:56.640 --> 02:37:57.640
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:37:57.640 --> 02:38:02.080
[Guest]: And the other day, I listened to one of your podcasts, and accidentally it happened to

02:38:02.080 --> 02:38:03.080
[Guest]: me.

02:38:03.080 --> 02:38:08.040
[Guest]: It's a new podcasting app, I think, and it almost sounds that you're intoxicated or something

02:38:08.040 --> 02:38:09.040
[Amit Varma]: like that.

02:38:09.040 --> 02:38:10.040
[Amit Varma]: Retarded.

02:38:10.040 --> 02:38:11.040
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:38:11.040 --> 02:38:15.600
[Guest]: But now, I mean, we are face to face now, and it, it doesn't sound odd at all.

02:38:15.600 --> 02:38:20.600
[Guest]: But I'm pretty sure that when I listen to this podcast, when it comes out, I will have

02:38:20.600 --> 02:38:22.480
[Guest]: to listen to it at 1.5x, I won't be able to listen.

02:38:22.480 --> 02:38:23.480
[Amit Varma]: The exact same thing.

02:38:23.480 --> 02:38:26.920
[Amit Varma]: So some of my writing students, when they, you know, the first webinar of the course,

02:38:26.920 --> 02:38:31.240
[Amit Varma]: they pointed out that you seem to be speaking so slowly, because they're just not kind of

02:38:31.240 --> 02:38:32.240
[Amit Varma]: used to it.

02:38:32.240 --> 02:38:33.360
[Amit Varma]: But that's the point.

02:38:33.360 --> 02:38:36.600
[Amit Varma]: That's why when you're talking to someone, their attention can wander, because only a

02:38:36.600 --> 02:38:40.400
[Amit Varma]: part of the brain needs to listen to you to comprehend, the rest of it can do whatever

02:38:40.400 --> 02:38:41.880
[Amit Varma]: the hell it wants.

02:38:41.880 --> 02:38:46.440
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, the mind wanders a lot, which is why, you know, listening at like, I listen

02:38:46.440 --> 02:38:50.400
[Amit Varma]: to everything at 2x, and some things at 2.5, or whatever, sometimes it depends on the accent

02:38:50.400 --> 02:38:56.000
[Amit Varma]: and how will you get it, but I would never listen to my podcast at less than 2x.

02:38:56.000 --> 02:38:59.840
[Amit Varma]: But the point is, it's normal at that speed for me, you know, otherwise, the mind will

02:38:59.840 --> 02:39:04.520
[Amit Varma]: wander, you know, listening at a higher speed can actually mean that you kind of retain

02:39:04.520 --> 02:39:07.120
[Amit Varma]: more and take in more and all of that.

02:39:07.120 --> 02:39:08.400
[Amit Varma]: So tell me another thing.

02:39:08.400 --> 02:39:12.840
[Amit Varma]: So you know, you were born in the 60s, grew up in the 70s and 80s, and all of that, and

02:39:12.840 --> 02:39:16.000
[Amit Varma]: a lot of our experiences, kind of a shared experience.

02:39:16.000 --> 02:39:19.160
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, and I've kind of grown up reading books.

02:39:19.160 --> 02:39:22.440
[Amit Varma]: And once in a while, you watch some TV, or you go out and watch a movie, but you're really

02:39:22.440 --> 02:39:23.640
[Amit Varma]: reading books.

02:39:23.640 --> 02:39:27.600
[Amit Varma]: And you're listening to music sometimes and all of that, not today, that entire experience

02:39:27.600 --> 02:39:28.600
[Amit Varma]: has changed.

02:39:28.600 --> 02:39:33.320
[Amit Varma]: Like, I find that number one, you know, we no longer need to think in terms of formats.

02:39:33.320 --> 02:39:36.920
[Amit Varma]: Like earlier, if you wanted to be a writer, you're going to write an article that's 800

02:39:36.920 --> 02:39:40.880
[Amit Varma]: words, you're going to write a book that's 100,000, a short story is whatever, you know,

02:39:40.880 --> 02:39:42.480
[Amit Varma]: you've got these fixed formats.

02:39:42.480 --> 02:39:47.160
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, for audio, you know, if you want to do audio back in the day, you know, radio

02:39:47.160 --> 02:39:51.720
[Amit Varma]: has this fixed formats, TV has this fixed formats, either you're a half an hour serial

02:39:51.720 --> 02:39:57.320
[Amit Varma]: episode, or you're a 90 minute Hollywood film, or you're a three hour Bollywood film, everything

02:39:57.320 --> 02:39:58.320
[Amit Varma]: has a format.

02:39:58.320 --> 02:40:02.200
[Amit Varma]: Today, I find as a creator, and you're also a creator, obviously, you're a podcaster,

02:40:02.200 --> 02:40:06.480
[Amit Varma]: and we'll discuss your future later, because we must talk about your future, because I'm

02:40:06.480 --> 02:40:09.160
[Amit Varma]: also a part of it, I've now realized.

02:40:09.160 --> 02:40:13.360
[Amit Varma]: And today, it has completely sort of changing, like, what are your thoughts on this?

02:40:13.360 --> 02:40:17.880
[Amit Varma]: And what are the changes that you've seen in the things that you consume, like a lot

02:40:17.880 --> 02:40:21.720
[Amit Varma]: of people now who don't have time to read books, because lives are busy.

02:40:21.720 --> 02:40:25.200
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, everybody doesn't have the privilege to be able to carve out hours in

02:40:25.200 --> 02:40:26.480
[Amit Varma]: a day to read.

02:40:26.480 --> 02:40:29.880
[Amit Varma]: People listen to audiobooks, or will listen to podcasts.

02:40:29.880 --> 02:40:33.280
[Amit Varma]: Because the point is, you want knowledge wherever you're getting it from, you want stimulation

02:40:33.280 --> 02:40:37.000
[Amit Varma]: from your brain, wherever you're getting it from, you know, I find a good podcast is a

02:40:37.000 --> 02:40:41.120
[Amit Varma]: perfectly valid way to get it, which wasn't, you know, there when I was a kid.

02:40:41.120 --> 02:40:43.080
[Guest]: So what are your kind of thoughts on this?

02:40:43.080 --> 02:40:50.560
[Guest]: So one, one is, I've, I've, you know, I used to be an inveterate readers, I'd read anything.

02:40:50.560 --> 02:40:52.320
[Guest]: And I had to be reading all the time.

02:40:52.320 --> 02:40:58.240
[Guest]: I used to read my, my mom used to make fun of me, I used to read while I could not eat

02:40:58.240 --> 02:40:59.240
[Guest]: without reading.

02:40:59.240 --> 02:41:02.160
[Amit Varma]: So I'd have a book, I'd read something.

02:41:02.160 --> 02:41:06.920
[Guest]: And they would, you know, my sisters would do that while I'm eating, while I'm reading,

02:41:06.920 --> 02:41:11.680
[Guest]: they'll pull my plate away, and I'll actually put my hand out and there'll be something,

02:41:11.680 --> 02:41:12.680
[Guest]: you know, missing.

02:41:12.680 --> 02:41:17.360
[Guest]: And I look up and then all of them are laughing, they made a fool out of me.

02:41:17.360 --> 02:41:24.400
[Guest]: And now I find myself not reading nearly like a 10th as much.

02:41:24.400 --> 02:41:28.120
[Guest]: But so the biggest change has been YouTube.

02:41:28.120 --> 02:41:34.520
[Guest]: So I've been I've been consuming content a lot on YouTube, it started with the math video.

02:41:34.520 --> 02:41:40.800
[Guest]: So I'm a mechanical engineer, and a lot of mechanical engineering is calculus and a lot

02:41:40.800 --> 02:41:42.640
[Guest]: of calculus is very hard to visualize.

02:41:42.640 --> 02:41:47.680
[Guest]: Now we, we've done that, and we don't really use calculus in day to day manufacturing,

02:41:47.680 --> 02:41:49.880
[Guest]: but it's something which always interested me.

02:41:49.880 --> 02:41:56.240
[Guest]: But a lot of a lot of calculus, for example, there are things called differential equations.

02:41:56.240 --> 02:42:00.920
[Guest]: Differential equations are basically equations that describe some physical phenomenon, you

02:42:00.920 --> 02:42:05.880
[Guest]: just put it into that equation, and they are all in the form of derivatives.

02:42:05.880 --> 02:42:10.160
[Guest]: And if you want solution, you have to solve those differential equations, and they're

02:42:10.160 --> 02:42:12.240
[Guest]: notoriously hard to solve.

02:42:12.240 --> 02:42:18.600
[Guest]: But there are techniques, there are things called Laplace transform, Fourier transform,

02:42:18.600 --> 02:42:25.120
[Guest]: they, they help you solve a lot of these things by, you know, making transformations.

02:42:25.120 --> 02:42:29.520
[Guest]: For example, Laplace transform transforms everything into the frequency domain from

02:42:29.520 --> 02:42:34.120
[Guest]: the time domain where, you know, you can just add things algebraically, you can solve things

02:42:34.120 --> 02:42:38.760
[Guest]: algebraically, and then you transform it back into the time domain, and you get your solution.

02:42:38.760 --> 02:42:44.400
[Guest]: All of this we have done, and not understood what the hell it was.

02:42:44.400 --> 02:42:50.440
[Guest]: Many many many years later, I find this channel on YouTube called 3blue1brown, which does

02:42:50.440 --> 02:42:56.680
[Guest]: such a wonderful way, I just saw that it was a 30 minute video, and I knew for the first

02:42:56.680 --> 02:43:01.140
[Guest]: time in my life, what a Laplace transform actually did.

02:43:01.140 --> 02:43:07.960
[Guest]: And my respect for old Laplace grew, because he figured this out in the 17th or 18th century.

02:43:07.960 --> 02:43:08.960
[Guest]: And I was hooked.

02:43:08.960 --> 02:43:15.040
[Guest]: So then, you know, I started Khan Academy, anything, you know, hundreds of things, probability,

02:43:15.040 --> 02:43:16.280
[Guest]: we all talk about probability.

02:43:16.280 --> 02:43:20.840
[Guest]: There was this thing about Bayesian, I give talks about Bayesian theorem, Bayesian aspect,

02:43:20.840 --> 02:43:28.400
[Guest]: I had no clue what Bayesian was, till I actually saw a few well produced, you know, videos

02:43:28.400 --> 02:43:34.400
[Guest]: on YouTube, and then you realize things like Bayesian, it's, you know, it also has some

02:43:34.400 --> 02:43:40.480
[Guest]: philosophical sort of implications, how, you know, every time you discover a new fact,

02:43:40.480 --> 02:43:45.760
[Guest]: you change your assessment of, you know, situations, things like that.

02:43:45.760 --> 02:43:52.280
[Guest]: So that started YouTube, and then after some time, it went beyond that, and it just became

02:43:52.280 --> 02:43:54.400
[Guest]: fun, right?

02:43:54.400 --> 02:43:57.900
[Guest]: So YouTube is a different dimension of fun, it says.

02:43:57.900 --> 02:44:03.440
[Guest]: So there are vlogs, there are people doing funny things, there's one YouTube channel

02:44:03.440 --> 02:44:11.920
[Guest]: I see, I, for no discernible reason, they just take melted metal and pour it into different

02:44:11.920 --> 02:44:12.920
[Guest]: things.

02:44:12.920 --> 02:44:18.000
[Guest]: And just they melt some aluminium or melt some iron, they pour it into things and see

02:44:18.000 --> 02:44:19.000
[Guest]: what happens.

02:44:19.000 --> 02:44:24.080
[Guest]: It's all kind of thing, it's a completely different dimension, there's no, I cannot

02:44:24.080 --> 02:44:28.640
[Guest]: imagine any circumstance in which anyone could write a book about these things.

02:44:28.640 --> 02:44:33.040
[Guest]: But these channels do exist, they're very popular on YouTube.

02:44:33.040 --> 02:44:40.240
[Guest]: And I think at least YouTube is the only one I have, I don't understand Instagram at all.

02:44:40.240 --> 02:44:45.880
[Guest]: I am on Instagram, and I follow a lot of people, but I'm mystified as to its purpose.

02:44:45.880 --> 02:44:50.800
[Guest]: They just post pictures of themselves, and you're just supposed to like them.

02:44:50.800 --> 02:44:57.680
[Guest]: And what I mean, I don't understand, what are your views on emergent social media?

02:44:57.680 --> 02:44:59.680
[Amit Varma]: I haven't used Instagram much.

02:44:59.680 --> 02:45:03.900
[Amit Varma]: I think the purpose is this, like it's what we spoke about earlier, that what draws me

02:45:03.900 --> 02:45:08.800
[Amit Varma]: towards a creator is a personal, you feel that you know the person, and then you're

02:45:08.800 --> 02:45:10.680
[Amit Varma]: drawn into their story.

02:45:10.680 --> 02:45:12.320
[Amit Varma]: And then you're kind of hooked into it, right?

02:45:12.320 --> 02:45:14.520
[Amit Varma]: That's what draws one to creators.

02:45:14.520 --> 02:45:18.580
[Amit Varma]: And I think Instagram is kind of an extension of that, that you're doing shit, like a story

02:45:18.580 --> 02:45:24.640
[Amit Varma]: I kind of sometimes talk about is like last year, you know, chess, YouTube kind of exploded.

02:45:24.640 --> 02:45:27.840
[Amit Varma]: And there's this comedian called Samera and he did a bunch of stuff and chess YouTube

02:45:27.840 --> 02:45:29.480
[Amit Varma]: kind of exploded.

02:45:29.480 --> 02:45:34.800
[Amit Varma]: So there was a day when, and there's a guy called Sagar Shah, who, you know, runs ChessBase

02:45:34.800 --> 02:45:35.800
[Amit Varma]: India.

02:45:35.800 --> 02:45:39.680
[Amit Varma]: ChessBase is this old venerable magazine from Germany, he runs the India version of it.

02:45:39.680 --> 02:45:45.640
[Amit Varma]: So you know, downstream of Samera, his YouTube channel started doing very well, the ChessBase

02:45:45.640 --> 02:45:46.640
[Amit Varma]: channel.

02:45:46.640 --> 02:45:48.600
[Amit Varma]: So they had a live stream.

02:45:48.600 --> 02:45:52.480
[Amit Varma]: And it was very interesting because the live stream was supposed to offer of an event,

02:45:52.480 --> 02:45:56.080
[Amit Varma]: where they were doing live commentary of an event and was supposed to start at a particular

02:45:56.080 --> 02:46:03.120
[Amit Varma]: time, and the guy realizes five minutes before that his internet isn't working at home.

02:46:03.120 --> 02:46:08.280
[Amit Varma]: But this is during COVID time, but the ChessBase office is five minutes away in Goregaon or

02:46:08.280 --> 02:46:09.540
[Amit Varma]: wherever this is.

02:46:09.540 --> 02:46:13.560
[Amit Varma]: So he picks up his laptop and camera and all the equipment, Mike Shaikh, and he runs to

02:46:13.560 --> 02:46:18.280
[Amit Varma]: his office physically, and he starts it a couple of minutes late, but he starts it.

02:46:18.280 --> 02:46:19.460
[Amit Varma]: And then the thing is happening.

02:46:19.460 --> 02:46:21.640
[Amit Varma]: And then his wife is at home where the internet has come back.

02:46:21.640 --> 02:46:25.920
[Amit Varma]: So she joins, she's a co-commentator, and the event ends.

02:46:25.920 --> 02:46:30.520
[Amit Varma]: And then some of the players who played in that event, top grandmasters, they join in.

02:46:30.520 --> 02:46:35.000
[Amit Varma]: And so what would have been like a three hour stream becomes a six hour stream where they're

02:46:35.000 --> 02:46:36.000
[Amit Varma]: just talking, right?

02:46:36.000 --> 02:46:37.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's great.

02:46:37.000 --> 02:46:38.000
[Amit Varma]: It's riveting.

02:46:38.000 --> 02:46:41.160
[Amit Varma]: You've got 10s of 1000s of people who are watching this live stream, where the chess

02:46:41.160 --> 02:46:42.160
[Amit Varma]: is over.

02:46:42.160 --> 02:46:43.280
[Amit Varma]: It's just riveting.

02:46:43.280 --> 02:46:47.680
[Amit Varma]: And then at about three or four in the morning, young Sagar reveals that in the in that particular

02:46:47.680 --> 02:46:52.640
[Amit Varma]: area, the streets are full of these dogs, and he's scared of walking home now because

02:46:52.640 --> 02:46:53.960
[Amit Varma]: he's got to go home.

02:46:53.960 --> 02:46:57.080
[Amit Varma]: So there's one reader saying in the live chat, hey, I'll come and I'll drive you home and

02:46:57.080 --> 02:47:00.160
[Amit Varma]: all of that shit is happening, but he decides to walk home.

02:47:00.160 --> 02:47:05.600
[Amit Varma]: But because everybody is so scared, worried about him now, they want to make sure he gets

02:47:05.600 --> 02:47:06.600
[Amit Varma]: home safely.

02:47:06.600 --> 02:47:11.120
[Amit Varma]: So he switches off the YouTube stream, and he starts streaming on Instagram, he does

02:47:11.120 --> 02:47:12.800
[Amit Varma]: an Instagram live.

02:47:12.800 --> 02:47:16.120
[Amit Varma]: And then all of these people switch from YouTube to Instagram, and they follow his journey

02:47:16.120 --> 02:47:17.120
[Amit Varma]: home.

02:47:17.120 --> 02:47:20.440
[Amit Varma]: You know, just seeing that whole thing unfold is fantastic.

02:47:20.440 --> 02:47:24.720
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, Instagram is more useful for things apart from this.

02:47:24.720 --> 02:47:27.720
[Amit Varma]: And I guess the only way to really know is to dive into it.

02:47:27.720 --> 02:47:32.880
[Amit Varma]: Because I just think that every medium, including podcasting, that if you just look at it from

02:47:32.880 --> 02:47:38.760
[Amit Varma]: the outside as a superficial thing, it seems like it seems very banal, like in the early

02:47:38.760 --> 02:47:42.040
[Amit Varma]: days of blogging, people would say, Oh, who wants to know what you had for breakfast as

02:47:42.040 --> 02:47:44.120
[Amit Varma]: if that is what blogging was.

02:47:44.120 --> 02:47:48.800
[Amit Varma]: And similarly, so now I've gone through, I've gone on many YouTube rabbit holes, I haven't

02:47:48.800 --> 02:47:54.400
[Amit Varma]: gone through any, I'm not on Instagram, I mean, I opened an account once, but zero posts,

02:47:54.400 --> 02:47:57.880
[Amit Varma]: and therefore nobody knows what it is, you know, maybe someday I'll go there.

02:47:57.880 --> 02:48:02.880
[Amit Varma]: But just, you know, in case listeners are confused, what do I mean by Naren's creative

02:48:02.880 --> 02:48:07.400
[Amit Varma]: future and all of that, Naren just revealed before we started recording that he's retiring

02:48:07.400 --> 02:48:12.000
[Amit Varma]: in a month, yes, people retire, young people, that he's retiring in a month, and we'll focus

02:48:12.000 --> 02:48:13.760
[Amit Varma]: on doing interesting creative things.

02:48:13.760 --> 02:48:16.400
[Amit Varma]: And I've been planning to start something on YouTube.

02:48:16.400 --> 02:48:21.960
[Amit Varma]: So we said that, okay, one of the many things that I'll do is a food blog with my good friend

02:48:21.960 --> 02:48:22.960
[Amit Varma]: Naren.

02:48:22.960 --> 02:48:27.440
[Amit Varma]: And we can go around and sort of talk about that, because I just feel that India in that

02:48:27.440 --> 02:48:33.640
[Amit Varma]: sense is so incredibly diverse, like, you know, Naren earlier mentioned this food trip

02:48:33.640 --> 02:48:34.640
[Amit Varma]: that we did.

02:48:34.640 --> 02:48:40.360
[Amit Varma]: And we, you know, a bunch of us, I think about eight to 10 of us, we went to Bangalore, went

02:48:40.360 --> 02:48:45.760
[Amit Varma]: around Bangalore and did some eating, but basically hired a bus and then went to Mysore.

02:48:45.760 --> 02:48:50.240
[Amit Varma]: And in Mysore, did a lot of eating a lot of epic places, including a pork biryani, I will

02:48:50.240 --> 02:48:51.600
[Amit Varma]: never forget.

02:48:51.600 --> 02:48:57.040
[Amit Varma]: And it was, it was pretty mind blowing, because like you said, Mysore is almost like an Istanbul

02:48:57.040 --> 02:49:03.760
[Amit Varma]: of India is a confluence of cultures, Persian, Turkish, you know, Asian, all over the, you

02:49:03.760 --> 02:49:07.320
[Amit Varma]: know, it's just, it's just incredible food wise.

02:49:07.320 --> 02:49:11.820
[Amit Varma]: And I don't think people have kind of mapped this out enough.

02:49:11.820 --> 02:49:19.400
[Guest]: So I'm very excited about, you know, starting off this YouTube thing with you.

02:49:19.400 --> 02:49:28.280
[Guest]: Because as we were discussing earlier, it's, it's a medium whose real, you know, real power

02:49:28.280 --> 02:49:31.640
[Guest]: really hasn't been explored.

02:49:31.640 --> 02:49:33.480
[Guest]: And it's interpretation.

02:49:33.480 --> 02:49:43.040
[Guest]: So you sort of, you just find out, and even about food, food as a map of as a snapshot

02:49:43.040 --> 02:49:52.920
[Guest]: or a map of our entire being as a, you know, a lot of food also connects cultures in many

02:49:52.920 --> 02:49:53.920
[Guest]: ways.

02:49:53.920 --> 02:49:57.480
[Guest]: And all of that is very interesting.

02:49:57.480 --> 02:50:09.540
[Guest]: And food is actually if you, one thing I realized is a lot of mainstream Indian food is common

02:50:09.540 --> 02:50:15.160
[Guest]: across castes or class than region.

02:50:15.160 --> 02:50:22.640
[Guest]: So food that Brahmins eat from Kashmir to Kanyakumari will be far more similar than

02:50:22.640 --> 02:50:27.800
[Guest]: the food a Brahmin eats and a Dalit eats in the same villages is what I'm guessing.

02:50:27.800 --> 02:50:28.800
[Amit Varma]: That's fascinating.

02:50:28.800 --> 02:50:29.800
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:50:29.800 --> 02:50:34.240
[Guest]: And I don't know if this is an Amche theory or something, which is really the fact, but

02:50:34.240 --> 02:50:37.520
[Guest]: it's something I would really like to figure out.

02:50:37.520 --> 02:50:46.080
[Guest]: The other thing about lower class food, so I, you know, they're not simply not available

02:50:46.080 --> 02:50:48.000
[Guest]: because they are not the restaurant class.

02:50:48.000 --> 02:50:55.240
[Guest]: So they just, and it'll be interesting to find out what they eat, what a farmer eats

02:50:55.240 --> 02:51:03.480
[Guest]: in Western UP, maybe, you know, what some other community, other caste, it'll be fascinating.

02:51:03.480 --> 02:51:04.480
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:51:04.480 --> 02:51:10.280
[Guest]: It's a journey that's intriguing and basically is also fun because eating is very fundamental.

02:51:10.280 --> 02:51:11.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:51:11.280 --> 02:51:16.360
[Amit Varma]: It's one of our primal impulses and like I did this episode with Peggy Mohan, who's written

02:51:16.360 --> 02:51:21.320
[Amit Varma]: this fantastic book on languages, how you can tell history through languages and, you

02:51:21.320 --> 02:51:26.760
[Amit Varma]: know, when you mentioned this, how, you know, Brahmins across India will have more commonality

02:51:26.760 --> 02:51:29.880
[Amit Varma]: in cuisine than a Brahmin and a Dalit in the same village.

02:51:29.880 --> 02:51:34.160
[Amit Varma]: And even across genders, there are interesting differences in language.

02:51:34.160 --> 02:51:38.640
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that she kind of points out is that, you know, back in the day when

02:51:38.640 --> 02:51:43.000
[Amit Varma]: the Aryans came, and by the way, yes, the Aryan migration theory is true.

02:51:43.000 --> 02:51:47.200
[Amit Varma]: You can, you know, check out my episode with Tony Joseph or read his brilliant book for

02:51:47.200 --> 02:51:48.200
[Amit Varma]: that.

02:51:48.200 --> 02:51:52.160
[Amit Varma]: I think that is, you know, something we know beyond all doubt that when the Aryans came,

02:51:52.160 --> 02:51:55.640
[Amit Varma]: they came in bands of men because that is how explorers go out.

02:51:55.640 --> 02:52:01.160
[Amit Varma]: So they took local women as their wives, you know, whether by conquest or consent or whatever,

02:52:01.160 --> 02:52:04.060
[Amit Varma]: we don't know, but they took local women as their wives.

02:52:04.060 --> 02:52:08.820
[Amit Varma]: And as a consequence for generations, it was a case that the women spoke a separate language

02:52:08.820 --> 02:52:15.000
[Amit Varma]: from the men, and it's very interesting to then see that reflected in the evolution of

02:52:15.000 --> 02:52:16.000
[Amit Varma]: both languages.

02:52:16.000 --> 02:52:19.560
[Amit Varma]: Like there is so much in Sanskrit that has come from local languages.

02:52:19.560 --> 02:52:24.040
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time, one of the consequences of that is that men and women would speak

02:52:24.040 --> 02:52:27.480
[Amit Varma]: subtly different languages because the young girls when growing up would spend more time

02:52:27.480 --> 02:52:31.440
[Amit Varma]: with the mother and at home, and the boys would be with the mother till sometime and

02:52:31.440 --> 02:52:35.200
[Amit Varma]: then they're out in the field with their fathers doing whatever fathers do in the field hunting

02:52:35.200 --> 02:52:36.240
[Guest]: or whatever it is.

02:52:36.240 --> 02:52:43.880
[Guest]: So the old languages took a really long time to get ironed out and probably never did get

02:52:43.880 --> 02:52:44.880
[Guest]: ironed out.

02:52:44.880 --> 02:52:45.880
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:52:45.880 --> 02:52:47.240
[Guest]: She speaks about those sounds, right?

02:52:47.240 --> 02:52:48.240
[Guest]: So the retroflex sounds.

02:52:48.240 --> 02:52:55.480
[Amit Varma]: Retroflex sounds like, you know, dhat and dhat, you know, so dhat is the and the, and

02:52:55.480 --> 02:52:58.960
[Amit Varma]: dhat, the and the, where your tongue hits the back of your mouth in the way that it

02:52:58.960 --> 02:53:05.840
[Amit Varma]: does are not there in any of the other, you know, Indo-Proto European languages.

02:53:05.840 --> 02:53:06.840
[Amit Varma]: It's not there.

02:53:06.840 --> 02:53:12.040
[Amit Varma]: So if you follow the Aryan languages journey all the way through, it's not there anywhere

02:53:12.040 --> 02:53:17.160
[Amit Varma]: till the Indian subcontinent, where it's clearly something that's kind of come from the local

02:53:17.160 --> 02:53:18.160
[Amit Varma]: languages.

02:53:18.160 --> 02:53:20.280
[Amit Varma]: And it's to me, that's kind of delightful.

02:53:20.280 --> 02:53:25.600
[Amit Varma]: I mean, obviously, there's also a tinge of what were lives like back then was the violence.

02:53:25.600 --> 02:53:30.560
[Amit Varma]: But the reason I brought this up is that in the same way as, you know, I find it fascinating

02:53:30.560 --> 02:53:35.080
[Amit Varma]: that you can look at something that is static today and tell the past through it, that you

02:53:35.080 --> 02:53:39.080
[Amit Varma]: can look at, like, like Tony Joseph writes about in his book, you know, you can look

02:53:39.080 --> 02:53:43.400
[Amit Varma]: at, you know, someone's genome, and you can, you know, go back to the past and figure shit

02:53:43.400 --> 02:53:44.400
[Amit Varma]: out.

02:53:44.400 --> 02:53:47.760
[Amit Varma]: You can look at languages that people speak, and you can tell something about the past

02:53:47.760 --> 02:53:48.760
[Amit Varma]: from there.

02:53:48.760 --> 02:53:53.320
[Amit Varma]: And I think that's got to be true of food as well, except it's probably much more complex,

02:53:53.320 --> 02:53:54.320
[Amit Varma]: and much more subtle.

02:53:54.320 --> 02:53:57.880
[Amit Varma]: And it's, but there's so much to be done.

02:53:57.880 --> 02:54:02.440
[Guest]: Yeah, there's a, that's an entire journey waiting to be made.

02:54:02.440 --> 02:54:06.620
[Guest]: So oftentimes, people make journeys like this with agenda.

02:54:06.620 --> 02:54:09.760
[Guest]: So the thing to do is to do that journey without an agenda.

02:54:09.760 --> 02:54:15.820
[Guest]: So there's no, you have no idea what you're going to find out in the course of doing this

02:54:15.820 --> 02:54:17.620
[Guest]: or the end of this.

02:54:17.620 --> 02:54:22.880
[Guest]: But it's, it's going to be fun, and it's generally going to be interesting, because always, it

02:54:22.880 --> 02:54:29.480
[Guest]: is, you know, these, these are things that interest everyone, where, where you came from,

02:54:29.480 --> 02:54:32.800
[Guest]: where other people came from, and how you are connected with each other.

02:54:32.800 --> 02:54:37.720
[Guest]: So it's, it's, it's something that really promises to be fun.

02:54:37.720 --> 02:54:38.720
[Guest]: So watch this space, everyone.

02:54:38.720 --> 02:54:39.720
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, watch this space.

02:54:39.720 --> 02:54:44.920
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I want to throw a lot of things at a YouTube wall, and see what sticks.

02:54:44.920 --> 02:54:48.520
[Amit Varma]: The point is, there is this initial nervousness, because there is a halo effect of the podcast.

02:54:48.520 --> 02:54:52.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that because the scene in the unseen now for the last three years or so has been

02:54:52.200 --> 02:54:55.320
[Amit Varma]: like a finished product where I really know what I'm doing, and I bring out what I bring

02:54:55.320 --> 02:54:56.320
[Amit Varma]: out.

02:54:56.320 --> 02:55:00.760
[Amit Varma]: And people, you know, expect a similar quality, whereas I know this is what I tell all creators

02:55:00.760 --> 02:55:04.560
[Amit Varma]: that when you do something for the first time, you're going to suck, embrace it, you know,

02:55:04.560 --> 02:55:09.560
[Amit Varma]: embrace the sucking, but just suck more, be regular at sucking, have a discipline eventually

02:55:09.560 --> 02:55:12.160
[Amit Varma]: through iteration, you'll become much better.

02:55:12.160 --> 02:55:17.320
[Amit Varma]: So obviously, when I begin doing my YouTube stuff, I will suck, which is fine, but you

02:55:17.320 --> 02:55:21.120
[Amit Varma]: know, except that there might be people who expect me not to suck, which is not fair,

02:55:21.120 --> 02:55:24.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, let me suck for a while, and then I'll figure it out.

02:55:24.040 --> 02:55:27.920
[Amit Varma]: And if there are any people who'd want to sponsor our specific show, which Naren and

02:55:27.920 --> 02:55:31.680
[Amit Varma]: I will do on food, you know, feel free to get in touch.

02:55:31.680 --> 02:55:35.360
[Amit Varma]: At this moment of time, we have zero followers on YouTube, because we don't have a YouTube

02:55:35.360 --> 02:55:36.360
[Amit Varma]: channel.

02:55:36.360 --> 02:55:41.360
[Amit Varma]: But yeah, so you know, before we kind of wind up, and you know, one of the things that I've

02:55:41.360 --> 02:55:46.400
[Amit Varma]: really loved about knowing you is that, you know, every time we meet, you tell at least

02:55:46.400 --> 02:55:50.480
[Amit Varma]: four or five incredible mind blowing stories, some of which you also share on Twitter threads,

02:55:50.480 --> 02:55:52.640
[Amit Varma]: which then go viral and all of that.

02:55:52.640 --> 02:55:56.720
[Amit Varma]: But there's one particular story, and you know, which particular story I'm talking about,

02:55:56.720 --> 02:56:02.480
[Amit Varma]: which I love so much, because it says so much about this incredible country that you're

02:56:02.480 --> 02:56:03.480
[Amit Varma]: in.

02:56:03.480 --> 02:56:07.600
[Amit Varma]: So, so may I invite you to now enlighten my listeners as well.

02:56:07.600 --> 02:56:13.720
[Guest]: So this happened, maybe, I don't know, 10, 15, 12 years ago.

02:56:13.720 --> 02:56:18.520
[Guest]: So we, Sheila and I, we were doing a powerhouse.

02:56:18.520 --> 02:56:25.920
[Guest]: And one of our friends, who was an architect, said that, you know, you could go to China,

02:56:25.920 --> 02:56:32.840
[Guest]: buy everything from China, import it, and you'll get a very good deal.

02:56:32.840 --> 02:56:37.720
[Guest]: It was very cheap at that point of time, and you have a lot of variety.

02:56:37.720 --> 02:56:39.880
[Guest]: So you know, and it was true.

02:56:39.880 --> 02:56:45.320
[Guest]: So China has this huge mall where you can buy furniture by theme.

02:56:45.320 --> 02:56:50.720
[Guest]: So if you want colonial furniture, and everything, you know.

02:56:50.720 --> 02:56:54.120
[Amit Varma]: And just to be clear, you weren't just throwing up your flat, basically the building that

02:56:54.120 --> 02:56:58.920
[Guest]: you had, you made a full building with many flats on it, so you were going to furnish

02:56:58.920 --> 02:56:59.920
[Guest]: all of them.

02:56:59.920 --> 02:57:00.920
[Guest]: Yeah, three flats plus ours.

02:57:00.920 --> 02:57:02.920
[Guest]: So we wanted to furnish all those flats.

02:57:02.920 --> 02:57:07.800
[Guest]: So we went there, we, you know, we bought all the stuff, everything got loaded onto

02:57:07.800 --> 02:57:08.800
[Unknown]: containers.

02:57:08.800 --> 02:57:15.120
[Guest]: And so some containers came soon, and it so happened that Sheila and I had planned to

02:57:15.120 --> 02:57:21.000
[Guest]: go to Europe at that time, we had planned a vacation there, this had been planned a

02:57:21.000 --> 02:57:25.440
[Guest]: long time ago, and you know, tickets had been booked, and hotels had been booked, and it

02:57:25.440 --> 02:57:27.920
[Guest]: was going to be the two of us.

02:57:27.920 --> 02:57:34.280
[Guest]: And I couldn't, and I think one of the containers hadn't arrived by the time I left.

02:57:34.280 --> 02:57:38.640
[Guest]: So my clearing agent said that, you know, no problem.

02:57:38.640 --> 02:57:42.440
[Guest]: These are all the papers, you sign everything in advance, and I'll, and you know, he gave

02:57:42.440 --> 02:57:48.360
[Guest]: me that there is duty to be paid, so he knew also what duty was going to be, so he paid

02:57:48.360 --> 02:57:52.880
[Guest]: all the shipping charges, everything was done, I paid all the money, and I went.

02:57:52.880 --> 02:57:58.020
[Guest]: And we are in Paris somewhere, in the middle of the night, the phone rings, and it's my

02:57:58.020 --> 02:58:03.160
[Guest]: customs clearing agent, and he says, sir, can you come, you know, are you going to come

02:58:03.160 --> 02:58:04.160
[Guest]: in the next couple of hours?

02:58:04.160 --> 02:58:07.000
[Guest]: I said, no, we just got here, and we've got this.

02:58:07.000 --> 02:58:09.120
[Guest]: So he says, no, there's a problem.

02:58:09.120 --> 02:58:17.320
[Guest]: So the problem was as follows, my import-export code number was in the name of Narendra Shenoy.

02:58:17.320 --> 02:58:24.120
[Guest]: And for some reason, the guy from China had shipped the material, and it was in the name

02:58:24.120 --> 02:58:26.800
[Guest]: of Mr. Narendra Shenoy.

02:58:26.800 --> 02:58:33.880
[Guest]: And I needed a notarized affidavit to be submitted, which stated that, to the best of my knowledge,

02:58:33.880 --> 02:58:37.920
[Guest]: Narendra Shenoy and Mr. Narendra Shenoy was the same person.

02:58:37.920 --> 02:58:41.000
[Guest]: And it had to be notarized, and it had to be signed by me.

02:58:41.000 --> 02:58:45.760
[Guest]: So I told him, can you not just, you know, sort of just sign it, he says, no, no, they

02:58:45.760 --> 02:58:50.160
[Guest]: check it with your, you know, you have your other signatures and things like that, I can't

02:58:50.160 --> 02:58:51.160
[Guest]: do that.

02:58:51.160 --> 02:58:58.860
[Guest]: And obviously, I couldn't, I couldn't, I couldn't fly down from Paris, and so I couldn't come.

02:58:58.860 --> 02:59:05.800
[Guest]: And when I came back, I had to pay a demerit, I had to pay a nice stiff fine for not being

02:59:05.800 --> 02:59:11.920
[Guest]: able to clear my goods, because I wasn't able to produce an affidavit that, to the best

02:59:11.920 --> 02:59:16.480
[Guest]: of my knowledge, Narendra Shenoy and Mr. Narendra Shenoy were the same person.

02:59:16.480 --> 02:59:19.880
[Guest]: It's been the high point of my life.

02:59:19.880 --> 02:59:26.880
[Guest]: And I can't even, most people don't believe it's true, but I, I, unfortunately, I don't

02:59:26.880 --> 02:59:27.880
[Guest]: have that affidavit.

02:59:27.880 --> 02:59:29.440
[Guest]: Someone, I think you asked me for it.

02:59:29.440 --> 02:59:31.520
[Amit Varma]: I wanted that copy of that affidavit.

02:59:31.520 --> 02:59:33.920
[Guest]: Yeah, unfortunately, I should have kept it.

02:59:33.920 --> 02:59:34.920
[Guest]: It's actually made.

02:59:34.920 --> 02:59:39.640
[Guest]: I'm still not clear whether, I used to think that it was the customs department that asked

02:59:39.640 --> 02:59:40.640
[Guest]: it.

02:59:40.640 --> 02:59:48.360
[Guest]: But apparently, it was a shipping company that wanted it before, so I'm still not clear

02:59:48.360 --> 02:59:50.400
[Guest]: who exactly asked for that.

02:59:50.400 --> 02:59:54.400
[Guest]: But I wrote that affidavit, it's been the high point of my life.

02:59:54.400 --> 03:00:01.880
[Guest]: And all my friends now, whenever there is any, you know, doubt about, they always ask

03:00:01.880 --> 03:00:08.240
[Guest]: me whether it's Narendra Shenoy or Mr. Narendra Shenoy talking.

03:00:08.240 --> 03:00:09.240
[Amit Varma]: It's a lovely story.

03:00:09.240 --> 03:00:14.600
[Amit Varma]: It just tells you so much about the Indian system that such a thing actually happened.

03:00:14.600 --> 03:00:16.320
[Amit Varma]: It's just complete nuts.

03:00:16.320 --> 03:00:20.640
[Amit Varma]: So you know, as we kind of wind up, a few final questions and here's one.

03:00:20.640 --> 03:00:25.760
[Amit Varma]: If you were to encounter the 25 year old Narendra Shenoy today, you know, let's say you are

03:00:25.760 --> 03:00:31.360
[Amit Varma]: Mr. Narendra Shenoy, what advice would you give him?

03:00:31.360 --> 03:00:39.800
[Guest]: So first thing I would say is don't hold back, don't hesitate.

03:00:39.800 --> 03:00:44.360
[Guest]: I've been very hesitant in many things that I've done, despite the fact that I've been

03:00:44.360 --> 03:00:46.520
[Guest]: impulsive and done a lot of things.

03:00:46.520 --> 03:00:49.880
[Guest]: So don't hesitate is one.

03:00:49.880 --> 03:00:56.200
[Guest]: And second, I would say is just be kinder to people.

03:00:56.200 --> 03:01:03.760
[Guest]: I younger Narendra Shenoy was probably not very kind person.

03:01:03.760 --> 03:01:13.120
[Guest]: I would definitely, I wish I was kinder to many people, especially people who are not

03:01:13.120 --> 03:01:22.280
[Guest]: up to my sort of expectation in like being clever in speaking.

03:01:22.280 --> 03:01:28.880
[Guest]: I've been guilty of judging people on how they speak and now I know that that's not

03:01:28.880 --> 03:01:29.880
[Guest]: a full story.

03:01:29.880 --> 03:01:34.840
[Guest]: So yeah, these are the two things I think I would advise my younger self.

03:01:34.840 --> 03:01:38.080
[Amit Varma]: Is this advice you've given your kids, for example, or do you think they've kind of internalized

03:01:38.080 --> 03:01:39.560
[Amit Varma]: it by watching you?

03:01:39.560 --> 03:01:41.580
[Guest]: And how has fatherhood changed you?

03:01:41.580 --> 03:01:50.760
[Guest]: So my kids, when they were growing up, the general situation in the house was that kids

03:01:50.760 --> 03:01:55.960
[Guest]: were kids, and they would do all kinds of silly things.

03:01:55.960 --> 03:01:58.560
[Guest]: And I sort of identified with them.

03:01:58.560 --> 03:02:05.680
[Guest]: So a lot of my childhood sort of appeared, they would do pranky stuff, they would just

03:02:05.680 --> 03:02:06.880
[Guest]: go do stuff.

03:02:06.880 --> 03:02:09.960
[Guest]: And Sheila was a disciplinarian.

03:02:09.960 --> 03:02:16.400
[Guest]: So she didn't like, you know, she didn't like mess in the house or she didn't like, like

03:02:16.400 --> 03:02:18.560
[Guest]: everything had to be done in time.

03:02:18.560 --> 03:02:21.960
[Guest]: So she didn't like homework not being done and things like that.

03:02:21.960 --> 03:02:31.360
[Guest]: So the thing was that, you know, they would try and sort of break Sheila's rules.

03:02:31.360 --> 03:02:36.920
[Guest]: And I've, if you know, oftentimes, I was the supervising authority.

03:02:36.920 --> 03:02:42.960
[Guest]: And if Sheila's rules were broken, then I would get, you know, get all the, I would

03:02:42.960 --> 03:02:43.960
[Guest]: face the heat.

03:02:43.960 --> 03:02:48.120
[Guest]: So she would tell me what kind of a dad are you, I use, you know, you don't care about

03:02:48.120 --> 03:02:52.000
[Guest]: your children's future, I'll go down that rabbit hole.

03:02:52.000 --> 03:02:57.880
[Guest]: And the kids would be laughing, like, you know, grinning from ear to ear, watching me

03:02:57.880 --> 03:03:02.800
[Guest]: squirm in front of thing, knowing fully well that next time it happened, they would be

03:03:02.800 --> 03:03:04.400
[Guest]: able to get away with that.

03:03:04.400 --> 03:03:10.680
[Guest]: So what fatherhood made me was more indulgent, and more tolerant towards kids.

03:03:10.680 --> 03:03:16.640
[Guest]: Kids were also, they had, they were very fun loving, they were funny in their own ways.

03:03:16.640 --> 03:03:20.760
[Guest]: They were, they were charmingly innocent as well.

03:03:20.760 --> 03:03:22.280
[Guest]: And they were different.

03:03:22.280 --> 03:03:30.880
[Guest]: So older son was very sort of, you know, composed and reserved, and the younger one was bratty

03:03:30.880 --> 03:03:36.520
[Guest]: and a little bit, you know, he was ebullient, he would like to jump around, sing, dance,

03:03:36.520 --> 03:03:38.860
[Guest]: do all those kind of things.

03:03:38.860 --> 03:03:41.480
[Guest]: So it was fun watching them.

03:03:41.480 --> 03:03:49.280
[Guest]: My only regret is, it was a difficult time in my life, financially as well, you know,

03:03:49.280 --> 03:03:53.560
[Guest]: the way my business was going, and I wasn't making any money.

03:03:53.560 --> 03:03:59.780
[Guest]: And, you know, so I used to work a lot, run here, there, do a lot of things.

03:03:59.780 --> 03:04:07.880
[Guest]: So I wasn't able to spend as much time as I could actually, I could have sort of recalibrated

03:04:07.880 --> 03:04:14.280
[Guest]: my priorities, and I could have, because for all the running up and down that I did, my

03:04:14.280 --> 03:04:20.080
[Guest]: business eventually, I mean, it sorted itself out and nothing, I mean, there are times when

03:04:20.080 --> 03:04:25.720
[Guest]: the economy is down, you don't get orders, costs are up, you don't make money.

03:04:25.720 --> 03:04:33.360
[Guest]: I had my share of those problems, but yeah, I think that's, that's pretty much, that's

03:04:33.360 --> 03:04:34.360
[Guest]: pretty much it.

03:04:34.360 --> 03:04:35.360
[Amit Varma]: Great.

03:04:35.360 --> 03:04:41.080
[Amit Varma]: So finally, to, you know, ending it with kind of the predictable question of if my listeners

03:04:41.080 --> 03:04:44.560
[Amit Varma]: are to want to kind of know, and actually even I want to know, because I don't think

03:04:44.560 --> 03:04:49.400
[Amit Varma]: we've really discussed this, that recommend some books for us, some books that make you

03:04:49.400 --> 03:04:54.120
[Amit Varma]: that when you think of them, you feel that man, everyone should read this, either for

03:04:54.120 --> 03:04:58.440
[Amit Varma]: knowledge or for joy or whatever books that mean a lot to you.

03:04:58.440 --> 03:05:05.520
[Guest]: One book that I strongly believe should be a one semester course for every undergrad

03:05:05.520 --> 03:05:09.040
[Guest]: course in this country, in the world, is Thinking Fast and Slow.

03:05:09.040 --> 03:05:13.480
[Guest]: So that, that's one book everyone needs to internalize totally.

03:05:13.480 --> 03:05:20.520
[Guest]: It tells you how we are hardwired for biases, the different kinds of biases that are, and

03:05:20.520 --> 03:05:27.680
[Guest]: as Kahneman himself, it is written by Daniel Kahneman, and as he himself notes that even

03:05:27.680 --> 03:05:32.360
[Guest]: though you are aware of all the biases, you are still going to fall for them.

03:05:32.360 --> 03:05:38.600
[Guest]: The thing is to know that those biases exist and to know when you've fallen in for them.

03:05:38.600 --> 03:05:42.380
[Guest]: That's one book that I think everyone should read.

03:05:42.380 --> 03:05:48.160
[Guest]: The other one, you know, there's this, there are many by Bertrand Russell, but the one

03:05:48.160 --> 03:05:53.000
[Guest]: I really, because it was the one I read, is Why I'm Not a Christian.

03:05:53.000 --> 03:06:00.400
[Guest]: It's not so much about not being a Christian, it's about not believing in something because,

03:06:00.400 --> 03:06:06.280
[Guest]: just because someone, the standard stand you should take, everyone, all of us, is that

03:06:06.280 --> 03:06:11.560
[Guest]: you don't believe in something unless there is a very good reason to believe in it.

03:06:11.560 --> 03:06:14.840
[Guest]: And most of us, the exact opposite is true.

03:06:14.840 --> 03:06:18.000
[Guest]: So we believe in something unless disproved.

03:06:18.000 --> 03:06:25.780
[Guest]: Bertrand Russell convincingly states why it should be the other way around and in fiction,

03:06:25.780 --> 03:06:27.520
[Guest]: I loved the Woodhouse universe.

03:06:27.520 --> 03:06:31.440
[Guest]: I just read Woodhouse incessantly.

03:06:31.440 --> 03:06:34.420
[Guest]: There were two things that appealed to me, I later realized.

03:06:34.420 --> 03:06:41.720
[Guest]: One is, Woodhouse, all his situations are basically unreal.

03:06:41.720 --> 03:06:47.880
[Guest]: So there are no serial, no one dies, no one gets hurt, no one goes bankrupt.

03:06:47.880 --> 03:06:56.520
[Guest]: It's, you know, they have really silly problems, like uncle is threatening to cut off their

03:06:56.520 --> 03:07:02.000
[Guest]: inheritance if they marry an undesirable person, things like that.

03:07:02.000 --> 03:07:08.160
[Guest]: And the second thing is, he's always laughing at himself and, you know, along with that,

03:07:08.160 --> 03:07:13.920
[Guest]: so most people who like Woodhouse I've seen have the ability and the capacity to laugh

03:07:13.920 --> 03:07:15.120
[Guest]: at themselves.

03:07:15.120 --> 03:07:18.440
[Guest]: That is something I think is a very valuable trait in people.

03:07:18.440 --> 03:07:24.240
[Guest]: When something, when you do something silly or when you do something goofy, you should

03:07:24.240 --> 03:07:27.880
[Guest]: have it in you to laugh at yourself.

03:07:27.880 --> 03:07:34.800
[Guest]: And if someone else laughs, you laugh with them and that dissolves the poison of the

03:07:34.800 --> 03:07:35.800
[Guest]: moment.

03:07:35.800 --> 03:07:44.000
[Guest]: So those are things and then there are a few others I can't think of, okay, this is about

03:07:44.000 --> 03:07:48.040
[Guest]: what I can think of on the spur of the moment.

03:07:48.040 --> 03:07:49.040
[Amit Varma]: Maybe some other time.

03:07:49.040 --> 03:07:53.240
[Amit Varma]: Maybe we shouldn't have, you know, both of us had that heavy ramen, wonderful, wonderful

03:07:53.240 --> 03:07:55.200
[Amit Varma]: ramen before the show.

03:07:55.200 --> 03:07:59.720
[Amit Varma]: So maybe we should have left it for later, but we'll have many more conversations.

03:07:59.720 --> 03:08:00.720
[Amit Varma]: So thanks a lot.

03:08:00.720 --> 03:08:04.560
[Amit Varma]: I mean, this has been a long time coming, given that my origin story of the show begins

03:08:04.560 --> 03:08:05.560
[Amit Varma]: with you.

03:08:05.560 --> 03:08:11.320
[Amit Varma]: It's a bit of, you know, a shame that episode 250 is when it was, but we'll get on YouTube

03:08:11.320 --> 03:08:15.080
[Amit Varma]: soon and everyone will laugh at us and we will laugh with them.

03:08:15.080 --> 03:08:16.080
[Guest]: Yes.

03:08:16.080 --> 03:08:19.680
[Guest]: So looking forward to that, hopefully very soon.

03:08:19.680 --> 03:08:21.480
[Guest]: And thanks for having me.

03:08:21.480 --> 03:08:24.200
[Guest]: I sort of suspect I've been rambling.

03:08:24.200 --> 03:08:26.760
[Guest]: If I have been, apologies, but.

03:08:26.760 --> 03:08:28.000
[Guest]: This is a show for rambling.

03:08:28.000 --> 03:08:31.200
[Guest]: So what do you think I do?

03:08:31.200 --> 03:08:32.200
[Guest]: Yeah.

03:08:32.200 --> 03:08:36.000
[Guest]: So thanks again and stay cool.

03:08:36.000 --> 03:08:37.360
[Unknown]: Bye.

03:08:37.360 --> 03:08:40.280
[Amit Varma]: Okay, so the episode isn't over yet.

03:08:40.280 --> 03:08:43.880
[Amit Varma]: Up ahead are some fantastic anecdotes from Naren that made me laugh.

03:08:43.880 --> 03:08:51.800
[Amit Varma]: And it also made me think, listen in.

03:08:51.800 --> 03:08:53.400
[Amit Varma]: So story number one.

03:08:53.400 --> 03:08:58.440
[Guest]: So there's this uncle I had, who's sadly no more.

03:08:58.440 --> 03:09:03.880
[Guest]: And he wasn't well regarded in the family was considered and, you know, a bad egg, but

03:09:03.880 --> 03:09:06.680
[Guest]: he was all kinds of awesome for me.

03:09:06.680 --> 03:09:12.760
[Guest]: He had a wicked sense of humor, which took a very practical sort of thing.

03:09:12.760 --> 03:09:18.000
[Guest]: So he actually went down and did mean things to people.

03:09:18.000 --> 03:09:21.320
[Guest]: And so one was to his own mother.

03:09:21.320 --> 03:09:27.920
[Guest]: So this is maybe 50s Mumbai, they used to live in Bhadala.

03:09:27.920 --> 03:09:33.840
[Guest]: And so my grand aunt, she was my dad's aunt.

03:09:33.840 --> 03:09:37.360
[Guest]: She had a brother who lived in Mulund.

03:09:37.360 --> 03:09:41.280
[Guest]: Back in the day, if you want to get from Bhadala to Mulund, you had to walk, catch a train

03:09:41.280 --> 03:09:44.000
[Guest]: at Dadar and then go to Mulund.

03:09:44.000 --> 03:09:47.480
[Guest]: So she knew how to get from and she could speak only Kannada and Konkani.

03:09:47.480 --> 03:09:50.720
[Guest]: She could speak no Hindi, no English, no Marathi, nothing.

03:09:50.720 --> 03:09:57.000
[Guest]: She knew how to get from Bhadala where they lived to the other station, she would walk

03:09:57.000 --> 03:09:58.000
[Guest]: there.

03:09:58.000 --> 03:10:01.160
[Guest]: And then from Mulund station, she knew how to go to her brother's house.

03:10:01.160 --> 03:10:05.480
[Guest]: But she didn't know which train to take because it's bewildering, right?

03:10:05.480 --> 03:10:08.080
[Guest]: And she couldn't read the indicators or anything.

03:10:08.080 --> 03:10:10.360
[Guest]: So she asked her son, this uncle.

03:10:10.360 --> 03:10:11.360
[Guest]: So it's very simple.

03:10:11.360 --> 03:10:16.040
[Guest]: You just go to anyone on the platform.

03:10:16.040 --> 03:10:21.640
[Guest]: And you ask them, yeh train Mulund kyun jata hai?

03:10:21.640 --> 03:10:23.800
[Guest]: And poor thing, she had no clue.

03:10:23.800 --> 03:10:29.760
[Guest]: So she spent an hour freaking out everyone on Mulund station by asking them a very existential

03:10:29.760 --> 03:10:30.760
[Guest]: question.

03:10:30.760 --> 03:10:32.240
[Guest]: Why is this train going to Mulund?

03:10:32.240 --> 03:10:35.640
[Guest]: Everyone, mujhe kya malum, jata hai toh jata hogi.

03:10:35.640 --> 03:10:41.360
[Guest]: And then someone, some kindly soul who knew her realized that she was in some kind of

03:10:41.360 --> 03:10:47.240
[Guest]: a jam and then they rescued her and put her on the right train and she made it.

03:10:47.240 --> 03:10:51.040
[Guest]: And he did another thing to another uncle of his.

03:10:51.040 --> 03:10:58.040
[Guest]: And this uncle was there for my dad and this uncle's father's maternal uncle.

03:10:58.040 --> 03:11:04.800
[Guest]: So they were very fond of their mama, they had only one mom.

03:11:04.800 --> 03:11:12.880
[Guest]: And the nephews hated him because they would have to do all the work for him and they were

03:11:12.880 --> 03:11:14.440
[Guest]: not really fond of him.

03:11:14.440 --> 03:11:19.440
[Guest]: But luckily for them, he never used to come very often to Bombay, he used to live somewhere

03:11:19.440 --> 03:11:20.440
[Guest]: down south.

03:11:20.440 --> 03:11:27.000
[Guest]: One day he happened to come and this guy was assigned the task of going and picking him

03:11:27.000 --> 03:11:28.240
[Guest]: up at Sion.

03:11:28.240 --> 03:11:33.120
[Guest]: So from Mangalore back in the day, they would come in bus, all the buses would stop at Sion.

03:11:33.120 --> 03:11:35.720
[Guest]: And from Sion to Vadala, it's like a longish walk.

03:11:35.720 --> 03:11:38.280
[Guest]: Today we'll take a cab, but back in the day.

03:11:38.280 --> 03:11:45.920
[Guest]: So he went there and the uncle goes down, gets down with his bedding and everything

03:11:45.920 --> 03:11:48.280
[Guest]: and he expects his nephew to pick it up.

03:11:48.280 --> 03:11:55.480
[Guest]: So nephew tells him that there's a recent police order saying that everyone has to carry

03:11:55.480 --> 03:12:01.120
[Guest]: their own luggage because of some security issues, even back then, some story he told

03:12:01.120 --> 03:12:02.120
[Guest]: him.

03:12:02.120 --> 03:12:08.560
[Guest]: So he made this elderly uncle put all the things on his head and this guy had planned

03:12:08.560 --> 03:12:09.560
[Guest]: it out.

03:12:09.560 --> 03:12:14.120
[Guest]: So he had got a little bag, empty bag of his own with nothing, an empty dabba or something,

03:12:14.120 --> 03:12:16.640
[Guest]: he took that and put it on his head and put it on his head and walked.

03:12:16.640 --> 03:12:21.320
[Guest]: So he made sure that the uncle was carrying all the luggage.

03:12:21.320 --> 03:12:26.120
[Guest]: Then when they got to their building, they have a large, it's still there.

03:12:26.120 --> 03:12:29.680
[Guest]: It's a large iron gate, okay, which is always locked.

03:12:29.680 --> 03:12:32.920
[Guest]: And there's a little wicked gate inside, which people go in.

03:12:32.920 --> 03:12:39.800
[Guest]: So presumably that thing was for cars and nobody had cars back in the day, always locked.

03:12:39.800 --> 03:12:45.680
[Guest]: And they get to this gate, they come to the building, they come to the gate and this guy

03:12:45.680 --> 03:12:49.440
[Guest]: is like, oh my God, this gate is locked, how do we get in?

03:12:49.440 --> 03:12:55.040
[Guest]: So the uncle is also nonplussed, he doesn't know what to do.

03:12:55.040 --> 03:13:01.040
[Guest]: So he tells them, I'll tell you what, you leave the luggage here, you climb up the gate,

03:13:01.040 --> 03:13:05.200
[Guest]: and you hop off on the other side, and then I will throw the luggage and then you catch

03:13:05.200 --> 03:13:06.200
[Guest]: it.

03:13:06.200 --> 03:13:12.400
[Guest]: And uncle said, okay, he left the luggage, 60 year old guy somehow clambered up the gate,

03:13:12.400 --> 03:13:17.200
[Guest]: then hopped off to the other side, and he's waiting for the luggage to be thrown.

03:13:17.200 --> 03:13:23.080
[Guest]: And this guy just opens the wicked gate, picks up the thing and comes in.

03:13:23.080 --> 03:13:25.880
[Guest]: Fabulous use of incentives that uncle wouldn't have visited.

03:13:25.880 --> 03:13:32.240
[Guest]: There are all these things, there are big sort of morals, life morals, but only problem

03:13:32.240 --> 03:13:37.880
[Guest]: is I haven't figured out what the moral is, if, you know, there's some deep truth.

03:13:37.880 --> 03:13:43.400
[Guest]: And I think the day I figure out the deep truth, I'll become a very lucky, prosperous

03:13:43.400 --> 03:13:47.280
[Amit Varma]: person. Deep truth is in the questions, like, why does this train go to Mulund, should really

03:13:47.280 --> 03:13:55.480
[Amit Varma]: be the title of a book or a film.

03:13:55.480 --> 03:14:03.740
[Guest]: So the same uncle, who was made to climb up the gate and then hop off again, his sister

03:14:03.740 --> 03:14:10.440
[Guest]: was my great grandmother, so my dad's grandmother, and my grandmother had a reputation of being

03:14:10.440 --> 03:14:12.160
[Guest]: a very irascible lady.

03:14:12.160 --> 03:14:17.720
[Guest]: She suffered no nonsense, she ran and back in the day, I mean, they came from a pretty

03:14:17.720 --> 03:14:23.860
[Guest]: poor family and a large family, little food and, you know, it was always a woman's responsibility

03:14:23.860 --> 03:14:26.560
[Guest]: to keep the ship sailing.

03:14:26.560 --> 03:14:34.640
[Guest]: So my father tells me that, so there was a rule that if you leave anything on your plate,

03:14:34.640 --> 03:14:39.000
[Guest]: especially the kids, the whole thing would get dumped on your head.

03:14:39.000 --> 03:14:43.920
[Guest]: And you won't be allowed to have a bath all day. So you'd spend a whole day with like

03:14:43.920 --> 03:14:48.120
[Guest]: food dripping on your head and stinking and everything.

03:14:48.120 --> 03:14:52.840
[Guest]: And that was a lesson. So you learn that lesson once. So you just wiped everything clean as

03:14:52.840 --> 03:14:54.720
[Guest]: clean as possible.

03:14:54.720 --> 03:14:57.240
[Guest]: So that shows that kind of a person.

03:14:57.240 --> 03:15:03.080
[Guest]: Anyway, this uncle was a big aficionado of classical, Hindustani classical music.

03:15:03.080 --> 03:15:08.400
[Guest]: And I think I've got it from that, you know, that bloodline, because I am also very fond

03:15:08.400 --> 03:15:09.920
[Guest]: of Hindustani classical music.

03:15:09.920 --> 03:15:17.000
[Guest]: So his big favorite at that time was a legendary singer now named, I mean, she's no longer

03:15:17.000 --> 03:15:19.040
[Guest]: alive, named Hirabai Barodekar.

03:15:19.040 --> 03:15:26.240
[Guest]: So he went and bought one of those gramophones and a record of Hirabai Barodekar.

03:15:26.240 --> 03:15:28.040
[Unknown]: And it was a morning rag.

03:15:28.040 --> 03:15:30.520
[Guest]: So it was Ahir Bhairav or something.

03:15:30.520 --> 03:15:32.600
[Guest]: And morning rags have to be heard in the morning.

03:15:32.600 --> 03:15:39.640
[Guest]: So at four in the morning, he puts on the gramophone, he puts this plate and he starts

03:15:39.640 --> 03:15:41.360
[Guest]: playing it.

03:15:41.360 --> 03:15:43.760
[Guest]: And everyone is fast asleep.

03:15:43.760 --> 03:15:46.880
[Guest]: And at four in the morning, we start singing.

03:15:46.880 --> 03:15:53.640
[Guest]: My great grandmother, mother apparently thought somebody was being strangled.

03:15:53.640 --> 03:15:58.120
[Guest]: So she comes running out, she's like, you know, she's had a hard day, she's like middle

03:15:58.120 --> 03:16:01.160
[Guest]: of a sleep, she's in a panic, she comes running out.

03:16:01.160 --> 03:16:06.840
[Guest]: And she finds this guy, you know, listening to music, she's so furious that she picks

03:16:06.840 --> 03:16:09.120
[Guest]: up a coconut, which is lying around.

03:16:09.120 --> 03:16:13.360
[Guest]: And she just hits him on the head with that coconut with such fury that apparently the

03:16:13.360 --> 03:16:19.520
[Guest]: coconut cracked, this guy immediately went off into a coma, he just knocked out cold.

03:16:19.520 --> 03:16:27.200
[Guest]: And apparently, that is the only time in recorded history, according to my dad, when the brother

03:16:27.200 --> 03:16:33.680
[Guest]: that's my grandfather and his brother actually yelled at their mother, they would never like

03:16:33.680 --> 03:16:40.920
[Guest]: motherly devotion was so strong that they would never, you know, speak, you know, harshly

03:16:40.920 --> 03:16:41.920
[Guest]: to her.

03:16:41.920 --> 03:16:46.680
[Guest]: Well, despite all this, I mean, she would be putting food on people's heads.

03:16:46.680 --> 03:16:52.160
[Guest]: Another favorite torture of hers was to put pickle, like we make pretty spicy pickle into

03:16:52.160 --> 03:16:57.440
[Guest]: children's eyes, if they, you know, if they misbehave or did something wrong, the punishment

03:16:57.440 --> 03:17:00.800
[Guest]: was to take a little pickle and put in their eye.

03:17:00.800 --> 03:17:02.120
[Guest]: It burns like hell.

03:17:02.120 --> 03:17:06.040
[Guest]: So I've had that experience accidentally, I mean, you just touch some pickle, and then

03:17:06.040 --> 03:17:10.200
[Guest]: you touch your eye, and then for hours later, it's burning.

03:17:10.200 --> 03:17:13.800
[Guest]: But she was that kind of a lady and they never used to say anything.

03:17:13.800 --> 03:17:19.800
[Guest]: Because that was how she was, she was a strict, non limit, fair lady, but like brutal.

03:17:19.800 --> 03:17:23.560
[Guest]: And this was the only time they ever really yelled at her.

03:17:23.560 --> 03:17:27.920
[Guest]: Luckily, uncle survived, he went on to father seven or eight children.

03:17:27.920 --> 03:17:30.200
[Amit Varma]: So there was no permanent damage.

03:17:30.200 --> 03:17:37.320
[Amit Varma]: Some parts of him were functional.

03:17:37.320 --> 03:17:44.720
[Guest]: So once when I was in engineering, I had a close friend who used to live in Bandra in

03:17:44.720 --> 03:17:50.280
[Guest]: very close to Pali Hill, and Bandra is a very different place.

03:17:50.280 --> 03:17:56.640
[Guest]: Today it is a, you know, it's a very, very tony neighborhood and you know, only the richest

03:17:56.640 --> 03:17:59.760
[Guest]: of the rich and the famous, only those people can live.

03:17:59.760 --> 03:18:06.360
[Guest]: But back in the day, I'm talking about early 80s, it was like any other little, they had

03:18:06.360 --> 03:18:09.960
[Guest]: a little village called Pali village.

03:18:09.960 --> 03:18:14.720
[Guest]: So it had a little marketplace and that was where you would, you know, you could buy your

03:18:14.720 --> 03:18:17.240
[Guest]: fish and meat and everything.

03:18:17.240 --> 03:18:19.440
[Guest]: And there was a tailor shop there.

03:18:19.440 --> 03:18:24.640
[Guest]: And it was just called Ladies Tailor, it was run by an old Muslim gentleman with a nice

03:18:24.640 --> 03:18:32.160
[Guest]: flowing beard and they used to call him Chacha and that was the only tailor in town.

03:18:32.160 --> 03:18:41.000
[Guest]: So one of his karigars, for some difference of opinion or whatever, he split, he split

03:18:41.000 --> 03:18:48.040
[Guest]: from Chacha and he took a shop opposite and he started his own shop.

03:18:48.040 --> 03:18:55.360
[Guest]: So he called it New Ladies Tailor because it was like, so Chacha, and all this every

03:18:55.360 --> 03:19:00.720
[Guest]: day used to go up and down the market and you could see all this happening.

03:19:00.720 --> 03:19:06.760
[Guest]: And the next thing that poor Chacha did was, in order to emphasize the vintage of his own

03:19:06.760 --> 03:19:13.920
[Guest]: practice, he named his shop Old Ladies Tailor and that was it.

03:19:13.920 --> 03:19:18.040
[Guest]: The next thing you know, Chacha went out of business for some mysterious reason, I don't

03:19:18.040 --> 03:19:19.840
[Guest]: know why.

03:19:19.840 --> 03:19:21.960
[Guest]: And then he converted it into a chicken shop.

03:19:21.960 --> 03:19:24.800
[Guest]: So last time I went to Pali market, a chicken shop was still there.

03:19:24.800 --> 03:19:34.240
[Amit Varma]: But it didn't say old chicken shop.

03:19:34.240 --> 03:19:35.640
[Guest]: Story number four.

03:19:35.640 --> 03:19:44.720
[Guest]: I spent a good four years of my life in Manipal and Manipal was a pretty, so the backstory

03:19:44.720 --> 03:19:45.720
[Guest]: is this.

03:19:45.720 --> 03:19:52.920
[Guest]: I wanted to get into medicine because my father was a doctor and I didn't get the marks.

03:19:52.920 --> 03:20:00.000
[Guest]: So we went to, you know, Manipal was a donation, what used to be called a donation college.

03:20:00.000 --> 03:20:07.680
[Guest]: So you had to pay what they call a capitation fee and you know, you just got it.

03:20:07.680 --> 03:20:10.280
[Guest]: I don't think they were very choosy about who they took.

03:20:10.280 --> 03:20:14.360
[Guest]: Anyway, I went there, the medical capitation fee was too high.

03:20:14.360 --> 03:20:16.360
[Guest]: My father said, I can't afford this.

03:20:16.360 --> 03:20:20.280
[Guest]: So my mother said, no, you have to be either a doctor or an engineer, otherwise who will

03:20:20.280 --> 03:20:21.280
[Guest]: marry my son.

03:20:21.280 --> 03:20:23.040
[Guest]: And he was right about that.

03:20:23.040 --> 03:20:27.720
[Guest]: Literally no one who would marry me had like, I got the job finding someone to marry me

03:20:27.720 --> 03:20:32.460
[Guest]: even though I did my engineering, but without engineering, there was no chance.

03:20:32.460 --> 03:20:42.200
[Guest]: So I joined engineering and I spent the most delightful four years, just met the most amazing

03:20:42.200 --> 03:20:49.240
[Guest]: people and had many amazing anecdotes from there.

03:20:49.240 --> 03:20:55.360
[Guest]: But one I'll give and here I have to make a humble brag that Satya Nadella was two years

03:20:55.360 --> 03:21:01.040
[Guest]: my junior and I keep telling everyone that whenever I met Satya, I used to tell him,

03:21:01.040 --> 03:21:03.400
[Guest]: you should go and join Microsoft, you'll do well.

03:21:03.400 --> 03:21:05.400
[Amit Varma]: So did you really tell?

03:21:05.400 --> 03:21:10.560
[Guest]: I just tell everyone and most of the younger guys are very odd.

03:21:10.560 --> 03:21:11.560
[Guest]: Actually I didn't even know him.

03:21:11.560 --> 03:21:15.160
[Guest]: I mean, he was there, but no one knew him.

03:21:15.160 --> 03:21:18.360
[Amit Varma]: This is like when I first shifted to seven bungalows in Andheri, I used to tell people

03:21:18.360 --> 03:21:24.680
[Amit Varma]: I live in one of the original seven bungalows.

03:21:24.680 --> 03:21:31.160
[Guest]: So we were like a new batch, we were the third cohort of the new thing, which was affiliated

03:21:31.160 --> 03:21:32.440
[Guest]: to Mangalore University.

03:21:32.440 --> 03:21:38.360
[Guest]: Before that, it was Mysore University and the Mysore University ones were very disconnected

03:21:38.360 --> 03:21:40.520
[Guest]: from their university.

03:21:40.520 --> 03:21:45.900
[Guest]: So all communication used to happen by telegram and back in the day, telegram was a thing.

03:21:45.900 --> 03:21:50.480
[Guest]: So most of this generation wouldn't know what it was.

03:21:50.480 --> 03:21:54.280
[Guest]: But if you do, you'll probably get this anecdote.

03:21:54.280 --> 03:22:03.120
[Guest]: So one of these guys failed in that subject and he got 23 marks and you had to get 35

03:22:03.120 --> 03:22:07.440
[Guest]: to pass and he thought everyone told him apply for revaluation.

03:22:07.440 --> 03:22:13.760
[Guest]: So you pay a little fee and you fill out a form and it goes to the thing and you have

03:22:13.760 --> 03:22:18.880
[Guest]: to also attach what was known as a reply pay telegram.

03:22:18.880 --> 03:22:26.560
[Guest]: So a reply pay telegram is you pay for the telegram that the recipient will send and

03:22:26.560 --> 03:22:28.960
[Guest]: you know that it's like a blank cheque.

03:22:28.960 --> 03:22:32.800
[Guest]: So it could be 10 rupees, it could be 100 rupees, if the guy decides to send you a very

03:22:32.800 --> 03:22:36.040
[Guest]: long telegram, you have to pay, but you have to pay all of it.

03:22:36.040 --> 03:22:43.560
[Guest]: He paid, that was the rule, he paid it and in due course, the revaluation results came.

03:22:43.560 --> 03:22:52.480
[Guest]: So it turned out that even the 23 marks that he got was a high number, his revalued result

03:22:52.480 --> 03:22:54.560
[Guest]: was 19 marks.

03:22:54.560 --> 03:22:59.640
[Guest]: But you know, the person who sent the thing, the clerk in the Vice Chancellor's office

03:22:59.640 --> 03:23:05.080
[Guest]: was a kindly man, he said, let me spare this guy the expense at least.

03:23:05.080 --> 03:23:07.360
[Guest]: I mean, I'm just conveying bad news.

03:23:07.360 --> 03:23:08.900
[Guest]: Why make him pay a lot?

03:23:08.900 --> 03:23:19.040
[Guest]: So he sent a single word, 19, that was it, but our local Manipal police post office interpreted

03:23:19.040 --> 03:23:22.240
[Guest]: that as something known as a greetings telegram.

03:23:22.240 --> 03:23:26.120
[Guest]: So back in the day, if you had a greet, if you wanted to send someone greetings, Diwali

03:23:26.120 --> 03:23:34.720
[Guest]: greetings, you would send three and the three was code for Happy Diwali and New Year and

03:23:34.720 --> 03:23:39.760
[Guest]: then it would come to Amit Verma saying that Happy Diwali.

03:23:39.760 --> 03:23:48.000
[Guest]: So the code number for 19 was heartiest Guru Parb greetings.

03:23:48.000 --> 03:23:54.800
[Guest]: So when the letter comes from the Vice Chancellor of Mysore University, everyone is really agog

03:23:54.800 --> 03:23:59.560
[Guest]: with, you know, sort of anticipation, like, am I going to pass, have I made it, have I

03:23:59.560 --> 03:24:00.560
[Guest]: made it to 35?

03:24:00.560 --> 03:24:05.400
[Guest]: And all that the Vice Chancellor of Mysore University has to tell him is heartiest Guru

03:24:05.400 --> 03:24:06.400
[Guest]: Parb greetings.

03:24:06.400 --> 03:24:14.400
[Guest]: He never recovered from the shock and so I've variously told this anecdote as this having

03:24:14.400 --> 03:24:19.240
[Guest]: happened to Satya Nadella and he got such a shock that he went to America and became

03:24:19.240 --> 03:24:20.880
[Guest]: the CEO of Microsoft.

03:24:20.880 --> 03:24:23.880
[Amit Varma]: But that's not true.

03:24:23.880 --> 03:24:38.360
[Guest]: So at number five, okay, so I have a lot of pretty interesting uncles, aunts, cousins

03:24:38.360 --> 03:24:43.560
[Guest]: and like over a period of time, some really hilarious things have happened.

03:24:43.560 --> 03:24:46.920
[Guest]: So one such is the following.

03:24:46.920 --> 03:24:52.200
[Guest]: So one of my cousins, so when you do your medicine, after you do your MBBS, you have

03:24:52.200 --> 03:24:57.680
[Guest]: to enroll for surgery and then you have to serve some kind of slave labor called registrar

03:24:57.680 --> 03:25:00.760
[Guest]: or not registrar, something, surgery resident, something.

03:25:00.760 --> 03:25:08.560
[Guest]: So he has to basically be in surgery like day in, day out for several years till he,

03:25:08.560 --> 03:25:13.360
[Guest]: you know, acquires the skills and then you give that exam and then you become a surgeon.

03:25:13.360 --> 03:25:18.760
[Guest]: So when he was on that rotation, his mother, he was the only son, mother very fond of him,

03:25:18.760 --> 03:25:22.880
[Guest]: mother was always, you know, she would always call him and this was, cell phones had just

03:25:22.880 --> 03:25:29.280
[Guest]: sort of, you know, entered, you know, common, it would just become common and she would

03:25:29.280 --> 03:25:30.280
[Guest]: call.

03:25:30.280 --> 03:25:34.640
[Guest]: And this guy would, half the time he would be in the surgery or assisting with the surgery

03:25:34.640 --> 03:25:36.560
[Guest]: or something, he couldn't take the call.

03:25:36.560 --> 03:25:41.480
[Guest]: So he told his mom that, you know, whatever you want to tell me and they would, calls

03:25:41.480 --> 03:25:47.640
[Guest]: would be like, have you had your food or, you know, have you, whatever, taken your medicines

03:25:47.640 --> 03:25:51.080
[Guest]: or whatever, something very inane.

03:25:51.080 --> 03:25:57.720
[Guest]: So he told his mom that, you know, you just text me, I mean, I'll respond to you whenever

03:25:57.720 --> 03:25:58.720
[Guest]: I can.

03:25:58.720 --> 03:26:02.520
[Guest]: And he indeed was in the operating theater 12 hours a day.

03:26:02.520 --> 03:26:05.480
[Guest]: So she said okay, but she didn't know how to text, so he taught her.

03:26:05.480 --> 03:26:10.320
[Guest]: So back in the day, it was those old Nokia phone thing and, you know, you had to, it

03:26:10.320 --> 03:26:14.800
[Guest]: took a little doing, typing a text message, but she figured that out.

03:26:14.800 --> 03:26:21.840
[Guest]: And then, so he worked in Sion Hospital and he lived in Juhu, so it wasn't very far, but

03:26:21.840 --> 03:26:28.760
[Guest]: even so, he had to basically live in the hospital 24-7 and just come once a week or something,

03:26:28.760 --> 03:26:30.400
[Guest]: change of clothes and things like that.

03:26:30.400 --> 03:26:35.640
[Guest]: So he comes after his first week and mother says, you know, you haven't responded to a

03:26:35.640 --> 03:26:37.280
[Guest]: single text, what's the matter?

03:26:37.280 --> 03:26:42.600
[Guest]: So he said, I haven't received a single text, who have you been sending it to?

03:26:42.600 --> 03:26:47.000
[Guest]: So she's been unfortunate, she wrote the text, but she didn't know how to send it.

03:26:47.000 --> 03:26:52.880
[Guest]: So it's by default going to the first person in the address book, whose name begins with

03:26:52.880 --> 03:26:57.480
[Guest]: A and it happens to be this guy's surgery boss.

03:26:57.480 --> 03:27:03.920
[Guest]: This guy is like, you know, a gosh, I mean, what would his surgery boss think?

03:27:03.920 --> 03:27:09.280
[Guest]: So he goes and he says, you know, I'm going to get yelled at because he's a famously irascible

03:27:09.280 --> 03:27:14.080
[Guest]: man and he's like, your suffers no nonsense, so he says, I'm going to get yelled at today,

03:27:14.080 --> 03:27:18.360
[Guest]: but I'll have to apologize, I didn't know.

03:27:18.360 --> 03:27:25.960
[Guest]: So he goes and he tells the boss that this is what happened and to his immense surprise,

03:27:25.960 --> 03:27:32.240
[Guest]: the guy almost breaks down into tears, he hugs him and embraces him and you know, he's

03:27:32.240 --> 03:27:36.000
[Guest]: like overcome with emotion, like relief.

03:27:36.000 --> 03:27:41.880
[Guest]: So I mean, he didn't understand what it was, then he figured it out later.

03:27:41.880 --> 03:27:48.440
[Guest]: So apparently, this guy's mother used to write texts like I love you very much, xxx, missing

03:27:48.440 --> 03:27:51.040
[Guest]: you so much and things like that.

03:27:51.040 --> 03:27:56.000
[Guest]: And the surgery guy had no clue whom it was coming from.

03:27:56.000 --> 03:28:00.240
[Guest]: And all he would get is text saying that I love you so much, I miss you so much, please

03:28:00.240 --> 03:28:02.960
[Guest]: come home soon or whatever.

03:28:02.960 --> 03:28:09.280
[Guest]: And he had to hurriedly delete all of them, lest his wife find out.

03:28:09.280 --> 03:28:18.040
[Guest]: So when he found out that this was the explanation, his grief was, I mean, his relief was immeasurable.

03:28:18.040 --> 03:28:24.240
[Guest]: He was like, completely relieved to know that his, you know, everything, his life was, he

03:28:24.240 --> 03:28:25.240
[Guest]: was totally freaked out.

03:28:25.240 --> 03:28:27.000
[Amit Varma]: He had no clue what was happening.

03:28:27.000 --> 03:28:33.440
[Guest]: But I mean, I'm just thinking if his wife had actually heard, one divorce, surgery resident,

03:28:33.440 --> 03:28:40.840
[Guest]: whatever, one surgery boss, the seen and the unseen.

03:28:40.840 --> 03:28:46.680
[Amit Varma]: Okay, story number six.

03:28:46.680 --> 03:28:50.040
[Guest]: Once I've, I don't know if you've been to Rajkot.

03:28:50.040 --> 03:28:53.640
[Guest]: So I haven't been recently, but I went some years ago.

03:28:53.640 --> 03:29:00.200
[Guest]: And at least when I went, Rajkot airport was a very charming little house like thing, you

03:29:00.200 --> 03:29:03.880
[Guest]: know, it could be somebody's bungalow, it's that small, very nice.

03:29:03.880 --> 03:29:09.240
[Guest]: And I landed up in Rajkot via Ahmedabad or something, I'd gone to Ahmedabad for some

03:29:09.240 --> 03:29:13.320
[Guest]: work and then I had to go to Rajkot, so I took a bus and then I landed.

03:29:13.320 --> 03:29:20.080
[Guest]: And then when my work was done, getting from Rajkot to Bombay is a pretty long journey.

03:29:20.080 --> 03:29:23.480
[Guest]: So train was not an option, it was too long.

03:29:23.480 --> 03:29:26.040
[Guest]: So I decided to fly.

03:29:26.040 --> 03:29:29.440
[Guest]: And I was very, this is back in the day.

03:29:29.440 --> 03:29:36.360
[Guest]: So not like not back in the days, maybe 15, 10-15 years ago.

03:29:36.360 --> 03:29:43.720
[Guest]: And I booked and I did a web check-in, web check-in had been introduced and I got myself

03:29:43.720 --> 03:29:47.720
[Guest]: a window seat because I wanted to see Rajkot from the air.

03:29:47.720 --> 03:29:53.680
[Guest]: And you know, so the only window seat I could get was row number 27, which was the last

03:29:53.680 --> 03:29:54.680
[Guest]: one.

03:29:54.680 --> 03:29:55.680
[Guest]: And I took it.

03:29:55.680 --> 03:30:02.200
[Guest]: And I landed up at the airport and it was Air India, very charming people.

03:30:02.200 --> 03:30:07.200
[Guest]: They, you know, somebody came, picked my luggage, took me to the check-in counter.

03:30:07.200 --> 03:30:09.280
[Guest]: It wasn't a very big flight.

03:30:09.280 --> 03:30:14.600
[Guest]: And there's a nice young lady sitting behind the counter and she looks at my boarding card

03:30:14.600 --> 03:30:17.880
[Guest]: and she says, oh, have you web checked in?

03:30:17.880 --> 03:30:18.880
[Guest]: I said, I have.

03:30:18.880 --> 03:30:23.440
[Guest]: Oh, but you have taken seat number 27F.

03:30:23.440 --> 03:30:25.920
[Guest]: I said, yes, because I want a window seat.

03:30:25.920 --> 03:30:27.760
[Guest]: But she says, sir, this is not a reclining seat.

03:30:27.760 --> 03:30:32.120
[Guest]: I don't mind, it's like a 50-minute flight, so I don't mind.

03:30:32.120 --> 03:30:37.160
[Guest]: She says, no, I have an aisle seat on number 17, so I can give you that.

03:30:37.160 --> 03:30:40.200
[Unknown]: She says, no, I said, I'm okay with a window seat.

03:30:40.200 --> 03:30:42.040
[Guest]: No, sir, but it's not reclining.

03:30:42.040 --> 03:30:43.480
[Guest]: I said, doesn't matter.

03:30:43.480 --> 03:30:48.920
[Guest]: She said, no, sir, you don't understand, at your age, it is better to have a reclining

03:30:48.920 --> 03:30:49.920
[Guest]: seat.

03:30:49.920 --> 03:30:56.560
[Guest]: So I was thinking of myself as a young whippersnapper and it was very clear what I looked like.

03:30:56.560 --> 03:31:02.440
[Guest]: So I gracefully accepted her offer and went on row number 17, quietly like a gentleman.

03:31:02.440 --> 03:31:08.040
[Amit Varma]: So now every time you kind of fly, you think of this and the realization of your sort of

03:31:08.040 --> 03:31:09.040
[Guest]: advancing years.

03:31:09.040 --> 03:31:10.040
[Guest]: Oh, yeah.

03:31:10.040 --> 03:31:16.560
[Guest]: And this is the thing, right, so everyone has a memory of how or when they were first

03:31:16.560 --> 03:31:17.560
[Guest]: called uncle.

03:31:17.560 --> 03:31:21.120
[Guest]: So when you're a kid, nobody calls you uncle and all of a sudden you're like in your 20s

03:31:21.120 --> 03:31:26.240
[Guest]: and some little kid says uncle and you're like, you know, that's a moment of truth.

03:31:26.240 --> 03:31:32.520
[Guest]: You realize that you have crossed some boundary and now you're no longer the young man you

03:31:32.520 --> 03:31:33.680
[Amit Varma]: thought you were.

03:31:33.680 --> 03:31:37.840
[Amit Varma]: What's worse is when some adult calls you uncle, that's problematic.

03:31:37.840 --> 03:31:40.880
[Guest]: Actually, yeah, actually girls are even more so.

03:31:40.880 --> 03:31:45.960
[Guest]: So we had, we used to have an employee in an office and just to troll her, the boys,

03:31:45.960 --> 03:31:52.280
[Guest]: the factory, she used to look after accounts or something and they used to call her auntie

03:31:52.280 --> 03:31:57.200
[Guest]: and she used to really lose it like because she thought she was young.

03:31:57.200 --> 03:32:05.480
[Guest]: So like 90% of our HR problems were guys going and calling her auntie and she's like yelling

03:32:05.480 --> 03:32:06.480
[Amit Varma]: at them.

03:32:06.480 --> 03:32:11.280
[Amit Varma]: I had a similar incident where I was at the Gaul Lit Fest after my book came out in 2009

03:32:11.280 --> 03:32:15.480
[Amit Varma]: and Sarnath Banerjee was one of the other people there and I'm in my 30s and so is he.

03:32:15.480 --> 03:32:19.760
[Amit Varma]: And at one point we went somewhere to some random beach or something and whatever and

03:32:19.760 --> 03:32:23.840
[Amit Varma]: he introduced me to one of his friends and the friend asked me, are you his father?

03:32:23.840 --> 03:32:26.080
[Amit Varma]: And the irony of this is Sarnath is older than me.

03:32:26.080 --> 03:32:27.080
[Amit Varma]: So really,

03:32:27.080 --> 03:32:33.880
[Guest]: Yeah, it's very brutal and completely gratuitous, right, you're not asking for his stage estimates

03:32:33.880 --> 03:32:35.720
[Amit Varma]: and then somebody comes and gives it to you.

03:32:35.720 --> 03:32:40.080
[Amit Varma]: But a dude who said that, you see me now, I look normal then.

03:32:40.080 --> 03:32:48.560
[Guest]: So we had an acquaintance who was famously, you know, used to tell like, you go to a sabji

03:32:48.560 --> 03:32:54.840
[Guest]: guy and he'll call you uncle and you sort of look down on him through his glasses and say,

03:32:54.840 --> 03:33:03.440
[Guest]: hum aapse sabji lene aaye hain, rishta banane nahin aaye hain, aap humko uncle math boliyega.

03:33:03.440 --> 03:33:08.880
[Guest]: That would shut them up for some time.

03:33:08.880 --> 03:33:11.560
[Guest]: Seven.

03:33:11.560 --> 03:33:16.880
[Guest]: So I am usually the know-all, know-it-all, right.

03:33:16.880 --> 03:33:24.240
[Guest]: So Sheila resents that and she's like, whenever, and I'm one of those N2 cutlets who has to

03:33:24.240 --> 03:33:30.200
[Guest]: jump in and enlighten everybody, you know, so mansplainer on steroids.

03:33:30.200 --> 03:33:34.520
[Guest]: I'm trying to, personsplainer, but anyway.

03:33:34.520 --> 03:33:40.360
[Guest]: So I had that and oftentimes to make matters worse, my explanations are also inaccurate

03:33:40.360 --> 03:33:46.760
[Guest]: and downright wrong most of the time, but that's my nature, it used to be.

03:33:46.760 --> 03:33:49.480
[Guest]: And I got my comeuppance in Uganda.

03:33:49.480 --> 03:33:54.560
[Guest]: So one year we decided to go to Uganda as tourists.

03:33:54.560 --> 03:33:56.920
[Guest]: Why Uganda specifically is a long story.

03:33:56.920 --> 03:34:01.560
[Guest]: We wanted to go to Kenya, but somebody said Uganda, we landed up there.

03:34:01.560 --> 03:34:08.360
[Guest]: And so we went to a place called Para Lodge or something.

03:34:08.360 --> 03:34:13.880
[Guest]: It's a wildlife resort in the middle of nowhere and you can either fly in or you can take

03:34:13.880 --> 03:34:15.480
[Guest]: a car and go.

03:34:15.480 --> 03:34:17.080
[Guest]: So flying was too expensive.

03:34:17.080 --> 03:34:18.440
[Guest]: We hired a vehicle.

03:34:18.440 --> 03:34:25.740
[Guest]: We had a Ugandan driver named Ronald, very, you know, in Uganda everyone speaks English.

03:34:25.740 --> 03:34:31.640
[Guest]: So that's because they have Swahili, they have their local language and then English.

03:34:31.640 --> 03:34:37.000
[Guest]: So virtually everyone speaks English and reasonably decent English you can understand.

03:34:37.000 --> 03:34:39.040
[Guest]: And so was Ronald.

03:34:39.040 --> 03:34:43.960
[Guest]: But it was just very transactional, say good morning, sir, and would you like to stop for

03:34:43.960 --> 03:34:46.720
[Guest]: lunch or a long drive.

03:34:46.720 --> 03:34:48.760
[Guest]: And that's all that, all the interaction.

03:34:48.760 --> 03:34:56.680
[Guest]: So we go to Para Lodge and then we go to another place called Pabidi Chimpanzee Reserve or something.

03:34:56.680 --> 03:34:58.360
[Guest]: So it's a rainforest with chimpanzees.

03:34:58.360 --> 03:35:04.320
[Guest]: So we go in and it was very nice to see chimpanzees in their natural habitat and you have a guide

03:35:04.320 --> 03:35:10.520
[Guest]: and all of these people, they are very, you know, they're very knowledgeable about.

03:35:10.520 --> 03:35:16.000
[Guest]: So we had a guide who told us about, you know, behavior of chimpanzees and actually chimpanzees

03:35:16.000 --> 03:35:17.220
[Guest]: are pretty brutal animals.

03:35:17.220 --> 03:35:21.920
[Guest]: So they're not the cuddly, sweet things that we think they are.

03:35:21.920 --> 03:35:25.920
[Amit Varma]: I still remember the books of anthropologist Franz Zaval about this, where he talks about

03:35:25.920 --> 03:35:28.400
[Amit Varma]: the chimpanzee politics and all of that.

03:35:28.400 --> 03:35:33.000
[Guest]: And it's so much, actually baboon politics is even more interesting, but chimpanzees

03:35:33.000 --> 03:35:34.000
[Amit Varma]: also.

03:35:34.000 --> 03:35:36.600
[Amit Varma]: That whole fight over the alpha male, you know, the last time I read something like

03:35:36.600 --> 03:35:39.360
[Amit Varma]: that, I kept thinking of Modiji versus Adityanathji.

03:35:39.360 --> 03:35:45.760
[Guest]: You know, it's a lot of parallels among humans.

03:35:45.760 --> 03:35:53.360
[Guest]: So all that was happening, then we come back and there's a nice sort of, you know, reception

03:35:53.360 --> 03:35:56.360
[Guest]: area and Mashila wants to go to the loo.

03:35:56.360 --> 03:36:02.240
[Guest]: So she's gone and I'm just hanging around and there is a tree and the manager of that

03:36:02.240 --> 03:36:07.760
[Guest]: lodge was free, he was chatting me up, our driver Ronald was there too.

03:36:07.760 --> 03:36:12.640
[Guest]: And he was telling me about the place and famous people who had come there, very popular

03:36:12.640 --> 03:36:18.240
[Guest]: and apparently one of our Prime Ministers had come there, Indian Prime Minister, everything

03:36:18.240 --> 03:36:19.580
[Guest]: was there.

03:36:19.580 --> 03:36:26.800
[Guest]: Then I noticed this tree under which we are standing, it's pretty stark and in the middle,

03:36:26.800 --> 03:36:29.480
[Guest]: on one of the branches, there's a riot of colors.

03:36:29.480 --> 03:36:32.520
[Guest]: There's a plant with a lot of flowers on it.

03:36:32.520 --> 03:36:37.360
[Guest]: So I said that looks unusual, I mean, rest of the tree, there's just a few very sparse

03:36:37.360 --> 03:36:39.160
[Unknown]: pattern.

03:36:39.160 --> 03:36:45.120
[Guest]: So the manager says this is probably a parasitic plant, you know, so it's basically sitting

03:36:45.120 --> 03:36:51.720
[Guest]: on that and this happens in the forest and other plants, they draw the sustenance from

03:36:51.720 --> 03:36:54.800
[Guest]: the main tree and then they do their thing.

03:36:54.800 --> 03:37:01.200
[Guest]: And this is the first time Ronald pipes up and before this, Ronald has only asked me,

03:37:01.200 --> 03:37:04.560
[Guest]: do you want to stop for lunch, do you want to stop for a toilet break, those are the

03:37:04.560 --> 03:37:08.320
[Guest]: only things, sir, we should be getting on, it's going to be late.

03:37:08.320 --> 03:37:10.440
[Guest]: That's literally the only thing.

03:37:10.440 --> 03:37:18.080
[Guest]: He says, I don't think that is a parasitic plant, because if it were a parasitic plant,

03:37:18.080 --> 03:37:26.240
[Guest]: then the branch at the distal end would be better because this plant would be sucking

03:37:26.240 --> 03:37:28.120
[Guest]: out all the sap.

03:37:28.120 --> 03:37:34.680
[Guest]: I think it's an epiphyte and the manager says, yeah, you're right, you're right, it must

03:37:34.680 --> 03:37:37.440
[Guest]: be an epiphyte, it can't be a parasite.

03:37:37.440 --> 03:37:42.160
[Guest]: And by this time, Sheila had returned and she was in on the entire conversation and

03:37:42.160 --> 03:37:48.480
[Guest]: she was delighted to see me completely open mouthed, she knew I had no clue what an epiphyte

03:37:48.480 --> 03:37:52.000
[Unknown]: was.

03:37:52.000 --> 03:37:59.040
[Guest]: And her mansplainer, person-splainer husband was, for at least for a little while, stunned

03:37:59.040 --> 03:38:00.040
[Amit Varma]: into silence.

03:38:00.040 --> 03:38:02.000
[Amit Varma]: You were outshinoyed by Ronald.

03:38:02.000 --> 03:38:03.200
[Amit Varma]: But did you find out his background?

03:38:03.200 --> 03:38:04.800
[Guest]: Was he like a biology PhD or something?

03:38:04.800 --> 03:38:14.720
[Guest]: He told me that, not that, but before he worked as a driver, he was a botanist at one of these

03:38:14.720 --> 03:38:15.920
[Guest]: parks.

03:38:15.920 --> 03:38:18.800
[Guest]: So he knew a lot about it, he was a botanist, that's what he told me.

03:38:18.800 --> 03:38:24.960
[Guest]: I don't know what his qualifications were, but amazing, I mean, he was such a charming

03:38:24.960 --> 03:38:25.960
[Guest]: fellow.

03:38:25.960 --> 03:38:29.800
[Guest]: And then, unfortunately, that was the fag end of the trip and you know, we came back

03:38:29.800 --> 03:38:32.040
[Guest]: to Kampala and we had to fly back.

03:38:32.040 --> 03:38:35.000
[Guest]: I never got to know Ronald better.

03:38:35.000 --> 03:38:40.160
[Amit Varma]: And shout out to Ronald, if he's listening to this, please get in touch with him.

03:38:40.160 --> 03:38:49.320
[Guest]: Okay, story number eight, Bandra Pali Hill days.

03:38:49.320 --> 03:38:56.520
[Guest]: So this friend who I used to hang out with, we used to hang out in, you know, in Bandra

03:38:56.520 --> 03:39:00.800
[Guest]: and his house, a very nice, charming building they used to live in and nothing to do, we

03:39:00.800 --> 03:39:05.480
[Guest]: just wander around and maybe play some cricket, do nothing.

03:39:05.480 --> 03:39:14.120
[Guest]: And one day, we were just sitting there in his house and a neighboring auntie walks in,

03:39:14.120 --> 03:39:20.880
[Guest]: she has a three-year-old daughter, she says, would you baby spend time with the uncle here,

03:39:20.880 --> 03:39:22.520
[Guest]: I'm just coming or something like that.

03:39:22.520 --> 03:39:28.120
[Guest]: And with practiced ease, she palms off the girl to us and she runs away like a hare,

03:39:28.120 --> 03:39:33.280
[Guest]: because she wants some time to herself, she wants to go shop or something like that.

03:39:33.280 --> 03:39:39.720
[Guest]: And this girl is one clingy mama, and absolutely on cue, moment the door shuts, she starts

03:39:39.720 --> 03:39:41.360
[Guest]: crying mama.

03:39:41.360 --> 03:39:47.480
[Guest]: And we don't know, we have zero experience in looking after little kids babysitting.

03:39:47.480 --> 03:39:48.920
[Guest]: So we don't know what to do.

03:39:48.920 --> 03:39:50.800
[Guest]: And we are trying to stress her.

03:39:50.800 --> 03:39:57.000
[Guest]: Just then, one older, another neighbor, he just walks in, he hears all the din must be

03:39:57.000 --> 03:39:58.280
[Guest]: happening, he says, what's happening?

03:39:58.280 --> 03:40:03.200
[Guest]: So we tell him, yaar yeh aisa ho gaya, aa girl, no problem, I'll handle.

03:40:03.200 --> 03:40:06.520
[Guest]: So he comes in, he says, do you have an album?

03:40:06.520 --> 03:40:09.920
[Guest]: So the guy says, yaa hoga kuch toh, bring any album.

03:40:09.920 --> 03:40:17.000
[Guest]: So he brings some album, travel album, and so he starts showing it to the girl and says,

03:40:17.000 --> 03:40:22.280
[Guest]: see, this is this bhaiya, this is this didi, and this is this chacha.

03:40:22.280 --> 03:40:27.600
[Guest]: And then eventually, as children, and this is a tip to all listeners, so if you ever

03:40:27.600 --> 03:40:30.520
[Guest]: want to show a small child, show them photographs.

03:40:30.520 --> 03:40:35.400
[Guest]: They will just stop and they'll just, you know.

03:40:35.400 --> 03:40:41.960
[Guest]: So she shuts up, and he's showing all this thing, and says, see, all these people are

03:40:41.960 --> 03:40:46.600
[Guest]: there, this bhaiya is there, that chacha is there, but where is your mummy?

03:40:46.600 --> 03:40:47.600
[Guest]: Mummy!

03:40:47.600 --> 03:40:49.260
[Guest]: She starts crying again.

03:40:49.260 --> 03:40:53.080
[Guest]: So after she starts crying, he starts the whole thing again.

03:40:53.080 --> 03:40:57.960
[Guest]: And the child sort of forgets, you know, she stops crying, eventually, and the moment she

03:40:57.960 --> 03:41:03.000
[Guest]: stops crying, he says the same thing, see, all these bhaiya is there, didi is there,

03:41:03.000 --> 03:41:04.000
[Guest]: but where's mummy?

03:41:04.000 --> 03:41:11.200
[Guest]: It was the most hilarious, for two hours, actually, I think, I don't think it will pass

03:41:11.200 --> 03:41:12.200
[Guest]: muster now.

03:41:12.200 --> 03:41:13.880
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you'll just get.

03:41:13.880 --> 03:41:18.720
[Amit Varma]: You'll get the little girl addicted to Instagram, and then it's all over, dude.

03:41:18.720 --> 03:41:19.720
[Guest]: Yeah.

03:41:19.720 --> 03:41:20.720
[Guest]: Nowadays, it's a lot easier.

03:41:20.720 --> 03:41:22.640
[Guest]: You just give them a phone and they shut up.

03:41:22.640 --> 03:41:24.360
[Guest]: Back in the day, you could do that.

03:41:24.360 --> 03:41:35.760
[Guest]: This guy was such a commensurate troll that he would, you know, he'd just make her cry,

03:41:35.760 --> 03:41:36.760
[Amit Varma]: make her shut up.

03:41:36.760 --> 03:41:39.040
[Amit Varma]: I think we might both be having a senior moment.

03:41:39.040 --> 03:41:41.800
[Amit Varma]: Let me find the definition of commensurate.

03:41:41.800 --> 03:41:46.000
[Amit Varma]: Commensurate is, I think, you know, when you pay someone a salary that is adequate for

03:41:46.000 --> 03:41:50.840
[Amit Varma]: them, they say this is commensurate to his skills, which is exactly what it means.

03:41:50.840 --> 03:41:53.240
[Amit Varma]: So what is the word we are both hunting for?

03:41:53.240 --> 03:41:56.800
[Guest]: Maybe if listeners can figure it out, masterful.

03:41:56.800 --> 03:42:04.600
[Amit Varma]: But we start with consummate, consummate, consummate, consummate, wow, redeems ourselves

03:42:04.600 --> 03:42:05.600
[Guest]: in time.

03:42:05.600 --> 03:42:06.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

03:42:06.600 --> 03:42:07.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

03:42:07.600 --> 03:42:17.080
[Amit Varma]: I don't want to get into this and saying that where is the explainer, you know, okay, story

03:42:17.080 --> 03:42:18.080
[Guest]: number nine.

03:42:18.080 --> 03:42:22.480
[Guest]: Okay, this is a pet peeve of mine.

03:42:22.480 --> 03:42:29.240
[Guest]: This obsession for English Premier League football team among the younger generation.

03:42:29.240 --> 03:42:34.720
[Guest]: So big victim is my big patient, I should say, is my son.

03:42:34.720 --> 03:42:38.760
[Guest]: My younger son, he's very fond, he used to be fond of Chelsea.

03:42:38.760 --> 03:42:44.920
[Guest]: And then somewhere down the line, he changed his allegiance to Tottenham Hotspurs.

03:42:44.920 --> 03:42:49.080
[Guest]: And they really spent a lot of time and energy.

03:42:49.080 --> 03:42:52.000
[Guest]: So they watch every match.

03:42:52.000 --> 03:42:58.640
[Guest]: And what I don't get, you know, there's this thing in Hindi, there's a saying called

03:42:58.640 --> 03:43:08.320
[Guest]: Begane Shadi Mein Abdullah Deewana, it's like, you know, but they do that and they get very,

03:43:08.320 --> 03:43:13.200
[Guest]: so I keep trolling them, you know, he and his friends will come to watch a match and

03:43:13.200 --> 03:43:17.440
[Guest]: I start off, now they don't react, they know I'm just trolling them.

03:43:17.440 --> 03:43:24.320
[Guest]: But it was my pet peeve, why are you celebrating, none of you have been to Tottenham, you have

03:43:24.320 --> 03:43:29.240
[Guest]: no, what is your connect, and they're like, you'll never understand and you'll never walk

03:43:29.240 --> 03:43:30.240
[Amit Varma]: alone.

03:43:30.240 --> 03:43:31.240
[Guest]: That's a Liverpool thing.

03:43:31.240 --> 03:43:39.480
[Guest]: So my thing was, I had if what, what if, let us say you have Tottenham Hotspurs, and there's

03:43:39.480 --> 03:43:45.080
[Guest]: another team, maybe Liverpool, and you hate Liverpool and you love Tottenham.

03:43:45.080 --> 03:43:50.680
[Guest]: And what if one of your favorite Tottenham players, like Harry Kane leaves and joins

03:43:50.680 --> 03:43:51.680
[Guest]: Liverpool?

03:43:51.680 --> 03:43:58.920
[Guest]: Do you still continue to love, you know, and be devoted to Tottenham?

03:43:58.920 --> 03:44:00.280
[Guest]: And obviously the answer was yes.

03:44:00.280 --> 03:44:06.760
[Guest]: So I said what happens if all each one by one, all your Tottenham players go and leave

03:44:06.760 --> 03:44:12.400
[Guest]: Liverpool and coincidentally, Tottenham starts picking up players from Liverpool.

03:44:12.400 --> 03:44:18.760
[Guest]: So after the transfer season is over, all your Tottenham players are now in Liverpool.

03:44:18.760 --> 03:44:19.760
[Guest]: Now what do you do?

03:44:19.760 --> 03:44:25.720
[Guest]: And yeah, so there, you know, it's, it's like a thought experiment, but they never get into

03:44:25.720 --> 03:44:26.720
[Guest]: that.

03:44:26.720 --> 03:44:30.200
[Guest]: So they say that it's not possible, because apparently the transfer window there you can

03:44:30.200 --> 03:44:33.280
[Guest]: only transfer three players or four.

03:44:33.280 --> 03:44:39.400
[Guest]: But no one saw any any listener out there who wants to engage with the best reply I

03:44:39.400 --> 03:44:46.160
[Guest]: got for this was from from one guy named Abhishek Upadhyay, who goes under the name logic on

03:44:46.160 --> 03:44:47.160
[Guest]: Twitter.

03:44:47.160 --> 03:44:52.040
[Guest]: And he says your allegiance is based on which jersey you bought from national market.

03:44:52.040 --> 03:44:57.440
[Guest]: So yeah, if you have a Tottenham jersey, then it is Tottenham.

03:44:57.440 --> 03:44:59.600
[Amit Varma]: You know, I find these tribal allegiances very weird.

03:44:59.600 --> 03:45:04.240
[Amit Varma]: And you could extrapolate this and say that, why is it only weird that somebody sitting

03:45:04.240 --> 03:45:08.840
[Amit Varma]: in Mumbai, who's never been outside Malad even perhaps support Tottenham, but it is

03:45:08.840 --> 03:45:10.600
[Amit Varma]: equally weird to support India.

03:45:10.600 --> 03:45:15.720
[Amit Varma]: I mean, all these are like abstract concepts, you can have a concrete loyalty to your family

03:45:15.720 --> 03:45:20.320
[Amit Varma]: and people you have met, but anything beyond that is absolutely abstract, you're buying

03:45:20.320 --> 03:45:23.080
[Guest]: into some kind of narrative scene there.

03:45:23.080 --> 03:45:31.200
[Guest]: And the thing is, the tribalism is so strong that I've invariably found the that I piss

03:45:31.200 --> 03:45:37.360
[Guest]: people off and I like when you threaten their tribal affiliations, they get threatened.

03:45:37.360 --> 03:45:41.400
[Guest]: So there's some deep lesson to be learned from this about human behavior.

03:45:41.400 --> 03:45:44.400
[Guest]: So I probably already learned I don't know.

03:45:44.400 --> 03:45:47.760
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, my allegiance when I follow football pretty closely, and my allegiance

03:45:47.760 --> 03:45:51.920
[Amit Varma]: is more towards coaches, because I like the particular styles and the way a team plays.

03:45:51.920 --> 03:45:55.680
[Amit Varma]: I was arguing with a friend of mine who's a big Barcelona fan about, you know, who fell

03:45:55.680 --> 03:46:01.280
[Amit Varma]: in love with Barcelona in those years when, you know, 2010, 2011, when Guardiola was in

03:46:01.280 --> 03:46:04.600
[Amit Varma]: charge and Messi was at his best.

03:46:04.600 --> 03:46:08.760
[Amit Varma]: And the point is that that spirit, if you look at it has been transplanted elsewhere.

03:46:08.760 --> 03:46:11.000
[Amit Varma]: And it is perhaps today in Man City.

03:46:11.000 --> 03:46:17.480
[Guest]: You know, so to actually I got this so over a period of time after after trolling these

03:46:17.480 --> 03:46:20.800
[Guest]: young boys was, you know, the diminishing law of return.

03:46:20.800 --> 03:46:23.360
[Guest]: So every time you troll them, initially, it was great fun.

03:46:23.360 --> 03:46:26.560
[Guest]: After that, it's so I stopped only and then I started listening.

03:46:26.560 --> 03:46:33.400
[Guest]: And then he started explaining the tactical and strategic aspects of and it's pretty intense.

03:46:33.400 --> 03:46:38.120
[Guest]: I mean, so he would illustrate like, you know, you'd almost be able to predict what is going

03:46:38.120 --> 03:46:42.480
[Guest]: to happen if this guy is heading out in the center, then these two guys will start coming

03:46:42.480 --> 03:46:46.600
[Guest]: out in the wings and they are looking for a rebound and counter attack and so on and

03:46:46.600 --> 03:46:47.600
[Guest]: so forth.

03:46:47.600 --> 03:46:51.800
[Guest]: And then it's pretty clear that it's a big mind game.

03:46:51.800 --> 03:46:58.920
[Guest]: And the players are really the managers, not the players, not just the players themselves.

03:46:58.920 --> 03:47:02.440
[Amit Varma]: The continued loyalty towards the club is still irrational, because I'm guessing that

03:47:02.440 --> 03:47:05.880
[Amit Varma]: your son must have fallen in love with Tottenham during the five and a half years when Mauricio

03:47:05.880 --> 03:47:07.680
[Amit Varma]: Pochettino was a coach.

03:47:07.680 --> 03:47:11.800
[Amit Varma]: And he was brilliant and they played a really attractive style of football, pressing all

03:47:11.800 --> 03:47:14.280
[Amit Varma]: the time, possession, aggressive, all of that.

03:47:14.280 --> 03:47:19.520
[Amit Varma]: But ever since he got sacked, you know, they've had Mourinho and then Nuno just got sacked

03:47:19.520 --> 03:47:25.080
[Guest]: and you know, the latest is Conte might be joining, who's also a defense plus counter

03:47:25.080 --> 03:47:29.040
[Amit Varma]: attack kind of coach, though far better than similar coaches of that type.

03:47:29.040 --> 03:47:33.360
[Amit Varma]: So it's like they're a completely different club if you look at the way they play.

03:47:33.360 --> 03:47:35.400
[Guest]: So I wonder what your son feels about that.

03:47:35.400 --> 03:47:43.360
[Guest]: It's good, it'll be a good discussion to have with them.

03:47:43.360 --> 03:47:45.200
[Guest]: So story number 10.

03:47:45.200 --> 03:47:52.080
[Guest]: So once Sheela and I, this way back when the boys were very, very young, we and Google

03:47:52.080 --> 03:47:55.040
[Guest]: was not around, Google Maps definitely wasn't around.

03:47:55.040 --> 03:47:57.600
[Guest]: So it's really way back.

03:47:57.600 --> 03:48:05.920
[Guest]: We had to go to Pune, and to a place called Kalyaninagar, and that was because someone,

03:48:05.920 --> 03:48:11.480
[Guest]: a relative on Sheela's side lived there and they've been inviting us for a long time and

03:48:11.480 --> 03:48:13.240
[Guest]: I did want to go.

03:48:13.240 --> 03:48:25.160
[Guest]: And so I took, I mean, we drove down, Sheela, the kids and I, and I, we had a map and we

03:48:25.160 --> 03:48:26.160
[Guest]: got lost.

03:48:26.160 --> 03:48:33.760
[Guest]: So there was no, we just lined up in Pune and Pune even back in the day was a pretty

03:48:33.760 --> 03:48:36.800
[Guest]: scary place to drive in.

03:48:36.800 --> 03:48:41.200
[Guest]: People have absolutely like random Brownian motion, I'm pretty sure that random Brownian

03:48:41.200 --> 03:48:46.680
[Guest]: motion was first discovered in Pune, that the guy who discovered it, got the idea from

03:48:46.680 --> 03:48:51.000
[Guest]: the traffic and then he goes and looks and says, Oh, this is Brownian motion.

03:48:51.000 --> 03:48:58.800
[Guest]: So we got lost and one thing that I hate in life is asking for directions.

03:48:58.800 --> 03:49:05.200
[Guest]: So I would rather navigate by the stars and then ask someone, but Sheela's not allowed.

03:49:05.200 --> 03:49:10.320
[Guest]: She'll stop here, she'll ask this panwala, then 100 meters away, she'll ask another cyclist

03:49:10.320 --> 03:49:11.400
[Guest]: and so on.

03:49:11.400 --> 03:49:15.760
[Guest]: But Pune being Pune, back in the day, there were no panwalas, no cyclists, nothing.

03:49:15.760 --> 03:49:21.240
[Guest]: We just go around and then we find one elderly, distinguished looking elderly gentleman standing

03:49:21.240 --> 03:49:23.600
[Guest]: on the road, doing pretty much nothing.

03:49:23.600 --> 03:49:28.640
[Guest]: So I pull over and then we ask this gentleman, so he says, where do you want to go?

03:49:28.640 --> 03:49:35.240
[Guest]: So I said, Kalyani Nagar, so he says, Kalyani Nagar, is that the one on Nagar Road, that's

03:49:35.240 --> 03:49:41.440
[Guest]: the one, because that says Nagar, is that the one near the Poonawala stud farm?

03:49:41.440 --> 03:49:45.720
[Guest]: I said, yes, I'm getting happier, he seems to know the place.

03:49:45.720 --> 03:49:47.720
[Guest]: And it's somewhere near Viman Nagar, right?

03:49:47.720 --> 03:49:49.600
[Guest]: Yeah, it's near Viman Nagar.

03:49:49.600 --> 03:49:51.440
[Guest]: So I asked him, do you know how to go there?

03:49:51.440 --> 03:49:52.440
[Guest]: He said, no.

03:49:52.440 --> 03:49:53.440
[Guest]: That's it.

03:49:53.440 --> 03:49:54.440
[Guest]: And he walked away.

03:49:54.440 --> 03:49:55.440
[Guest]: That was the end of the conversation.

03:49:55.440 --> 03:49:56.440
[Guest]: I don't know.

03:49:56.440 --> 03:50:03.880
[Amit Varma]: This guy is more like Shenoy than Ronald.

03:50:03.880 --> 03:50:05.920
[Amit Varma]: I have a Kalyani Nagar story.

03:50:05.920 --> 03:50:10.480
[Amit Varma]: It's actually where I saw a naked woman in the flesh for the first time in my life.

03:50:10.480 --> 03:50:11.600
[Amit Varma]: But it isn't what you think it is.

03:50:11.600 --> 03:50:18.040
[Amit Varma]: So I was probably in the 9th standard, 8th or 9th standard, 9th standard probably.

03:50:18.040 --> 03:50:22.120
[Amit Varma]: And I had gone to visit this friend of mine who lived there, who I haven't been in touch

03:50:22.120 --> 03:50:25.640
[Amit Varma]: with since, but he's actually a very prominent economist right now.

03:50:25.640 --> 03:50:30.200
[Amit Varma]: So I won't name him because very serious guy, as he was, he was a serious kid.

03:50:30.200 --> 03:50:35.440
[Amit Varma]: So anyway, so we were in his bedroom chilling out and there was a third friend over there.

03:50:35.440 --> 03:50:40.680
[Amit Varma]: And opposite his room, you know, the two balconies facing each other, opposite his room, some

03:50:40.680 --> 03:50:43.280
[Amit Varma]: foreign a couple used to live.

03:50:43.280 --> 03:50:46.980
[Amit Varma]: And he happened to mention that the lady used to walk around naked.

03:50:46.980 --> 03:50:50.800
[Amit Varma]: So at one point in time, you know, both me and this other friend, I'm trying hard not

03:50:50.800 --> 03:50:53.020
[Amit Varma]: to take their names because they're just coming.

03:50:53.020 --> 03:50:56.840
[Amit Varma]: Me and this other friend, we just opened the curtain a little bit and we see that she's

03:50:56.840 --> 03:50:59.000
[Amit Varma]: stark naked and she's walking around in the room.

03:50:59.000 --> 03:51:00.280
[Amit Varma]: She's doing something.

03:51:00.280 --> 03:51:03.520
[Amit Varma]: And then she comes out on the balcony and she's standing there.

03:51:03.520 --> 03:51:07.360
[Amit Varma]: So both of us, 9th standard kids, right, this is back in the day, you don't even have free

03:51:07.360 --> 03:51:09.640
[Amit Varma]: access to porn and all of that.

03:51:09.640 --> 03:51:12.400
[Amit Varma]: Both of us went mad and we jumped up.

03:51:12.400 --> 03:51:15.600
[Amit Varma]: And this economist friend whose room it was, was very chill.

03:51:15.600 --> 03:51:17.440
[Amit Varma]: He said, I can see what you're doing.

03:51:17.440 --> 03:51:18.440
[Amit Varma]: Don't do it.

03:51:18.440 --> 03:51:19.440
[Amit Varma]: But we just went nuts.

03:51:19.440 --> 03:51:24.160
[Amit Varma]: We opened the balcony door and we also go out in the balcony and right opposite her,

03:51:24.160 --> 03:51:26.240
[Amit Varma]: which was the stupidest thing to do.

03:51:26.240 --> 03:51:30.880
[Amit Varma]: And she just looks at us, looks away, turns this way, turns that way and then casually

03:51:30.880 --> 03:51:34.200
[Amit Varma]: walks inside and shuts the door and that was the end of the show.

03:51:34.200 --> 03:51:38.880
[Amit Varma]: So an early kind of lesson there, I suppose.

03:51:38.880 --> 03:51:45.760
[Guest]: There is some like economic lessons also, right, when you have some insights and you

03:51:45.760 --> 03:51:50.800
[Guest]: want to do something in the market, you have to do it as they say in Bombay, Sumdi mein.

03:51:50.800 --> 03:51:57.840
[Guest]: So Sumdi is, I love that, I have no idea what the etymology of that word is, but Sumdi apparently

03:51:57.840 --> 03:51:58.840
[Guest]: means slyly.

03:51:58.840 --> 03:52:02.200
[Guest]: So you have to do it very slyly without anyone knowing what's happening.

03:52:02.200 --> 03:52:10.360
[Amit Varma]: Many deeper questions, yeh train Mulund kyu jati hai?

03:52:10.360 --> 03:52:12.120
[Guest]: Story 11.

03:52:12.120 --> 03:52:17.720
[Guest]: So I grew up listening to a lot of classical, Hindustani classical music, and I grew very

03:52:17.720 --> 03:52:22.480
[Guest]: fond of it to the point that I'm unable to listen to any other kind of music.

03:52:22.480 --> 03:52:29.360
[Guest]: I just listen to Hindustani classical and as fate would have it, both my children, at

03:52:29.360 --> 03:52:40.840
[Guest]: least my oldest son hated it, like when he was a toddler, if I put on a Hindustani tape,

03:52:40.840 --> 03:52:47.720
[Guest]: he would start crying loudly or when he learned how to walk, he would just go and start hitting

03:52:47.720 --> 03:52:48.900
[Guest]: the nearest person.

03:52:48.900 --> 03:52:53.560
[Guest]: So if it was mom, he would start hitting mom, if it was me, just stop, just stop, you just

03:52:53.560 --> 03:52:54.560
[Guest]: come and hit.

03:52:54.560 --> 03:52:57.840
[Guest]: So like over a period of time, it just stopped.

03:52:57.840 --> 03:53:05.160
[Guest]: And then they grew up and then it was no longer such a big issue and I discovered the internet

03:53:05.160 --> 03:53:10.360
[Guest]: and you had all these things and you could get free mp3s and one of my favorite singers

03:53:10.360 --> 03:53:17.080
